reviewText: SPOILER FREE (mostly)Cabin in the Woods is a movie who's success depends largely on how much you pretend the core joke is funny.  For me, It was funny as in smirk funny, but not really LOL funny.  For some people, this will be a riot.  For others, a stale shaggy dog story.  I'm a little in the middle.On the surface this is In the Mouth of Madness meets Army of Darkness.  I don't think it's as threatening a premise as the former or as charming as the latter, but it does burn 90 minutes with some occasionally creative touches.  Maybe this is more Evil Dead meets Buffy.  Is it SAW meets Blade? Or is it Event Horizon meets Big Brother?  All of the above.  That's the whole point.  The "monster's ball" of mayhem sequence is probably the most riotous fun of Cabin in the Woods, but the rest of the movie doesn't quite hold up.  The ending especially is pretty flat.  The rest of the film builds so much to it and it feels like Goddard and Whedon forgot that in referencing so much other mateiral, they really need to write something good of their own. The whole thing feels as disposable as a Big Mac container. There was a better last 2 or 3 minutes instead of what/who they threw up there before the credits roll.  Or they ran out of money, which is a possibility.You could do worse, but I've already heard this joke a few times and it was better told and more entertaining when Kevin Williamson called it Scream.
summary: Stop Me If You've Heard This One Before...

reviewText: As a horror movie fan, I see a few good movies and some stinkers (actually a LOT) and my main complaint is that once moviemakers find a formula, they beat, stab and chop it til it's boring.  Joss Whedon pulls together an excellent cast, including some some Buffy The Vampire Slayer alumni, plus Chris Hemsworth (SWEET), and takes the horror movie formula and simultaneously wallops it, turns it upside down while loving it and laughing at it--all the while delivering tension and a GOOD SCARE.  The beginning is just like every other horror flick from Friday the 13th to Saw---until.....This film is unique in the horror genre in that it delivers tension, makes you care about the characters whether you love 'em or hate 'em, and is unapologetic regarding its romance with the horror movie formula.  There's a surprise guest here, too. There's jumpy stuff, and above all, the tension as you wonder how the protagonists are going to possibly escape this situation.  The answer will surprise you, as this film surprised me.
summary: Scary, funny frolic in the woods with Whedon

reviewText: Joss Whedon (Buffy the Vampire Slayer: The Complete Series,Angel: Complete Series,Firefly - The Complete Series,Dollhouse: The Complete Seasons 1 & 2,Marvel's The Avengers) is a true master of his craft. And even though I knew Drew Goddard had prior writing experience with TV greats (and some of my favorites such as "Buffy," "Angel,"Alias - The Complete Collection (Seasons 1-5 + Rambaldi artifact box), andLost: The Complete Collection), I still was not sure what to think of him as a director and co-writer of a major film (even though he wrote the impressiveCloverfield). After viewing this masterpiece, I can say he does extremely well! This film's release had been delayed a bit (originally set for Feb. 2010, then Jan. 2011), but it was very much worth the wait! I can truly say that "The Cabin in the Woods" is a fresh, innovative, fun, scary take on the horror film. It was also nice -- almost comforting, like a warm blanket -- to see former Whedonverse actors like Amy Acker ("Angel," "Dollhouse"), Fran Kranz ("Dollhouse"), and Tom Lenk ("Buffy") in the fold. Nobody can mix action, horror, suspense, and humor like Whedon, and this film proves it. All of the actors performances are spot-on and even though their characters are all stereotypical cliches, that ultimately serves the film's plot for reasons I cannot say without spoiling anything. My favorite moment in the film is near the end -- again, I don't want to say too much -- and it is every horror movie fan's DREAM. But, more on that later. There are many aspects to Whedon and Goddard's "Cabin" than most would think. The best thing about this movie is that in a genre (horror) that is second to predictability (following romantic comedies), "The Cabin in the Woods" delivers a fresh approach to horror; and the result is one fun, impressive movie that you want to see again and again. Now comes the part of the review where if you have not seen the film and want to see it, you cannot - and should not - read anymore.SPOILERS BEGINThe best thing about this film was its double meaning. First, one could argue that the "evil gods" that "the company" is attempting to appease are us, the audience. After all, who goes to see horror films despite the cliché of stereotypical characters (the jock, the slut, the intellectual, the fool, the virgin) tossed into the meat grinder? Who expects or hopes to see a little nudity and/or sex in a horror film, along with massive blood and gore? That would be the audience. It made me wonder if the two company workers (Richard Jenkins & Bradley Whitford) were working for us rather than some director. Second, the film makes the statement that we have to face up to all of the decisions we make in life. When the five decide to continue to their cabin despite the creepy old man's warning, and when Dana (Kristen Connolly) continues to read the Latin despite Marty's protests (as well as the protests of the audience), they have to face the harsh consequences.Another aspect to the plot could be the argument of utilitarianism. For those who don't know the term, utilitarianism is "a theory that the aim of action should be the largest possible balance of pleasure over pain or the greatest happiness of the greatest number" (Merriam-Webster), or, basically, in this case, the philosophy that the saving of billions of lives are worth the sacrifice or one or even five. Whedon and Goddard make it known in their film that utilitarianism is wrong. With the outcome of the film being what it is, they appear to make the remark that one life does not hold any less weight than 6-7 billion lives. However, there is one misnomer with this statement. To loosely reference the stoner fool Marty's words, what if the world - and its inhabitants - have become too advanced and too corrupt for its own damn good? It's a good question and a good statement to throw out there in a horror movie. But don't think this is some existential borefest. Like I previously stated, Whedon (along with Goddard) is a master of his craft and he knows exactly how to properly balance the horror with the laughs, the philosophical metaphor with the fun, and all without any pretentiousness.Now, onto my one small, teensy-weensy, itty-bitty criticism of the film and that is not showing the hawk getting zapped by the invisible electro-wall ... especially in the movie trailer. It leaves no "wow" factor for the audience when it inevitably comes up again later in the film. It's the only change I would have made to this movie. As for my absolute favorite part, as I mentioned earlier, it is when Dana opens all of the doors to release many, many horrible things upon the company. After that distinct sound of multiple synchronous "ding"s from the elevator doors, I immediately thought to myself for a millisecond, "Wow. Whedon has outdone himself. This is gonna be great!" And then with the security guard whispering an expletive, the doors open and all hell breaks loose! Like I said, it's a moment that all horror fans and aficionados will love!SPOILERS ENDThis is definitely the best horror film I've seen in a LONG time! The film makes fun of the horror genre while also delivering to the audience what they so love about horror films. In the school of horror/slasher/zombie/suspense/headgame/conspiracy films, and the fans/students who so adore them, "The Cabin in the Woods" is a mandatory course!
summary: Horror, suspense, humor, action? Yes, please!

reviewText: Joss Whedon's sarky, tongue-in-cheek, "post Modern", "meta-horror" is the latest cut-n-paste effort that has Whedonites wetting themselves in the usual frenzied way. Not only that, but it's received generally favorable reviews from other areas too and currently holds around 90% positive on Rotten Tomatoes.I have to say, I find the former tiresome and no less obvious from the Whedonites, but the fact that other critics are writing glowing words about it, makes the latter part nothing short of astonishing. Astonishing, because 'Cabin in the Woods' is nowhere near as smart as Whedon, or his irritating acolytes, thinks it is.Although it's directed by Whedon protege, Drew Goddard, Whedon himself has taken his cue from 'Scream' and simply nicked an existing idea, tinkered with it, claimed it as his own, packaged it for his usual audience and marketed it as a revelation in film. A comedy-horror (my most hated genre after the rom-com) that'll have horror fans quivering in their boots and change the face of the genre for years to come.Unfortunately though, the film fails on both fronts. It isn't that funny and the horror elements are diluted badly by the attempts at comedy. Each angle is neutered by the other. But the worst thing about 'Cabin in the Woods' is that it's all been done before. The film's central reference, in a film whose raison d'etre is to function as a reference game for genre fans, is Sam Raimi's 'The Evil Dead' and that film did everything better and with better comedy (even though I personally think it's vastly overrated too).The problem with Whedon's approach (to nearly everything he does), is that the nudge-nudge-wink-wink "did you see what I did there?" attitude that he infuses into the picture, becomes tiresome very quickly. The endless references to films, that in the main are vastly superior, just gets old. Everything from 'Friday the 13th', to 'Hellraiser', to 'IT', 'The Strangers', 'The Shining', 'Night of the Living Dead' and a whole host of others are mentioned in brief passing. Many of which will go flying over many peoples heads, I'm sure. The viewer needs to be a fan of horror films in order to get 'Cabin in the Woods', without which the film may come across as yet another silly slasher flick.It's not all completely bad though. In the film's final third, everything goes haywire and there's some fun to be had trying to spot the different monsters that mangle the screen (and the people), but it's too little, too late and by the time the film is over, it's long since outstayed its welcome.
summary: Tumble down shack posing as premium priced property

reviewText: The title of my review says it all. The less you know about Cabin in the Woods going into it, the more surprised you're going to be. Simply put, if you're a fan of horror movies, ignore reading up on anything about it, and take a risk by going into it with no expectations. That's how I watched the movie, and I can tell you with 100% honesty that Cabin in the Woods is one of the best movies I've watched in the last couple of years. I can see why it was so hard to market, and why it sat on the shelf for as long as it did (check out how Chris Hemsworth looks here, not long before he starred in Thor). This section of my review right here is going to get the main things out of the way, with the next paragraph being my usual format with the plot summary. But please, just stop reading and watch it! The only reason I'm giving it 4 out of 5 stars instead of 5, since I did just say it's one of the best movies I've seen in a while, is because despite all the new things the film does, it takes a standard way out towards the end and starts to become just another horror movie. As weird as it sounds to praise something that goes this way, it still works, and I was only let down that they didn't keep the original pace up all the way through. That and some not-even-good-for-the-year-it-came-out CG are the two things holding it back. Even then, I enjoyed watching Cabin in the Woods and didn't want it to end, and I even wanted a couple of sequels given the variety of ways things could have gone.Alright, if you HAVE to know about the plot (man, I warned you)...Cabin in the Woods starts out with two men in a big business who are part of something big. They set up scenarios all over the world that are essentially what you see in horror movies. In Japan, a school for girls is haunted by a ghost in the class room, and they have cameras set up to show the whole thing. It turns out that these guys are part of something even bigger, and these situations are going on for a reason, though we don't find out what it is until much later. One of their main "shows" involves 5 college kids who go off to a cabin in the woods for a weekend in order to kick back and get off the grid, so to speak. You have the virgin, the jock, the...*ahem* cheerleader-type, the geek and the stoner. The funny thing is, all of these guys are friends and get along perfectly, not showing any signs of those labels until they get to the cabin. The jock dude isn't even a "bro" type- he's a great student! When they make it to the cabin, the guys back at the corporation get the gears going. They control a lot of elements about the scenario, but it's still up to the kids to decide on what to do. Different types of gases are used to change how their decision-making, voices will echo with advice on what to do next, and a trap door to the cellar opens up unexpectedly when the kids are all just kicking back in the living room. Of course they go down to inspect, and find a treasure trove of oddities. A puzzle sphere of sorts, a music box, an old diary, masks, a conch shell...the list goes on. Each of the kids is about to do something with what they pick up, but it's a special phrase in the diary that gets read out loud and activates which terror comes to the cabin- an undead family.As soon as the undead family is announced, and one of the two main guys in the company expresses his disappointment because he really wanted to see a mermaid kill the kids, that should tell you about the tone of the movie. Think of how From Dusk Till Dawn was two movies in one- the first half being crime and the second half being horror. Well, here it's horror mixed with comedy, with most of the comedy coming from the guys pulling off what's essentially their own horror movie. I loved it when the film would switch over to the workers in their lab, taking bets on what was going to happen next. When we see the list of all the monsters that could have been let loose, it brings to mind a whole bunch of ideas on what could have happened. Cabin in the Woods could almost be a kind of Choose Your Own Adventure movie, with even more potential for sequels if they showed the footage from other places int the world like that Japanese classroom. When the kids start to get killed off, it's kind of sad for once, because these aren't just plain dumb kids. We can see that for the most part, there's no way out of this trap, and they're helpless. And yet we cut over to the guys partying about how they're winning the bets, and it's easy to forget about the victims because this cast here is so damn likable!Honestly, I don't want to say much more about the movie. Horror films don't do a whole lot for me for various reasons (mainly because I saw two huge ones as a kid and nothing since then has scared me even in the slightest). Cabin in the Woods isn't scary at all, but instead just a very interesting film to watch play out. Very rarely do I go back and watch movies after I've seen them the first time. This is one of the exceptions where I'd gladly sit down with people who haven't seen it before and watch it again with them.
summary: Don't read any reviews- just watch the movie.

reviewText: Cabin in the Woods is a very unique type of film and is definitely not for everybody! I love horror, comedy, satire - in fact, I find something to love in just about any genre of movies. I initially watched Cabin in the Woods not knowing anything about it (which is honestly the best way to watch it IMO) and it kept knocking me on my butt. I expected a typical horror film and it was everything but typical. It kept me guessing, it made me laugh constantly, and it gave me several "WTF!?!" moments. I loved the constant homage to the horror genre and, honestly, this is now one of my favorite movies. I can see why some people don't like it but, for me, this was perfection. I recommend this to everyone I know that doesn't mind a film that has blood and guts but still doesn't take itself too seriously. If this is you, give it a chance.

reviewText: I'm one of those people who sneers at the dozens of predictable and bland slasher movies whose titles all sound very similar to "The Cabin in the Woods", so it was with great pleasure that I experienced this fun movie-- which so deftly spoofs and twists the formulaic genre. You have all the trappings of the classic scary flick here as the movie unfolds: stereotypical college kids, creepy and surly gas station hick, and so on. But at the same time, something nefarious is going on elsewhere, a sinister scenario that we become privy to.It couldn't be easy to write a script that is both an homage to horror cinema and also a biting satire of it ... but this was a success.Stealing the show (with the best lines of dialogue in the film) was Fran Kranz as the stoner dude Marty. He's the character you want to survive this weekend of mayhem and gore.I could gush on and on about this smart movie (a movie which, beneath its surface, speaks volumes about the state of spooky movies, and its audience), but I will simply recommend it; the final act alone (one of the most busy and wild sequences I've seen in a long time) is worth the ticket. I'm still smiling about it, days after watching the movie.

reviewText: This is the most inventive horror comedy in recent memory.  If you are a fan of the Evil Dead movies and Drag Me To Hell then check out this movie.  It is very "Sam Raimi"-esque and it delivers intense gore and alot of laughs. Certain scenes even seem like direct nods to Evil Dead (just look at the cabin itself, the placement of the trap door, the look of the stairs, EVIL DEAD!)As other reviewers have said, it takes the typical horror films cliches and turns them on their ear then cooks them into the plot.  I'm glad that someone in hollywood had the cajones to make a film like this with a big budget.  I'm not a fan of Joss Whedon's other films or shows, but I'm a fan of him just for producing this film.  Based on the short previews that I saw, I thought that the film was going to just be another lame haunted cabin movie or torture film.  I was very pleasantly surprised by how clever and fun this movie is.  It also features my favorite movie prop in recent memory, the coffee thermos bong.  Listen for the shotgun cocking sound effect when it pops open, haha!!!Don't watch it if you want a serious scary film (who over 14 years old gets scared by a movie anyway? ITS JUST A MOVIE!) This is a horror comedy.

reviewText: What's it about?Five friends go for a break at a remote cabin in the woods, where they get more than they bargained for. Together, they must discover the truth behind the cabin in the woods.Is it any good?The film begins in `groan' territory with the cliché premise of a road trip to a cabin in the woods owned by one of their friends. Yeah, the cabin has some weird things in it, like a two way mirror, but other than that, things appears semi-normal. Fast forward a bit and one of the females reads a passage of Latin out of old dusty book (SERIOUSLY, what insane person would think this would be a good idea?) which unearths an army of Zombies (*sigh*). Queue running, screaming, fighting and nothing you haven't seen before (including some woeful CGI). However, writer Joss Whedon (Buffy and Avengers) has a trick up his sleeve, managing to pull off a reveal that turns the film on its head and into something a bit more fresh and interesting. Unfortunately though, it descends into absolute absurdity, with a climax that will leave you scratching your head and laughing in hysterics. A good horror film, that's a bit of fun on a Saturday night, but, an extremely overrated one at that.Best bit?A one way elevator ride down to hell, where the worst-of-the-worst characters awaits.Did you know?The film's release date was postponed because the studio wanted to convert it to 3D, despite objections from Joss Whedon and Drew Goddard. These plans were eventually scrapped, and the film was released only in 2D.
summary: Fun horror film, but very overrated...

reviewText: Don't read too much about "Cabin in the Woods" before you watch it.  It's a clever, funny, scary, well-written subversion of the classic spam-in-a-cabin genre on multiple levels.  If you are expecting spam-in-a-cabin, you will be disappointed.  Imagine a cross between "Evil Dead 2" (which gets referenced in a few subtle and not-so-subtle ways), "Battle Royale," and "Cube," in a Lovecraftian mythos, in the nuclear plant from the Simpsons, and you might get some idea of what this movie is like.  Rent, watch and enjoy before you read too many reviews and spoil the surprises.

reviewText: I went to see "Cabin in the Woods" at a Saturday matinee on the second weekend of its release.  There were a total of six people in the movie theater.  I told myself that it was probably because most people saw it opening weekend.  However, after sitting through it, I think maybe word of mouth has slowed its progress.  Despite the number of 5 star reviews the film has received here on Amazon, and the 92% rating on Rotten Tomatoes, this may be the most overrated film ever.  Recently, there was an article in Vanity Fair by James Wolcott in which he lamented the dearth of quality movies and the lowered expectations of many filmgoers (presumably including film critics, themselves) and praised the high quality of television's current offerings.  "Cabin in the Woods", in my opinion, only reinforces his argument.  Produced and co-written by Josh Whedon, "Cabin" is no "Buffy, the Vampire Slayer", by any stretch of the imagination.  More a combination of "Evil Dead", "Resident Evil", and "Doctor Strangelove" (without the first and third film's imagination), "Cabin in the Woods" tips its hat too early, whispering its little secret to us without completely spilling the beans, although many will have it figured out long before the ending, which feels cribbed from the ending of another film written by Drew Goddard, "Cabin"s co-writer and director. The writers have obviously also harvested some of the more esoteric internet conspiracy websites to gather some of their material.With the exceptions of Richard Jenkins and Bradley Whitford as two project managers, the actors are neither better nor worse than any others in movies of this genre.  Chris Hemsworth ("Thor", "The Avengers") is the college jock who leads his small group to the titular cabin in the woods that allegedly belongs to his cousin. Enroute to the cabin, the group stops at a rundown gas station attended by the requisite nutjob--think the nutty alcoholic in the original "Friday the 13th" film--who drops ominous hints at what awaits them. Ignoring all this, the kids aren't at the cabin long before all sorts of horrors begin to unfold.  But, as the film basically shouts from the beginning, THIS IS NOT WHAT YOU THINK IT IS.  Neither is it as surprising, innovative, or as interesting as it is given credit for being (it's really a lazy man's movie that combines scenes from other movies and adds a little twist in order to appear to be more clever than it is).  And, finally, the cinematography is often murky and the CGI effects aren't that impressive, either.In fact, if you've ever played a video game, this movie is basically the same type of experience, only much less fun.  At least that's how it felt to me.I give "Cabin in the Woods" a star for its sometimes fleeting, loopy humor (particularly in the performances of Jenkins and Whitford), and a star for the fact that it somewhat resists the temptation to get overly grotesque. Otherwise, there's not much else to recommend it over a rerun of "Buffy" or "Angel", which are free and about a hundred times more entertaining.
summary: A Video Game in Sheep's Clothing

reviewText: I saw that over 90 percent of the critics liked this film, and so I thought, "Wow.  With a number like that, and with a horror movie, it really must be good."  Boy, was I wrong.I haven't read A.O. Scott's review yet - I will after writing this review - but I was happy to see that he panned it.  I don't know why yet but I will soon.  But for me, perhaps one of the biggest problems that I had with it:  expectations management.  It is such a bummer when you believe that a film - particularly in the horror genre - is going to be really good and it isn't.  But it starts out with real promise.  For example, there are a couple of really cute gals (O.K. more than that) and you think, "Cool!  They're gonna get it!"  But the satire that is used - with an odd religious undertone - just seems to fall flat to me, and I found it neither profound nor funny.Now, a film such as this is difficult to review without giving things away.  So what I will do is the following:  give you a list of movies that it has "borrowed" from - at least ones that I have seen - and let you be the judge.  Jump to the end if you don't even want this much information.  So here we go.  "I Know What You Did Last Summer."  "Scream."  "Hostel."  "The Truman Show."  "The Hunger Games."  "13 Ghosts."  I'm sure that there are more, but in reality, I wasn't much a fan of any of these films, so just munging them together for me was not really a treat.A huge disappointment for me.  And also a pretty big pass.
summary: Oh, the horror of it all

reviewText: It's best to say that no one, no matter their background, will regret viewing this film.  It's a smart horror film that isn't ashamed of it's somewhat satiric take, paying homage to the cheese of the genre as much as the scares and frights. While I doubt anyone will be so terrified as to lock their door at night after viewing this film, there will be moments and lines that will stick with you even if you aren't a fan of gore, nudity, and things that go bump in the night.The largest on screen element that bears applause is the acting.  They aren't trying to fit some pre determined role (literally) and, traversing between the worlds outside and inside the cabin develops in their changes as much as plot and jump scares.  The close runner up is masterful craftsmanship which the film is made.  Giving the type of classic jump scares in a modern context, acknowledging as many predecessors as they could (heavy on Rami, but watch out.  You might get your soul torn apart).  It is the best answer American Films have made in response to Shaun of the Dead as being outweighly funny, but having a few legitimate scares thrown in with superb writing, direction, cinematography, and acting at a level beyond most B horror, but nevertheless derived from the genre there in.Now comes the reason for three stars.  This time around, I agree with one of major criticism of this film: it could have done so much more.  I realize this is like saying, "I wasn't suspecting it to be so big, but I wish you could have done more with it."  But it's true: as fresh as the movie feels, the extent at which it could have been explore seemed to be sacrificed in the name of keeping it 90 minutes.  In particular, the scale of tension which the movie works at seems to get strained at the three quarter mark.  At it's core, the argument is one of scale and proportion, which is why I'm leaving any margin of error up to personal choice.  As I said, no one will regret viewing this film.
summary: The Most Heartbreaking Three Star I Have Given: This Film Will End Up On Shelves

reviewText: Joss Whedon and Drew Goddard reteam to bring us the 2011 smash-hit, THE CABIN IN THE WOODS! An idyllic weekend away turns in to a terrible nightmare for five friends when rampaging monsters attack their remote cabin in the woods. Meanwhile, the mysterious members of a secretive organization watch from their secure command post to ensure that no one gets out alive.Here we find that the standards of the Slasher genre are being deconstructed and played out with loving homage and a tremendous amount of self-referential humor. Dana and her friends form the five teen stereotypes that would be expected in a film of this kind... At least, their observers are counting on this considering that the fate of the world may hang in the balance. Whedon's sharp wit makes for a number of wildly entertaining exchanges between the characters, even if their clever quips take away from the natural flow of dialog. As the group enters the cabin basement, we learn that it is up to them to choose their fate by selecting one of many accursed items, each of which are linked to some terrifying creature from ancient lore. And so, they fall under attack by... zombies? Of the limitless possibilities that could have been chosen, we are stuck watching another dull zombie movie?! Luckily, all hell breaks loose towards the end, and we get to see all of the creatures that are hidden deep beneath the cabin. Kristen Connolly, Chris Hemsworth, and the other unfortunate college kids are fine enough in their respective roles, but the real fun comes from Richard Jenkins and Bradley Whitford as Sitterson and Hadley, the two quirky men behind the controls. Many of the best moments come from their crazy antics, like when the different departments bet on which monsters will dismember the unsuspecting teens first.THE CABIN IN THE WOODS puts an exciting new twist on many of the tired old cliches, and despite requiring a few minor adjustments to improve upon an otherwise perfect premise, it may yet prove to become a modern classic in the genre.-Carl ManesI Like Horror Movies
summary: ILHM Reviews: The Cabin in the Woods

reviewText: Words can't do this movie enough justice. Would the word "brilliant" be an insult? reviewText: "The Cabin In The Woods" is not your average horror movie and you definitely should not read any spoiler reviews before seeing it since there are a lot of twists. I am a horror movie fan and also enjoy most of Joss Whedon's projects (Buffy, Firefly, Dr. Horrible's Sing Along Blog, etc), so likely was predisposed to enjoy this quirky and fun movie.No spoilers from me: The movie centers on five stereotypical college kids (three guys and two girls) that head off for a weekend of fun at remote "Cabin In the Woods". The movie starts as expected, with every possible bad horror film cliche being poked at, but quickly becomes something different. The acting is on par with most modern horror movies and the special effects are actually better than expected, but the real reason to see this movie is enjoy the various clever plot twists and turns.This isn't a great a movie, but it is an enjoyable twist on horror flicks.Recommended!CFH

reviewText: "Cabin in the Woods" had a delayed release. It was filmed and produced in 2009. Usually, that is the markings of a movie that has tested poorly or doesn't have a lot of potential. Such is not the case with this movie. The reason for the delay are many but one was the casting of Chris Hemsworth who had a much bigger movie released called "Thor" and they didn't want "Cabin" to be overshadowed.There is much to be said about "Cabin in the Woods", a movie that was written by Joss Whedon who has written a variety of things in his career, including "Toy Story" "Alien: Resurrection" and most notably the cult television hits, "Buffy the Vampire Slayer", "Angel" & "Firefly". Knowing that Whedon penned "Buffy the Vampire Slayer" must be noted upon viewing "Cabin in the Woods" because it makes perfect sense. "Cabin" is "Buffy" on steroids and without the television rating system.Part of the movie's appeal is the mystery of it and so I am not going to linger upon the details of the film for long. If you choose to view this movie, and I highly recommend it, know going in that it is like nothing you've ever seen in the horror genre before. We've seen kids get in a Winnebago and head into the middle of the wilderness to a remote cabin before, dozens of times. From that point, the creator's put together one of the most creative horror movies I've ever seen."Cabin in the Woods" will slowly grow on you with quick witted writing, perfectly placed humor that had me laughing out loud and the same shocks and scares that you expect from such a movie. As the science fiction/horror/comedy rotisserie unfolds you won't be able to take your eyes off of it, especially the slam bam out of this world finale that will leave you caught between chuckling and gasping. One thing is for sure with "Cabin in the Woods", horror movies have been given an ultimatum. The generic formula seen-it-before a dozen times, here we go again routine is dead.
summary: Probably just a 4 if it weren't for the rest of the run-of-the-mill horror genre movies

reviewText: Many horror flicks are self aware, be that the character that knows what is going to happen, because that's what would have to happen if this were a horror flick, while no one believes him (that's in this movie). Or how the victims of the horror movie have to make the choice to experience the horror by taking positive actions to initiate and potentially pursue the other-worldly events (also in here). Or the realisation that all it takes to escape the horror would be to do "something" but fundamentally that is impossible (again, it's here).And although many horror movies that double as a comedy realise these things about themselves, none do it like The Cabin in the Woods.As you can probably guess from the cover / poster, this movie is about a world, not unlike a Rubik's cube, where actions unlock and enable other actions or paths. And just like a Rubik's cube, IF you don't know how it works things will quickly go to complete entropy. And that's what a horror movie experience is like for the victims, but this film goes deeper. Rather than this being an un-/super-natural horror, this is all controlled by humans. In fact, when you start watching the film, first time, you'll wonder what this could possibly have to do with anything, but that becomes apparent quite quickly.Effectively there are two stories being told, which are intertwined, and you sort of realise there is a third facet that is never actually addressed, namely how the setting was ever established. In some ways this would make a terrific movie in its own right and with any luck we will get to see that some day. Anyway, there is little one can say about this film without giving a lot away, so just accept this: two stories, intertwined and in the end one. Things will fall into place, and although where things are going become very apparent very quickly, this will take you for a ride.So, story: intriguing and out there. Characters: acting surprisingly good, though a bit shallow, with characters being archetypes and thus not being established any deeper, for some of the characters that works fine, for others typecasting and association will do the rest, though overall a bit more depth would have been good. Setting is good, cinematography/direction is at times a bit confused with the style being more akin to a TV show, than a big screen production, which isn't surprising as this is Drew Goddard's first gig as director. Some of the CG looks very cheap, though by that point you'll likely be howling with laughter, though it does grate especially combined with the other TV like looks.If you go into this movie with high expectations you will be disappointed. Even though it is different and quirky, this is aimed at a comic book audience, so if you like Joss Whedon's other work (Buffy, Avengers, even Toy Story) you will likely guess where this is going before they arrive at the titular cabin. But that isn't why you watch his stuff, you do it for the interesting take on what he's doing, and unless you are overloaded on his stuff already, you will likely enjoy it. If you don't know his stuff, or what to expect, and you like horror flicks, you probably will enjoy this. Some reviewers have said that this was one of the best things in 2012, and although I tend to agree, don't approach it with that expectation. It is one of the best things in a specific genre, namely introverted/self-aware horror comedy, which isn't a broad field. That said, it is probably one of the best things in that field for a few years.
summary: Differentiates itself by being a horror movie about horror movies, without talking about other horror movies

reviewText: I saw "Cabin in the Woods" in the theatre when it came out and just took advantage of watching it again via Prime.  Chances are if you're a fan of Joss Whedon (probably best commercially known for TV's "Buffy the Vampire Slayer" although he also wrote the movie version), you didn't and wouldn't hesitate to see "Cabin in the Woods."  I loved it!  But I will say, if you're not at least a fan of and familiar with the first "Scream" movie, you're probably not going to enjoy this movie much.  It's very well-done...probably one of the most clever takes on the movie-within-a-movie trope that I've ever seen.  It offers a great balance of humor and gore and never loses site of what it's trying to do -- entertain.  But it's largely trying to entertain horror movie fans who have a solid knoweldge of the genre.  This should not be the first horror movie you've ever seen, or even the second.To very basically describe the plot, five college students who fit the stereotypes of teenagers we find in pretty much every horror movie starring teenagers head off to spend the weekend in a cabin in the woods.  It's supposed to be cliche because the movie is an allegory -- not a satire (that would be "Scary Movie").  Nor does it as straight-forwardly deconstruct horror movies the way "Scream" does.  "Cabin in the Woods" makes its point by putting the five kids in the middle of an annual ritual sacrifice, perpetrated by an underground global organization the goal of which is to appease some very ancient, sadistic gods.  (Or perhaps perpetrated by the movie industry to entertain some twisted theatre-goers?)The organization's staff watches the sacrifice from a substation that looks like a NASA control room and although the kids involved have "free will," their actions are also manipulated by the staff making them do dumb thinks we make fun of every horror movie character for doing -- like splitting up when it's obviously best to stay together.  The kids get to choose their own adventure in terms of how they die, based on common horror movie deaths by common horror movie monsters.  They are unaware of what's going on until it's too late...or is it?"Cabin in the Woods" sports some twists and turns and is certainly never boring in terms of the pacing and action.  The humor is constant and not at all juvenile.  But I do think the movie is hard to appreciate if you're not someone who appreciates horror at a level where you can sit with friends over dinner and hash out the history of the genre and its greatest hits.  In which case, I'm sure you've already seen this movie.
summary: Too "inside" if you're not horror savvy, but so awesome if you are

reviewText: I wouldn't say this is my favorite horror movie. Not at all. But why? Because, in a way, it transcends other horror movies. The film gracefully walks the line between tongue-in-cheek and legitimate horror so incredibly well; I was still thinking about it after I'd gotten home from the theater; how the filmmakers managed to pull it all off in such a short amount of time and yet so smoothly is something of a mystery to me.The film literally showcases every type of horror film (and masterfully pays homage to quite a few specific horror films). The genre builds from a Deliverance / Wrong Turn theme and quickly shifts to something reminiscent of the Evil Dead series, complete with a self-opening hatch leading to the inevitable basement. It hovers over this sub genre for a while, and then evolves into homages to films like the Cube, The Mist, Hellraiser, various ghost, monster, and zombie movies, and eventually caps it all off with Lovecraftian Cthulhu mythos.The film rips apart every horror movie you've ever loved, stitches them all back together lovingly (albeit sarcastically at times), and what you get is one heck of an entertaining movie. If you were to have a horror movie night, or even a full-blown festival, this is the movie you'd want to play last. I'm not saying that it's any kind of "pinnacle" of horror movies. I'm saying that it is the definitive statement and a concluding, passionate love letter to the genre.
summary: The Horror Movie to End All Horror Movies

reviewText: First of all, I thought Cabin in the Woods was a lot of fun.  However, its clever ideas and its bombardment of homage seem to overshadow the fact that you're watching a black-comedy horror film.  I'll have to watch it again because, while I was checking it out the first time, I was just waiting to see what the next in-joke would be or what the next twist on an old convention would be.  Like I said: all this cleverness seems to overshadow the fact that you're watching an actual story unfold.  However, as a RABID horror fan for most of my 38 years, I felt it was nice to see that there are others out there with the same love of the genre.  Joss Whedon and friends obviously wanted to make a movie expressly for devoted horror fans, and that's great!  But, like I've mentioned, the whole affair kind of weighs itself down after a while and takes away from the fact that you're actually supposed to be watching a new version of something(s) you've loved forever.  If you're more than a casual scary movie fan, you'll definitely want to check this out just for the smile it will produce.  Others may not even understand the humor or the references.  I give it a solid B.
summary: Loving Tribute Fails to Hit the Bull's Eye

reviewText: To give you some context, I am not a horror movie freak.  I rarely watch them.  But I really like Joss Wheadon's Firefly and Serenity.  After reading that he was involved in this movie, described as a twist on the classic horror genre, I was interested enough to pre-order this without reading any reviews.  I was hoping that he had brought some of the inventiveness and interesting characters he displayed in Firefly/Serenity to this effort, and I was interested to see what he came up with.  Alas, my hopes were not realized and I am sorry that I bought the DVD vs. pay-per-view.  I watched it all the way through but I am not sure I will ever watch it again.  It definitely is a new twist on the genre, but the cutting back and forth between the two scenarios is a bit jarring, and with less time for each, it means that the characters in both are not as fully developed or sympathetic.  And I didn't find the underlying secret to be that shocking, scary or compelling.  I think the problems start in the script and I'm not sure that any director could have made a better movie out of it.  At least you can say that Wheadon and co. didn't pull any punches at the end and did not go for the feel-good ending.

reviewText: The title of my review pretty much sums the movie up.  If your familiar with Whedon's tv series, you'll pretty much find a little bit of everything, including a few familiar tv faces.Basically the premise is Firefly-Meets-Buffy/Angel-Whille-Stuck-In-An-Episode-of-Dollhouse.  Five college pals (including Chris Hemsworth; The Avengers, Snow White and the Huntsman) take a weekend trek to a remote cabin in the woods (hence the title) while, unbeknownst to them, they are the pawns in some elaborate underground society built on trying to keep the Gods happy.  In order to keep the balance, a select group (our heros) must be killed in a specific order.  There's The Virgin, The Jock, The Burnout, The Slut, and The Brain/Token Minority.As a whole, the movie is ok.  There isn't much really to root for.  As a group, our heroes are fine in their roles.  I'm not a big fan of Hemsworth but here he is beginning to show some talent.  Far and away, the best of the group is Fran Kranz (the Burnout).  He's basically us.  While everyone else goes off and does whatever they're programmed to do, he's the one saying "You want us to do what?  Are you crazy?"  It also helps that he provides the comedic relief.My only gripe is whenever we cut to the underground lab.  Here the pacing just comes to an abrupt halt.  I don't know about the rest of you but seeing old men in suits trying to "get jiggy with it" is not funny.  It's sad actually.  At least once our survivors get inside the lair in the third act that the payoff is worth it.  And as for the ending, it's refreshing to see the writers take a non-Hollywood style ending.  Is it the best way to bring the movie to a close?  Not necessarily as proven by a number of other reviewers opinions but it worked for me.  Plus how can you bash getting a chance to see Sigourney Weaver prove she still has a bit of Ripley left in her?

reviewText: If you read my Juan of the Dead review, then you probably not only have an idea of how much I love horror films but also how much I thrive for originality and creativity in the genre. Something unique is so hard to come by anymore. It's as if Hollywood is afraid of taking risks. They'd rather remake something well-known to try and capitalize on a well-known name or franchise than go forward with something completely fresh and new because it might bomb. It makes sense on one hand, but for somebody who sees one hundred films a year or more it becomes kind of tiresome. You begin to make the most with what you have in front of you. If only a horror film could come along and be clever, original, pay homage, and offer something new for horror. That's exactly what you get with The Cabin in the Woods.Curt (Chris Hemsworth) plans on taking his girlfriend Jules (Anna Hutchison) and his friends to his cousin's cabin. There's the new recruit to the football team Holden (Jesse Williams), the paranoid stoner Marty (Fran Kranz), and Jules friend Dana (Kristen Connolly) who is kind of on the fence of whether or not she'll enjoy herself on the trip. Everything seems to be progressing in typical horror movie fashion even up to the cellar door slamming open in the middle of their festivities. But something more sinister is going on; something that will put the lives of these five friends on the line.The Cabin in the Woods is a horror film that is incredibly special. If you're a fan of anything by Joss Whedon and/or Drew Goddard, then you should have a small idea of what you're in for. The entire film can be spoiled in as little as one sentence or even a few words, so don't let anyone spoil it for you. The humor is sharp witted much like most of Whedon's work. The Marty character is especially hilarious. The film is so aware of the horror films it borrows from and pays tribute to and it makes fun of that fact whenever it starts to go down a similar path. It's kind of like the concept of Scream only smarter.It's when the college students make their way down into the cellar is when things get legendary; a bold word to use perhaps but the film earns it on more than one occasion. That's all you're getting out of me as far as the storyline is concerned. This is one instance of mindblowing that deserves every opportunity to surprise and excite you. The score is just as extravagant as the film, as well. When it first begins, it's subtle and creepy. It's slow rising and a lot like what you'd expect a horror movie score to be. As things pick up though, the score becomes more triumphant and blaring. Everything is so loud and screams to be seen and heard on the best sound and video devices you can get your hands on.The Evil Dead and Evil Dead II are the films you'll hear this compared to the most, but there were shades of Friday the 13th in there as well. The blood and gore deliver in spades, especially in the final act. You practically feel like buckets of blood have been dumped directly into your lap by the time Trent Reznor is screaming at you during the ending credits. But let's talk about that final act for a moment. You have an idea of where the film is going leading up to that point. The Cabin in the Woods is telling this story from two different angles and you think you have everything figured out. But then that one scene happens. If you've seen the film, you know exactly what I'm talking about; where everything hits the fan. My jaw was on the floor and I had goosebumps all over my body. This is why I go to the movies. This is why I love horror; to experience something like this.The Cabin in the Woods doesn't reinvent the horror genre, but it does completely manipulate it in a way that is just so freaking spectacular that you won't know what to do with yourself. If this was the last horror movie to ever grace the silver screen I would be completely content with that. The full-length horror movie era can begin with The Cabinet of Dr. Caligari in 1920 and end with The Cabin in the Woods in 2012, as far as I'm concerned. My brain was turned inside out and I was never so happy to have that sensation after viewing a film. Brilliant, terrifying, and fantastically imaginative, The Cabin in the Woods makes you feel like your brain explodes during its duration and you're left piecing it back together like Humpty Dumpty after the credits. Sensational doesn't even begin to describe how superb this film really is.

reviewText: This kind of film is a bit out of Joss Whedon's usual wheelhouse, but he makes it work.  It's evident from the first few minutes that this isn't your standard horror/slasher movie... or is it?  It takes a while for the viewer to be fully aware of what's happening, and even then you're really unsure.  You know things are not as they seem, but the extent becomes clearer as the movie progresses, building to a quite satisfactory (and quite unusual) ending.  Hemsworth, Connolly et al are adequate to good and sufficiently engaging for their roles (as such), but the best casting in this film is Bradley Whitford and Richard Jenkins who are perfect as the pair of, well, whatever they are. You'll have to judge for yourself.  A few minor plot holes and inconsistencies, which don't detract from the overall enjoyment; maybe the book explains them (though reviews seem to indicate otherwise).  Otherwise, recommended.
summary: Good Whedon work; smart take on slasher/horror genre

reviewText: Yes this is horror film but your would be WRONG if you thought it was about the "monsters" in this film.Here is a quote from Joss Whedon on CITW: On another level it's a serious  critique of what we love and what we don't about horror movies. I love being scared. I love that mixture of thrill, of horror, that objectification/identification thing of wanting definitely for the people to be alright but at the same time hoping they'll go somewhere dark and face something awful. The things that I don't like are kids acting like idiots, the devolution of the horror movie into torture porn and into a long series of sadistic comeuppances. Drew and I both felt that the pendulum had swung a little too far in that direction.This film is a satire and statement about what can be horrific..and I think this film succeeds where 90% of the current horror films fail miserably. And I for one found the film funny and scary at the same time.Do NOT go see this film if all you want to see is T&A; horror that is not what this film is about. Do see this film if you like well thought out satire and subplots that become far more important than what you THOUGHT was the main plot.

reviewText: I don't think you would rent this movie unless you were a fan of Joss Whedon or the horror genre in general, and with that I don't think you will be disappointed.  It kind of takes the self aware slasher film semi spoof (brought to life so well 16 years ago in Scream) to a new level.  My main complaint is that the writing that is so great in the "control room" scenes (a big thumbs up for Bradley Whitford and Richard Jenkins), is not as good in the cabin scenes - they just are kind of standard - but it still works.  One thing I love about Joss Whedon (besides his plotting, dialog, and visual sensibilities) is his devotion to people he has previously worked with and he is rewarded with Fran Kranz's performance here as the obligatory stoner in the group - great.  It was also funny to see Chris Hemsworth, after seeing the Avengers (multiple times), Snow White, and Thor, as a college student.  I had the same feeling here as I used to when I was a kid and my mother would watch Big Valley, and I would wonder why Lee Majors didn't beat the bad guys up with his bionic arm.Anyway, good movie, interesting premise, worth the rental.
summary: Enjoyable ... if you like this kind of thing.

reviewText: Five friends (Chris Helmsworth, Kristen Connolly, Fran Kranz, Anna Hutchinson, and Jesse Williams) head to a backwoods cabin for a getaway.  Unbeknownst to them, they are being watched and monitored...and very soon, they are about to be plunged into a nightmare beyond all imagination.Here's the thing about THE CABIN IN THE WOODS: it's a horror movie.  Not a horror/comedy, but a straight-up horror movie with a sense of humor (in the same sense that writer Joss Whedon's THE AVENGERS was a superhero movie with a sense of humor).  And yet, it manages to rewrite the very underpinnings of the horror genre, making it a parody of sorts.  The smart script and solid direction (courtesy of CLOVERFIELD director Drew Goddard) are both entertaining, thoughtful, and full of references to all sorts of horror cliches (hence the generic title); and yes, it's just a damn good horror film in and of itself, scary and gory and all-around fun.Of course, this wouldn't be possible without the cast.  The five leads are great; supporting actors Richard Jenkins, Bradley Whitford, and Amy Acker are also fantastic, providing much of the dark humor (and it IS dark).  There's also a great cameo I shan't reveal.  In fact, you'll probably find this whole review very lacking in plot description.  Why is that?  Because to say any more would be to ruin the fun.  It's not necessarily a film with "twists"; it's more like each component builds upon the previous elements, creating a bloody canvas by which we can compare most every horror film ever made.  THE CABIN IN THE WOODS is for Whedon fans, and fans of the genre in general.  If you like smart horror that isn't afraid to shirk the conventions, then this is your film.
summary: How do you turn an entire genre on its head?

reviewText: It's hard to be original these days, everyone's done everything. Combine that with an ever more terrible selection of good horror films, leaves me yearning for something, anything interesting.Expectations and realitiesCabin in the woods was NOT what i expected, i didn't read the synopsis, i just went off the genre and general word of mouth. I was pleasantly surprised it took an unconventional approach and while i can't really see it as a pure to goodness horror movie, it has some good elements of horror, rolled in with a nice helping of mythological mystery and a cherry of well done comedy.GoreA note about gore: i usually hate it, and gore to me is not horror in the slightest. In this film while there is gore, it isn't over the top and isn't harped on or focused on or used in any way to just make the audience squeal/cringe. Most of it is just a part of whats happening and fits in stylistically and that's it. I like that.QuipOh and half the time you'll be yelling at hemmsworth to just use his damn thor hammer and finish it.Attention spanThis is not a movie to have playing in the background, you need to pay attention, or else you'll miss small but important information, or some hilarious little comedic shtick.How long does it feel?It moves along very well, i never got bored or found myself waiting for the next thing to happen, it's a well written script in that aspect that it hits the proper points at the right times.SEMI-but-NOT-totally-SPOILERSSo what i gathered before watching this, was that it was a bunch of kids that go into a cabin in the woods and get killed somehow. it's the somehow that defines and separates this flick from a lot of the boiler plate horrors out there. Theres 2 more layers of dynamic on top of that, the first characters you're introduced to are the ones controlling all the bad stuff going on, and you'll get to find out their reasons for doing so. I feel like i should be turned off with everything going on in this film, but it actually pieces and works together quite well, which is usually the sign of a good script.Overall, i found it a good watch, it doesn't set out to get awards, but then, what comedy or horror ever does? It's here to entertain and give you something a bit different than the conventional crap that's out there.
summary: It's a horror? It's a comedy? it's a mystery? Yes it actually works, and it entertained my brain!

reviewText: If you follow the Horror genre then you've probably heard how Cabin in the Woods was sitting on the shelf for the last few years due to MGM/UA's bankruptcy. But with the upcoming release of The Avengers, Written and Directed by Joss Whedon who co-scripted Cabin with its Director Drew Goddard, and the bankability of Thor/Avengers/Cabin actor Chris Hemsworth, Cabin in the Woods has been finally released.And I'm glad it was because CITW is a Horror/Comedy masterpiece that I would easily put aside anything that came out during Horror's glory days in the 1980's when we got classics like Return of the Living Dead (my favorite movie), Creepshow, An American Werewolf in London, Evil Dead 2 etc...Now, a lot of people have been mentioning Scream (1996) in comparison to CITW because both movies act as a post-modern meta exploration of the Horror genre while also delivering the prerequisite scares, blood and boobies. But Cabin is soo much more as it doesn't simply have the characters be aware that they are in a Horror movie scenario and comment on it (which was Screams only innovation despite the fact that it had been done before in, for instance, Return to Horror High (1987) and many other movies including Wes Craven's own New Nightmare) and instead uses the archetypical characters (The Jock, Stoner, Nerd, Virgin and Slut) to tie the story into something more mythological which gives the movie greater resonance.Then there's also the fact that CITW keeps building and building towards and epic crescendo with one twist and turn after another and not in some stupid M. Night Shamalamadingdong way as what Cabin gives us is mysteries and revelations followed by satisfying answers and an ending that isn't simply designed to lead into a sequel unlike so much of the mindless franchised garbage of the last decade or so (Final Destination, Saw, Underworld, Resident Evil).Cabin in the Woods is a GREAT movie that should be seen by any self-respecting Horror fan and will be a day one Blu-ray purchase for me. It's the best Horror movie I've seen since American Psycho back in 2000 and the first movie to leave me buzzing from seeing it since Fight Club blew the back of my head off in 1999.
summary: As good as anything that came out in the 1980's! A Horror/Comedy masterpiece!!!

reviewText: Let me make it clear at the outset, I'm a fan of Joss Whedon, especially Firefly and Dollhouse, but this time around I was a bit underwhelmed, given this movie's pedigree and my love for a well-crafted horror story. All the hype - elevating one's expectations - doesn't help either.I was entertained by this movie, but never really scared or intrigued. I'm not sure that the film's split personality does it much service. We're Joss-tossed between some really good monster visuals, and silliness reminiscent of a TV sitcom. There are some moments of really good satire: the evil toothless owner of a rural gas station, warning our traveling teens not to head into the woods. Another vignette rips into Japanese schoolgirl supernatural, capturing the cliche perfectly. On the other hand, moments of ghoulish horror didn't quite jell for me. Our hapless characters (well, most of them) are dispatched in efficient fashion, but I can't say I cared enough about them to really bat an eye. Actor Fran Kranz's portrayal of an eccentric stoner grated on my nerves after awhile. It was not a matter of acting craft, but more the fact that he was merely reworking his crazy immature eccentric mode as Topher Brink in 'Dollhouse'. I hope he's not going to spend a lifetime in this type of role.This being said, the Blu-ray picture was impressive and the DVD did come with a boatload of extras. To the potential buyer, I'd suggest really mulling over what you expect in a spook film before spending your hard-earning dough.
summary: Much Ado About Nothing All That Great

reviewText: In the world of filmmaking, genres must occasionally be reinvented; otherwise they become predictable and stale. In the late 90's, West Craven reinvigorated the horror genre with "Scream," by combining sly self-awareness and humor with genuine scares. Not since "Scream" has a mainstream film come along and reinvented the horror genre like "The Cabin in the Woods".The film begins with two opposing and intertwined storylines. One is the oldest cliché in the world - 5 attractive college students decide to head off to a cabin in the woods for a weekend of fun, sex, and substance abuse. It's a surprise to no one that terror, bloodletting, and death await them. But there's another storyline happening; where a group of corporate drones are watching the youngsters on TV screens, anticipating their actions as if they're producers making a reality show. If that were the case, then the film would hardly be fresh and original. Tying reality TV to horror has been done many times in recent years. So what, exactly, is really going on with the workers watching the kids, and why does their fate alternately amuse, entertain, and terrify them?To give anything else away would be a crime, because the best thing about this film is its unpredictability. If you think you know what's coming ... you don't. Lots of films and television shows try so hard to shock, titillate, or surprise their audience that the tactics just come across as empty and manipulative, but "The Cabin in the Woods" has genuinely new, fresh ideas that it executes expertly.I will give one thing away ... the ending of this film offers no possibility for a sequel. So as an added bonus, fans of the film won't have to watch a fresh, original piece of filmmaking turn into a redundant franchise.

reviewText: While it doesn't quite have the scope or organization to make it a truly stand-alone film, THE CABIN in the WOODS successfully incorporates horror, science fiction, digital age conspiracy, and, above all, spoofs of all these genres under one wrap. It's far from frightening (nor does it really try to be),  but the Pandora's Box of monsters and villains from various horror films through the ages, along with all its other vestiges and nuances, give it something that many fright aficionados (and even many of those who normally hate this kind of thing) should find hilariously enjoyable. Best of all, it's full of surprises!

reviewText: An ingenious vehicle for poking and prodding the clichés present in almost every horror movie made over the last thirty years. Part self-referential tongue-in-cheek a'la the first Scream and part identity crisis horr-edy in the same ballpark as Shaun of the Dead, it adds a bevy of original salts and spices and emerges as something completely different. I was told to avoid spoilers like the plague, and I'd strongly advise you to do the same - it's not a premise that translates well to explanation, and half the fun lies in the viewer's slow internal realization of where it's headed. Brilliantly paced, unrelentingly funny, thoroughly unpredictable and boldly written, (with an ending so ballsy and appropriate, I wanted to stand up and cheer) this is one of the most bright, daring, original efforts I've seen in years. Great fun that may be directed particularly at hardcore fans of the genre, it's just opaque enough for casual viewers to have a ball, too.
summary: A Bright, Layered, Effective Effort That's Also Thoroughly Hilarious

It is all there and it is wonderful in its impact and successful communication of hell unleashed.Prior to the real movie beginning in the last half hour, this movie rips off Evil Dead 2 and I found myself so irritated at this seemingly pointless, message free horror fest since I am not and never have been a fan of horror films despite my attendance at more than one Fangoria Horror Convention.  I know it but I'm not a part of it.But the ending rocks.  The sacrificial lambs go off script.
summary: The last part of the movie is the REAL MOVIE.

reviewText: Bragging that you've written something in three days then filming it is not always the best way to position yourself when your three-day product comes under scrutiny.The Cabin in the Woods is an overly cute attempt to invigorate an aging genre.  Simultaneous storylines lead the viewers towards the ultimate showdown.  One half of this movie is brightly lit and glibly handled; the other half is an aching cliché drowned in darkness (literally, couldn't see much of anything).  Neither half of the movie actually meshed into a cohesive story.  There were moments that were quite effective, yes, but too many times everything fell flat, weighed down by a concept that didn't allow much wiggle room.  The inherent problem with a one gimmick premise lies with whether or not the viewer will want to see it again, knowing the punch line.  It didn't help that co-writer/director Drew Godard made the claim that they wanted to pay homage to slasher films.  A homage only works if you plan to replicate or elevate the genre in question.  This movie did neither.  The slasher part of the film was half hearted, the jazzed-up-joke-part wasn't fully realized; in the end, it all came down to a single sentence explanation that was more loopy than clever.  Only the mayhem sequence was truly spectacular and intriguing, unfortunately, it didn't last long.My greatest complaint is with Drew Godard's idiot choice of filming the slasher half of this movie in almost total darkness and wimping-out with the killing sequences, most done out of the sightline.  The fact that he did this on purpose is even more bewildering.  For example, he boasted that he filled the cellar to capacity with a multitude of items necessary to the story, but then he obliterated any sight of them by filming the sequence in darkness making the entire sequence null and void.  The five characters could have all been looking at cans of beans for all it mattered.Bad choices are just that.

reviewText: The love shack meets Lovecraft narrative in this film follows five characters who are fleshed out with personality and charm as they set off for an ill-fated vacation. There is a hulking athlete on an academic scholarship named Curt (Chris Hemsworth) who is dating the pretty co-ed, Jules (Anna Hutchison), a newly minted (or dyed) blonde. His cousin recently purchased a vacation home and he invited him to enjoy the weekend there. His friends are Marty (Fran Kranz), a joking marijuana enthusiast, Dana (Kristen Connolly), the cute but courageous girl-next-door, and Holden (Jesse Williams), Curt's fellow student-athlete.They joke around, pack up a RV and hit the road until they make a pit stop at a decrepit gas station. As Curt goes to fill up the RV with gas, it become clear that this is eerie territory. The gas station is falling apart on the outside, but the inside is filled with filth, dead animal pelts and other freaky Leatherface-esque paraphernalia as well as a creepy hick of a proprietor (Tim de Zarn). There is a brief stand-off between the friends and this judgmental creep, but he gives them directions and they head off with a newly fueled RV. The gang makes it to the cabin in the woods, but there are a few oddities that might be a harbinger for things to come. Particularly scary is a painting of what appears to be gray-skinned frontiersmen and their hounds ripping apart an unlucky goat for food or, perhaps, sacrifice. Still, they have fun swimming during the day and dancing to music at night but the fun ends when they stumble upon the evil and supernatural threats in the cabin's basement. Over the course of the night, they must discover the truth behind the cabin in the woods  and persevere hell on Earth.The script by Joss Whedon is original, sharp, funny, entertaining and  ambitious. The film is well-produced featuring great special effects and make-up as well as direction from first time director, and co-writer of the film, Drew Goddard. The acting is top notch across the board, but Hutchison, Connolly and Kranz stand out in particular as they add some flair, vulnerability and humor to their characters. Bradley Whitford and Richard Jenkins are excellent in the thankless supporting roles of hard-working, smart aleck bureaucrats who make one heck of a duo. Richard Jenkins has an amazing ability to switch from jolly, middle-class white collar stiff to outraged and concerned neurotic in a millisecond, and Bradley Whitford beautifully effuses subtle shifts in attitude using facial and body language while also portraying the cool, wise ass to a tee. There is a scene where Jenkins' character mocks Whitford's bet on a prediction and his reaction is priceless, which is on top of great dialogue by Whedon and Goddard. Brian White and Amy Acker are also both superb in supporting roles as bureaucrats in different departments within a government agency. At around ninety minutes of film, there could have been some more exposition or scenes, but it is still nothing short of excellent.The Cabin in the Woods combines the original media (horror), dark humor, satire and even meta fiction.  You can sense the meta and satirical aspects of the film as similar in spirit to the TV shows Tales from the Crypt and South Park. In some ways, it did to horror films whatDr. Strangelovedid for Cold War nuclear politics. The Cabin in the Woods is a fantastic ride, a breath of fresh air and an instant classic. It has been decades since horror of this caliber has been on the silver screen. The DVD release is loaded with features such as a making-of documentary, audio commentary by Whedon and Goddard and featurettes about the film's production such as animatronics, visual effects and make-up.
summary: A horror film almost too good to be true

reviewText: Joss Whedon doing a cliched horror film? Surely, this cannot be. He has always given very layered and complex stories and we always love the characters because they break all the stereotypes. Surely, this must be a mistake. He would do not so simple a thing.Yep. He did it. And it was a LOT more than we ever bargained for.In this dual-arced story we see not only a typical horror film, but the reason why we have typical horror film. And that might be too obtuse a line to use, but I really want to do this review sans-spoilers. We've got zombies, we've got werewolves, we've got unicorns, we've got tentacles, we've got giant snakes, we've got dastardly robots, all pitted against five stereotypes that don't fit the stereotypes. It's a wonderful symphony of chaos and destruction. Oh, and we've got Sigourney Weaver, too. And that's always a plus!So, why should you watch something like this? Because it explains the past 20 years of bad horror cinema. Because Joss does NOT know how to tell simple stories and we love him for that. In the end, we watch the film because we love the past 20 years of bad horror cinema.Oh, and there are some bonus features too. Sorry, I almost forgot to mentioned them because I was distracted by the movie. That's some good stuff, too. Just watch the film, and don't take it too seriously until you realize just what the movie is actually about. Because THAT is the really scary part if you ask me....

reviewText: This is one of the most original horror movies I have seen in a decade.  The premise starts off as obvious, 5 teenagers out for a weekend in the woods.  The "eye in the sky" part lets you know something ominous is going to occur.  Just how ominous you really are not sure until about the last 20 minutes.  So for most of the film, it is a typical teen horror movie (with all the teens being in their 20s or 30s), slowly they begin to perish in awful situations, which may or may not have been created by our "eye in the sky".  Then the story line takes a turn, and what you thought was, is no longer.  All hell breaks loose and there is sheer pandamonium as two of our teens are still alive (although should not be).  What comes from this is a great plot twist, some of our childhood horrors and a cameo by a great actress who is at the head of it all.  This is a must see/must be movie.  One of the best in this genre I have seen in awhile.

reviewText: I give this five stars for enjoyment. Sure, the plot had some holes. As I read some of the reviews, I realize that some people do not place as much importance on editing, music and the message in the movie as I do, so the plot holes did not bother me.Pros:"In" references.  If you don't know them, you won't enjoy it because you will be clueless.Sardonic humor. Sarcastic humor. Highbrow humor. Droll humor. Dry humor. If you don't get any of these, see above.Better than average acting. Seeing some faves in a different light.The editing and music. The way some scenes were shot, with the music and editing, to make you feel a certain way when you already logically knew that what they were gearing up for could not possibly happen. It was the perfect dichotomy of facts and feelings. My kids and I laughed hysterically over some of these scenes, they were so well done.Cons:Some plot holes, but don't we all suspend disbelief for a lot of movies?"In" references. See above.Each person can take away a different meaning from a movie like this. Some of the scenes just reminded you of your own life when you thought you'd seen the end of the bad times, but you were wrong. *Ding!* Some of it was an overall "Somebody else is pulling the strings in our lives".  And some of it was the famous "You're not pulling MY strings, I'm changing the rules!" Some people won't see anything at all and just come away confused. If you like movies that are a little wry, give it a try.
summary: It wasn't what I was expecting, but that's a good thing.

reviewText: 99 out of 100 movies that come out of Hollywood are crap.  Boring, unimaginative, unfunny, derivative - you get the idea. But that 1 in 100 is actually entertaining - as is Cabin In The Woods.  It's a horror movie for horror movie fans, and especially horror films that manage to blend real humor with the scares (think the Scream series or Return of the Living Dead, or the Evil Dead series). This movie skewers, with real affection, dozens of horror films and even those films that on their own did a real job of skewering the genre. It's well made and smart and provides some truly funny dialogue as well as several priceless sight gags.  Oh there's plenty of gore but most of those scenes are sight gags as well. Among my favorite scenes include the hut-hut SWAT team and the unicorn. Overall a really fun horror film and worth the price of admission. One of the rare films today that can be watched and enjoyed more than once..

reviewText: (My review is 3.5 out of 5.0 stars and contains minor spoilers)THE CABIN IN THE WOODS was one of the most creative horror films I've ever seen. It begins in an unusual way; within a laboratory where a group of scientists are preparing for the arrival of the "target." Then it proceeds as one would have originally expected in this genre: a group of young adults, in this case college-age students, are going away for a wild weekend of sex, drugs, and partying before everything falls apart in a somewhat predictable fashion.I didn't hate the approach but I didn't really love it either. It felt like a cross between TEXAS CHAINSAW MASSACRE (group goes to mysterious house and gets butchered) and SAW (in terms of the outsider controlling aspects of the disaster) that while original did take some of the scare out of it. By the time the scientists are celebrating I found myself asking, "What the heck is all this?" I did want to know where it was all going to end up and found the conclusion very surprising.While I suggest this movie is a cross between TEXAS CHAINSAW MASSACRE (the original) and SAW, the reason I would consider those films to be classics in horror and this not is that the back and forth between the puppets and the puppeteers didn't feel genuine. I wasn't jumping out of my seat, my heart didn't race, and I wasn't really disturbed by what I had just seen when it was all over. (Perhaps because it didn't seem real.) And if the goal was to make it feel artificial so as to turn it into a comedy, that didn't quite work either.The bottom line is that if you are looking for a modestly thrilling semi-horror, semi-mystery, semi-parody movie with good-enough acting and special effects, THE CABIN IN THE WOODS is worth renting for a rainy evening.
