reviewText: I didn't go see this in the theatre.  I wasn't even going to buy a copy of it, despite knowing Joss Whedon's name was attached to it.  Until my friends told me I had to see it and that all is not what it seems and this really isn't your run of the mill kids go out to some cabin and get killed kinda movie.  I mean, I dislike slasher movies.  They are so predictible.  That was one thing this movie was not, and I loved it for that as much as for the far more witty than ususal horror movie dialogue.I won't give away the surprise...but this movie starts with the typical plot device of 5 dumb kids go off to some rundown old cabin in the middle of a dark spooky woods.  Each one represents the normal assortment of dumb kids that you tend to see in such movies--the handsome jock, the smart nerdy guy, the sexy cheerleader kind of girl, the smart guy with a heart of gold, and the shy "virgin."  We all know these people, even if the names and actors change from movie to movie.  We know the handsome jock goes with the sexy cheerleader and that the good guy and the shy virgin may or may not end up together, while the smart nerdy guy figures out what is going on long before anyone else does, but no one listens to him.Of course, there is also the crazy old guy they run into along the way who warns them Not To Go There...which, of course, they ignore.  After all, what can some crazy old guy know?  Plus the physical star of the piece, the haunted cabin with its dark secrets and scary decor.  Accordingly, our group sets up shop in this cabin and make the mistake of going down into the basement which, in this case, is filled with all sorts of strange weird junk that looks like it came out of thousands of other horror movies, plus a few we've never even thought of.  It was like stepping into a horror movie collection to end all horror movie collections.Of course, danger and death and blood ensues.  The five kids are forced to fight off scary monsters and, along the way, the real plot of the movie unfolds itself...one far more terrifying than any old spooky cabin in the woods.  This is a movie wrapped up in a movie and plays a good old twist on modern "reality" tv.Highly recommended.  Just let it all play out.  You won't be disappointed unless you come into the movie with your mind made up that it should be the typical slasher monster movie.
summary: Not Your Run of the Mill Horror Flick

reviewText: People act like Cabin In The Woods is a horror masterpiece. I advise you, if you are in fact a horror fan, to keep your expectations at a minimum. However, if you like comedy & don't mind seeing a little splash of blood here and there, you'll probably enjoy this movie more than I did.  Call me OCD, but I like to keep my horror and comedy separate when it comes to movies...but (clearly after reading all of the other reviews here) I am in the minority. Even if we push this films attempt at jokiness aside, I am STILL disappointed: the kill scenes were pretty PG, and the "monsters" reminded me more of soft-edged comic book creatures than blood-hungry beasts.  The only part that intrigued me (the sacrificial rituals) wasn't discussed enough to satisfy, and the ending didn't make too much sense to me (you'd rather kill a building full of people & possibly the entire country along with yourself instead of just offing your stoner buddy?!?! Come on!) To sum it up: if you're a fan of Hellboy, you'll probably enjoy this movie quite a bit. If you want a scary movie, though, skip Cabin In The Woods.
summary: DON'T GET YOUR HOPES UP TOO HIGH...

reviewText: At first glance it appears to be a typical teens go to a cabin and a killer offs them one by one kind of movie.  This movie is anything but typical.  It is a smart, witty, often hilarious roller coaster ride that keeps amping up the tension.  It does a great job of setting expectations, then randomly fulfilling or shattering those expectations.  It also takes a step back examines the structure of slasher movies and why we need and love horror movies. Mostly it's good scary fun. The ads do a good job of setting up this bait and switch.  It's like ordering a Miller Lite and instead getting a delicious, hand crafted, micro-brew IPA.  Sure, a few will ultimately will dislike the switch, but for most of us, we get to enjoy a delicious, carefully crafted masterpiece.
summary: Super fun twist on the slasher genre

reviewText: I wanted to see this when it came out in the theater, and was intrigued by some reviews I read where people described this as smart, funny, and with an interesting twist.  WHAT?  So glad I waited for video, because this is barely worth the cost of renting, much less paying to see in an actual theater.  We have almost no character development here, not even much in the way of stereotypical horror development.  I didn't care AT ALL about any of the characters, except the stoner, who was the only one to show even a modicum of common sense. Further, though, this just simply wasn't scary.  What's more, it wasn't even funny.  And it certainly wasn't "smart" as some reviewers claimed.  In fact, it was absolutely stupid.  I won't spoil it for those who insist on watching this, but there was just no explanation for anything that went on here.  The entire premise of the movie made absolutely no sense at all.  And I'm not a big snob - a movie with huge plot holes can be fun, so long as the story moves along, the characters are decent, and/or the satire is good enough.  Here, we get none of that.  As the characters are killed, we could care less.  There is so little buildup to the movie becoming "scary," it's just, well, not scary.  I'd add here that I am truly horrified of zombies, but even THEY can't scare me in this one.  Just lame.  See it if you're curious, but don't expect much.
summary: Bad, had me shaking my head...

reviewerName: Gregory J. Casteel "Dr. Gregory J. Casteel"
reviewText: This is not only a brilliant horror film, but also a brilliant deconstruction of horror films.  If you're a fan of the horror genre, you absolutely have to see it.  It's scary, suspenseful, and sexy; but it's also funny, clever, and self-aware.  It's a fresh new take on a genre that was starting to get rather stale.  Written by geek icons Joss Whedon and Drew Goddard, produced by Whedon, and directed by Goddard, this film takes all of the standard tropes you'd expect to find in a modern, blood-soaked horror movie, shines a spotlight on them, and gives them a fresh new interpretation that somehow manages to be both subversive and celebratory at the same time.  Here, subtext becomes text, as Goddard and Whedon pull back the curtain and allow us to see what's really going on behind the scenes of the typical slasher film, letting us in on the secret of why all of these movies seem to follow the same basic plot.  Some things in this movie will feel very familiar to anyone who has seen any of the popular horror films of the past few decades, especially the "Halloween", "Friday the 13th", and "A Nightmare on Elm Street" franchises and their derivatives.  But everything else in this movie is so original, so unexpected, and so unlike anything we've ever seen before in a slasher film that it transcends the genre and redefines what a horror movie is capable of being.  This is not merely a horror film.  It's a subtle commentary on the very nature of horror films.  It is a loving critique of the genre, as well as a satirical homage to it.  It's not a parody like the "Scary Movie" franchise; though it does often blur the line between the grotesque and the absurd.  This is an actual horror thriller that is just as suspenseful, just as violent, and just as gory as any other slasher film.  But there's a lot more to it than that.  As you'd expect from Joss Whedon and Drew Goddard -- who first worked together on Whedon's cult classic TV series, "Buffy the Vampire Slayer" -- this movie manages to find the dark humor in the midst of all the horror; and it celebrates the aesthetics of the macabre.  More importantly (at least from the perspective of geeks like me) this movie has an intellectual depth to it that you just don't find in the typical slasher film.  If you're not a geek, you can thoroughly enjoy this movie simply for its edge-of-your-seat thrills, its laugh-out-loud jokes, and its eye-candy cast (personally, I liked the redhead; but, then again, I always like the redhead).  But geeks will also appreciate the clever subtext that Goddard and Whedon have built into this film.  There's definitely a lot going on underneath the surface.  If you're a fan of horror movies, you really owe it to yourself to watch this.  And you'll definitely want to watch it more than once in order to make sure you catch all of the subtle details that are easy to miss the first time around.I think you'll also enjoy the bonus materials included on this disc.  I certainly had a big grin on my face the entire time I was watching the mini documentary on the making of the film, and the featurettes on monster design and special effects.  It's fun to see how all this stuff gets done.  The audio commentary by Joss Whedon and Drew Goddard is also a lot of fun to listen to.  Overall, the special features complement the movie quite nicely.  I was quite pleased with them.I can't guarantee that you'll love this movie as much as I do, because your tastes may be very different from mine.  But if what I've written here has piqued your curiosity about this film, then you really need to check it out and decide for yourself whether or not you like it.  I'm certainly glad I saw it.

reviewText: Opening scenes of the so-overused horror movie hooks of:(1.) No cell phone reception (added bonus of no GPS either).(2.) Coeds of every likable and non-likable persuasion e.g. virgin, jock, promiscuous girl, intelligent one, pothead. Meant to die in predictable order.(3.) Large vehicle, or off road vehicles, but in this case we get a bonus - a large RV motorhome with motorbike on the back.(4.) Helicopter view of said vehicle traveling on back country roads. Really overdone visual hook.(5.) Chaw spittin' grizzled, scripture quotin', nasty, crazed gas station attendant. Yes, all that in one human package.(6.) House (cabin - whatever) has the sordid past with some of it's sordid tools still in the, guess - (a.) basement or (b.) attic. Well, no attic so your choice is limited.(7.) Sex innuendo, booze and pot, but all pretty low key and quite tertiary to the story.With that intro I'm prepared for another stolen ideas and redux of countless other movies in this genre - a < one star vote. Except, about a third of the way in you begin to sense a bit of horror genre parody, burlesque, satire, sarcasm, understatement. By the end, every horror entity ever seen gets a brief second life. Power to the evil ones! OK, carried away. Extra bonus, a guest appearance by Sigourney Weaver.The Rubik's Cube cabin on the cover, like most every other movie DVD cover-enticing visual, is marginally applicable to the movie.

reviewText: - a disembodied voice: "Forgive us and let us get it over with."Once in a blue moon, some brilliant so-and-so elevates a horror film beyond the limitations and schlockiness of its genre. The last time I saw a horror flick that had this much awesome sauce on it, it was Wes Craven's SCREAM. And, seeing as THE CABIN IN THE WOODS was birthed from the fiendish minds of Joss Whedon and Drew Goddard, you are in for some clever creep-outs.I promise, no spoilers. The plot initially trots out that creaky premise: a group of college students go to a remote cabin for fun and frolic, and then cue horrific shenanigans. These youths are drawn out of stock archetypes (the good girl, the promiscuous girl, the jock, the brain, and the school cut-up). Except that one of the film's neat conceits is that most of these kids actually defy their stereotypes (the jock is himself a brain; the p0t-smoking clown is the most sensible). Folks who've worked with Whedon in past projects pop up. There is a surprise guest or two. I refuse to go into detail about them two lab geeks (Richard Jenkins and Bradley Whitford) what opens the film, except that they immediately compel you to wonder what in heck they're doing in this story. Part of the fun is in seeing the two separate threads converge.Surely, at some point in your theater-venturing life, you've yelled at the screen over some film character's questionable move. Odds are, you've done this most during a horror flick. THE CABIN IN THE WOODS submits an explanation for all those dumb choices made by past victims in horror cinema. And, yes, there's something going on here that smacks some of meta storytelling. Don't be too surprised when the narrative strays off the beaten path. But, first, you'll get the clichéd menacing local (naturally, he welcomes the kids with ominous remarks) and there's a dusty diary (parts of which passages are worryingly in Latin), and other familiar horror tropes. THE CABIN IN THE WOODS would like to make you feel at home before it pulls the rug out from under you. When that cellar door bursts open... there's no going back.One concern is that the novelty and inventiveness and the sheer smarts that went into the film may actually overwhelm (or is it undermine?) the jump-out-of-your-seat moments. But there are enough good scares here, I think. And because Joss Whedon wrote this in part, I tried not to get too invested in any one character. We recognize the diabolical delight Whedon takes in priming us into rooting for his characters before he kills them off brutally. Except, it turns out, I couldn't NOT pull for some of the characters, because they're actually played with some wit and verve by the actors. Will history teach us nothing? Whedon lulls you. He's a luller.I don't know that THE CABIN IN THE WOODS is quite the game changer other folks are claiming it to be. It's original and creative and whip smart. It's spooky and funny (them lab geeks provide plenty of tongue-in-cheek dialogue, and I suppose we're meant to draw a correlation between their callous responses and the movie audience's own jadedness). For horror fans, there are insane homages galore. The film's third act absolutely blew my mind, and it absolutely sucks that I can't even talk about it for fear of ruining it for you. Whedon and Goddard have managed to tweak the fright genre, even as they've simultaneously, lovingly crammed in so many horror tropes. Presumably, to offset the excess, they had to come up with the most vanilla title for their project (Whedon winkingly calls the film a "loving hate letter" to the horror genre). Go see THE CABIN IN THE WOODS. But avoid that creepy hillbilly gas attendant.

reviewText: LoL, this is a horror movie of sorts but not your typical horror movie!  One thing I will say after having watched through this entire movie was that it most definitely had Joss Whedon written all over it.  For those of you who are familiar with Joss Whedon's past works, especially Buffy the Vampire Slayer and Firefly/Serenity, you will know what I'm talking about.  Firstly, just simply the sense of both humor and irony throughout it...that's definitely Joss Whedon.  Furthermore, all of the creatures & whatnot toward the end of the movie...only Joss could come up with so many interesting and unique types of creatures.  Furthermore, for those that are familiar with Reavers from Firefly/Serenity, he even through some of them in the mix.  Haha, gotta love it.  That being said though, I don't want to spoil too much of the movie, because it's been said and it's true...the less you know going into the movie, the more you'll enjoy it.From many positive reviews I'd seen here online and that I'd heard from my brother in law, and just simply the fact that Joss Whedon's name was on this, I bought it up without hesitation.  I am a long time Joss Whedon fan, as is one of my buddies that watched this with me, and we both very much enjoyed it, plus another friend of mine and my wife had sat down and watched it too, and they liked it as well.  My one friend isn't even big into horror and he loved this.  This is only sort of a horror movie, but I really don't want to say anymore than that though...you just need to watch it for yourselves.  I'm a big fan of zombie movies/shows, and I think this is one of only few other sorta horror type movies that I have liked about as well as many of the zombie movies/shows that I love.  Just as an FYI for those of you sensitive to it, there is some heavy gore in parts, so you might want to avoid this, but for those of you like me who aren't phased by this and perhaps even enjoy gore fests, definitely give this movie a watch straight away if you haven't already!  Don't read into stuff too much about it before you watch, because then you'll enjoy it more.  It's good throughout, but the last half an hour is just simply out of control...I love it!

reviewText: The Cabin in the Woods took a very unique approach to the slasher film genre in which teenage revelers characteristically meet their fates at the hands of inbred, scythe-bearing psychopaths in remote, wooded areas.  Those films are generally bad and predictable, but this one was a little different.  It wasn't great, but it was unique and interesting enough to get one more star than I would likely have given it otherwise.  It is kind of like "Friday the 13th" meets "The Cube" meets "House of 13 Ghosts," with a bit of comedy thrown in a la "Scream."  If you don't like those films you won't like this one; but if you enjoyed any of those you might give this a shot, particularly if you have nothing else going on Saturday night and there's no MMA to watch.

reviewText: If someone unexposed to horror films from the past 35 years or so were to watch a marathon of several of these films back to back (and let's say none of them were sequels), how many would it take before he or she began to predict what's going to happen next? For an American film audience culture that has by now endured the irony-heavy Scream franchise and the gloomily unironic spate of "torture porn" from auteurs like Eli Roth and others, can there truly be any genuine shocks in horror anymore? "Cabin in the Woods" film attempts to answer that question with a wink and a nod.In the 1980s modern classic "Fright Night", Roddy MacDowall's hammy veteran of vampire films makes a self-aware observation that informs the proceedings of "Cabin":  "Nobody wants to see vampire killers... or vampires (anymore)... Apparently all they want to see are demented madmen running around in ski-masks, hacking up young virgins.""Cabin" features five college-aged protagonists, each fitting a certain stock cliché to be found in assorted horror films: the jock/de facto leader (Chris Hemsworth ), the dumb blonde (Anna Hutchison), the nerd/token minority (Jesse Williams), the druggie (Fran Kranz) and the nice girl (Kristin Connolly.) The (slight) twist is, not all of the characters inhabit these roles from the get-go, but are manipulated into them.A creepy gas station attendant (is there any other kind?) gives an oblique warning (to the students and the audience) as the quintet heads up to the titular cabin for a weekend of unsupervised fun. Before the film is over, threads from Deliverance, Friday the 13th, Ju-On/The Grudge and more are touched on in various depths. The "Saw" films, which are already on their seventh (or is that VIIth?) installment, are also clipped for some thematic DNA.The film was co-written by Joss Whedon ("Marvel's The Avengers") and directed by Drew Goddard--the latter of whom wrote and/or directed several episodes of Whedon's "Buffy" and "Angel" TV series as well as the conspiracy-heavy TV drama Lost. Both collaborators bring a satirical sensibility to this horror entry. Cabin reveals its core conceit in its opening scenes (though less-knowing viewers may be hard-pressed to connect the dots early on), and so perhaps the film has less bite (pun intended) than it would have were it to wait until later. Still, the twists, when they happen, are more intriguing than draining, especially by the climax, which manages to be nihilistic and liberating at the same time."Cabin" functions as a witty indictment and an apology of sorts for the clichés of contemporary horror cinema and the slasher subgenre in particular. Depending on how cynical the viewer is, the only way to really ruin this experience--would be to have a sequel.
summary: Blood and Lore:  A Revisionist Take on Scary Films

reviewText: I'll admit, it took me quite awhile to realize I was watching a sort of horror classic in "Cabin in the Woods". The reviews were all over the map; some went the Pavlov's Dog route and saluted while salivating, while others decried this unquestionably original (and yes, cynical) thriller as typical of this smug, disconnected generation. I found myself leaning toward the latter until the last half hour just blew me away. In fact, so wonderfully outlandish and unpredictable was the film's third act that I was forced to re-appraise my initial misgivings.Sure, you got your sexy couples heading to spend a wild weekend at the oh-too-familiar Cabin. But the filmmakers decide to let us in on the little in-joke up front: these ready and randy teenagers just happen to be unaware participants in a brand new Reality TV show (apparently taking place in the not too distant future, where genuine decapitations and actual sexual intercourse are par for the course on modern networks). I knew that much going into the film, and frankly, it didnt sound too enticing. In fact, it sounded highly predictable and tedious. Thankfully, and not for the first time, I was wrong.To give out much more would make me the cruelest of spoilers. Let's just say that the clueless kids refuse to follow the stereotypical guidelines for horror flicks, and more importantly, the TV executives have far deeper intentions than simply garnering ratings. "Cabin in the Woods" is extremely gory, with plenty of lewd sexual content, so listen up, children: don't watch this with your parents. They could turn into major bummers halfway through. Haha.Once this rollercoaster is blasting downhill, you become aware that no matter how they decide to end it, you're gonna see a climax unlike any other you've ever experienced. Thankfully, the director and screenwriters took the right track all the way down, because the film's final scene is simulateously shocking, staggering, hilarious, and horrifying. Enjoy!
summary: Strap in for a wild ride...

reviewText: A Cabin in the Woods is the best comedy horror since Tucker and Dale vs Evil, and unlike T&DvE; the title is totally misleading as if this is another 'kids get picked off one by one' flick. You meet five stereotypes, the jock, the nerd, the slut, the stoner, and of course the virgin, and besides the nerd they all played their respective stereotypes very tongue in cheek, the stoner being my personal favorite. The whole time they're setting up their trip to the woods you see two white collar's watching/commentating on the whole thing, the Cabin in the Woods is like a reality show where the employees who orchestrated the whole thing start placing bets, and provide a hilarious commentary on the whole thing like two longtime horror fans. Really this whole setup is ingenious and it's hard to really explain more because it all gets so batsh** crazy near the end, so I'll leave it at here and just say you should see it, RIGHT NOW!Cabin in the Woods really works mostly because it throws so many movie boundaries out the window and goes off the deep end, the main 'cabin in the woods' story wraps itself up so quickly it really made me realize how much unnecessary padding is in most of those movies. There was a scene where a character pushes a button and from that point on I was grinning like an idiot the whole rest of the movie, the whole thing felt like it was 40 minutes that's how much fun this movie is. It sure isn't perfect, it's too crazy to be a stellar movie but for what it is it delivers in spades.

reviewText: This is one of those post-modern deconstructed movies that's almost too clever for its own good and almost every criticism of the film can be explained by its dedication to or subversion of the genre. Horror fans will enjoy the nods to classic movies that occur in almost every scene but anyone watching it cold will probably wonder what all the critical acclaim was about.The film starts at some mysterious government facility looking to do something fairly evil things at a remote location involving some teenagers. Our main characters are extremely wooden, one-dimensional school kids (who all look like 30) and quickly establish their character types in single scenes (nerd, jock, innocent, etc.) The dialog is so purely driven by exposition that I can't decide whether Joss Whedon is making a brilliant reference to the genre or just got bored trying to set up our zombie bait.Every single horror motif is shoe-horned into the first half from the harbinger ("Don't go to the house, you'll die!") to the 'sex means death' routine that guarantees getting naked will result in a bloody, untimely demise. Meanwhile the evil organization behind the cabin is manipulating events for reasons that don't get explained until later on.*** Potential spoilers ahead ***I enjoyed the film but found the choice of monster was banal, especially given the variety of creatures available once the main plot device is exposed. I've seen enough zombies in the last five years to be completely done with them (and clearly none of the cast ever watched the Walking Dead since they're pretty bad at killing them off). The last 20 minutes starts to get increasingly ludicrous and becomes a splatter-fest with pretty bad CGI and minimum suspense. There's a token appearance at the end by Sigourney Weaver who has to reel off some bad lines of dialog - it's a waste of a great actress.*** End spoilers ***Overall, CITW is an enjoyable, fun film for horror fans but not particularly cohesive. It's not as clever as Scream was at poking fun at itself but it's still leagues ahead of much of the horror I've seen in the last few years.

reviewText: EDIT: I'm enjoying getting to know the cross-section of the people who loved this film and the people who hated it here on Amazon. A lot of the positive reviews are well-written with proper spelling and punctuation. The one-star/two-star reviews are mostly "LOL THIS movie TOTALLY RETARD". Kinda makes you think, doesn't it?Onto the film though. It is almost impossible to talk about how unbelievably awesome THE CABIN IN THE WOODS is without spoiling it. There's so much that goes on within the film that is incredibly important to how special, unique and flat-out brilliant the concept of this film is that to write a review of it without giving those parts away, so I won't even try. And there are enough reviews that go into non-spoiler territory about the specifics, so mostly I write this to share my thoughts.Sadly, because of the seeming disconnect between the critical raves for this film and the target audience for this film, this film was something of a box-office failure (it really underperformed), but I can practially guarantee that this film will have the most rabid cult horror following since the EVIL DEAD films.This is where marketing a film poorly can make or break a film based on how it's presented. Watching the commercials and trailers, it focuses strictly on the horror elements that the film is, at least in part, thumbing its nose at. When the walls of the mystery break down further and further as the remaining characters go further down the rabbit hole, this becomes less of a horror film and more of a forced examination of the tropes of the entire horror genre. Marketing the film this way, on the more gore and sex aspects of the film, will get casual horror fans in the door, but with a CinemaScore of C (D+ amongst females) and a Rotten Tomatoes score of 93% at the time of its release in March 2012 (as of right now, in October of 2012, it's fallen to a 91%...), there seems to be a massive difference in what true fans of the genre who tend to look at things with a more critical eye and casual moviegoers are seeing in this film. This was also indicitive of myself and my wife seeing the film. I loved it; my wife, someone who casually enjoys Whedon's work and is more of a casual moviegoer, did not love it.It's very rare to see this kind of disconnect. Usually with genre films, if the critics enjoy it, most moviegoers will enjoy it too. However it's Roger Ebert who stated it best in his review, calling this film "a fanboy's final exam". That is very true of THE CABIN IN THE WOODS. While this is a film that is meant to entertain all, it is much more aimed at the moviegoers who are fed up with the horror genre and the constant recycling of films, whether they are the endless parade of sequels, witless retcons, and a slew of American remakes of Japanese Horror films (which this film HILARIOUSLY satirizes in a small but important subplot).It's also important to realize that this film was originally made back in 2009, and was in pre-production when many of the horror films coming out were of the so-called "torture porn" sub-genre as well as sequels to remakes and sequels to Americanized remakes, but it's remarkable how timely this film still is. Many of the trappings of modern horror cinema have extended to the current market to the point of unintentional parody, and now, we have them with the "benefit" of 3D, which unless the film is shot in 3D, looks terrible by all accounts when it's post-converted, and is a trend that I am very surprised that hasn't died out yet. So with all of this going on, there was a lot for horror fans like Whedon and Goddard to hate.EDIT: I realized that I haven't talked too much about the technical and artisan-style prowess of the filmmakers. Joss Whedon is a one-of-a-kind. There's a reason that people refer to his style of dialogue as "Joss-Speak". It's incredibly witty and whip-smart. He's absolutely not a lowest-common-denominator writer. The idea of these kids, who are all intelligent despite how the events in the film conspire to make them into cliches, having all of this wit is a little hyper-realistic, and that's part of the nature of Joss-Speak. It's like David Mamet, and no, I'm not comparing the two as artists, but the nature of their dialogue requires a certain ear. Most people who find this film's dialogue awful are not familiar with Whedon as a creative force, and it can be a little grating if you're hearing it for the first time. Drew Goddard is from the Whedon School if you will, being weaned on shows like BUFFY and ANGEL, and then moving on to shows like LOST and films like CLOVERFIELD. As a co-writer, you can tell that these two have a rhythm that compliment each other. Goddard is also a surprisingly good director. He knows more than enough on how he needed to construct this film in order to get the maximum impact, whether for the scarier or the funnier or the more human moments. The creature effects are largely loving tributes to many great creatures of the history of horror. Many of them are surprisingly done practically as opposed to using primarily CGI (with a few obvious exceptions). And for those of you who have seen it, I just have one word for you: Unicorn.It's important to understand that I am personally not a fanboy of horror films. I love a great horror film that transcends the genre. I love Carpenter's THE THING, Cronenberg's THE FLY, Landis's AN AMERICAN WEREWOLF IN LONDON, Friedkin's THE EXORCIST (and THE EXORCIST III), Romero's NIGHT OF THE LIVING DEAD and so on. For me, the last great horror films I saw were Frank Darabont's THE MIST (2007) and Tomas Alfredson's LET THE RIGHT ONE IN (2009). Before that, it was Neil Marshall's THE DESCENT in 2006. That's three really great horror films in the course of four years (unless you consider CLOVERFIELD a horror film, which I don't). After that came a whole lotta nothin'; at least until THE CABIN IN THE WOODS.The film that this is getting the most comparison to is Wes Craven's SCREAM and that franchise. It's mainly for two reasons: First is because of the cleverness and wit of the horror tale told within, and second is because of how 'meta' both of these films are. I know that 'meta' is a term that gets thrown around quite a bit in genre entertainment right now, and is as easily applicable to this film as well as the films of the SCREAM franchise. These are films where the horror doesn't just stay within the film, but the films are about horror films as well. SCREAM ushered in, for at least a while, a great metatextual discussion about the tropes of the slasher sub-genre and the idea of the sequel. While the conversation continued throughout the third and fourth films, the quality decreased once the third film hit. Both THE CABIN IN THE WOODS and the SCREAM franchise clearly love the horror genre but both felt that things had continued for too long in the same direction and something so new had to come along. SCREAM came along right at the right time, and you could feel its influence in so many other horror films that came after. THE CABIN IN THE WOODS, judging by its lack of opening weekend success and its failure to generate the positive word-of-mouth it would've needed to compete with films like THE HUNGER GAMES due to false expectations, will likely not have the same cultural impact amongst the audience and the studios as SCREAM did, and there are a few reasons for this, but the main reason is that this film's only real fault is being too ambitious.While I don't think that's actually a fault, it's currently a reason of another big disconnect between great filmmaking and great box-office. Most people would rather have a double cheeseburger than try a new restaurant, and sometimes that's fine. I like a good double cheeseburger too. The problem, though, is just being satisfied with the same recycled fast-food entertainment over and over, because the market does dictate what things we see and read and consume. Too often, some of the most talented voices in the creative world are silenced before they're every really exposed, and it has more to do with the mass market not being ready for it yet or that people are threatened by the idea of something truly smart. I think films like EVIL DEAD 2 are films that challenge the expectations of the audience watching it and there are those that are in on it, and those that aren't. If EVIL DEAD 2 hadn't gained the following it got on home video, there never would have been ARMY OF DARKNESS five years later, which for a sequel to EVIL DEAD 2, was a pretty successful film. SCREAM is a different animal altogether because it was a great film and it made a lot of money, and by all reason, it shouldn't have. It was more of a confluence of events that made it the blockbuster it was. I'd be very interested to see how this film might have fared back during its original intended release in 2009, because, while not doomed to obscurity, it quickly faded due to the One-Two Punch of THE HUNGER GAMES and Joss Whedon's other brilliant film, THE AVENGERS, hit theaters.During and after the film, I was buzzing with energy and felt something akin to cinematic bliss. And it certainly doesn't hurt that the song playing over the end credits is Nine Inch Nails' "Last", which is the most creative and appropriate use of a NIN song in a film ever (and that includes songs that Trent wrote for films and SE7EN). I knew I had just seen a film that was probably the most entertaining and most invigorating film I had seen in quite some time, and at the same time, I knew that like myself and my wife, it would be polarizing amongst audiences. But what Whedon and Goddard do with this film is frame a debate amongst horror fans, and it's the most exciting debate to have: Do you hope that something different will come along that will try and test your preconceptions about the horror genre, or are you satisfied with the way things are?Many people who come into this film blind, expecting a horror film and are genre fans who are looking for the cinematic equivalent of a quickie ("Give me some boobs, some creative kills and some decent jump scares and I'm good for the night.") are going to be either furious or perplexed. I've found that the people who are supporting this film are more of the "I Love Film" club, because understanding the power Cinema has, you're just falling in love with how effortlessly this film shatters everything you think it would be and instead takes you into a world where anything can, and does happen.
summary: Easily The Most Polarizing Horror Film in Years. And it's AWESOME.

reviewText: 4 Stars = ClassicWhat do you get when you combine "Night of the Living Dead," "The Evil Dead," "Waxwork," "The Truman Show," & a little torture porn Zombies? Why you get "Cabin in the Woods," of course!Yes, yesterday I went to see "Cabin in the Woods," with fully great expectations! I mean, many critics were going GA GA over this film. The movie trailer it's self promised a inventive variation on "Night of the Living Dead" & "The Evil Dead." Well, did it meet my expectations??? Yes, but not, YES!!! I knew going in to the movie that I was going to get a combination of those two films, & sure enough, I did, right down to the Zombies trying to force their way in to the house (btw, these Zombies had more on their minds than eating brains, an ample amout of torture was on their menu! A nod to films like "Hostel."), & the cellar trap door opening all by it's self, ala' "The Evil Dead," with all sorts of goodies to rummage through down there! I knew by watching the trailer, that there was some sort of human intervention pulling the strings to this whole affair, but just not how it all configured, & I won't tell you either. I will tell you, this film is both a homage, & poke-age, right in the ribs, to all the films I mentioned.The first 3/4's of the movie is a very good, though not great, rotted Zombie tongue in cheek tribute to "Night of the Living Dead" & "The Evil Dead," while "The Truman Show" pulled all the strings. The script was funny (Gotta love the Pothead!), the direction sharp, the editing on cue, the makeup was excellent, & the special effects & cinematography made for an atmospheric romp, but not a thrill ride. It was not until the last fourth of the movie, that "Waxwork" came in & weaved it's spell over my old horror movie loving heart, that "Cabin in the Woods" became not just a very good film, but a classic film! All I have to say is, someone let all the monsters out of the zoo, & rampage was the theme of the day! Here the make up & special effects are outstanding, & there was rhyme & reason to all this chaos, but again, I'm not telling.In the end, "Cabin in the Woods" was saved from an enjoyable, but eventually forgettable film, to one that all true horror addicts will love, & will want on their blu-ray players. It's just to bad the first 3/4's of the film were not as maniacal as the last fourth. We would've had at minimum, a minor masterpiece in the horror genre, but horror fans rejoice! We do have a new classic in the over used & abused horror genre, & that in it's self is no small fright!
summary: "Night of the Living Dead," "The Evil Dead," "Waxwork," "The Truman Show," With Torture Porn Zombies!,

reviewText: The Cabin in the Woods, directed by Drew Goddard, tells the story of five college students headed out to a remote cabin for spring break. Like most slasher/horror films, these teens begin to exhibit the standard clichés. But this is all a ruse; deep below the earth, a facility monitored and controlled by a secret organization watches the five from all angles, subjecting them to whatever horrors are released. Will these students survive long enough to uncover the mystery?Drew Goddard and Joss Whedon (creator of Firefly and Dollhouse) crafted a true horror gem with "Cabin," taking all the horror movie clichés and turning them on their heads. Goddard's direction really helps to create the foreboding and eerie atmosphere that is filled with terror, and laughs? That's right. Laughs, and a lot of them. Joss Whedon brings his creative genius with dry, witty humor to the big screen. And while the humor is absolutely hysterical (I died laughing a few times), the scares are there too. The script was cinematic gold. The characters were perfectly written, nothing ever felt rushed or cut-down, and it played out with such skill and admiration for a genre that had become crap, with what Whedon calls "torture porn" (aka, the Saw franchise, the Hostel films, etc.). The Cabin in the Woods is filled with gory violence and kills, too, but at least the film itself has a complex story and intelligent characters. The visual effects, surprisingly, were and still are top-notch for a low-budget film, combining CG and practical effects. The musical score by David Julyan (The Prestige, Insomnia) was superb, and the acting was great, especially Fran Kranz and Richard Jenkins, with Jenkins playing one of the engineers within The Facility.The Cabin in the Woods is easily one of the best horror films of all time not for re-inventing the slasher or what scares it had, but for the mind-bending and thoughtful story that was a homage to H.P. Lovecraft and all great horror films, their creatures and abominations. On a final note: Beware, movie-goer, for your understanding of Unicorns is wrong.5/5 Stars*****
summary: Both Disturbing and Hilarious, and Then Thought-Provoking

reviewText: I cannot begin to express how brilliant this movie is.  I have seen it twice at the movie theaters and could easily see it a third time.  This movie plays upon conventional horror movie stereotypes and also subtley delivers a political message at the same time.  I won't be spoiling much, since what I'm about to point out comes near the beginning of the movie.One of the chief protagonists, Marty, while being driven to a cabin in the woods with his friends, mentions about people putting computer chips in children's heads and that as a result of things like these, society needs to collapse.  We're all just too afraid to let it.  He is of course making a remark about our own increasingly depraved and decaying culture.  This remark is easily overlooked the first time you hear it, but it ultimately serves a major basisfor another observation of Marty's towards the very end of the movie.Some critics have hated the last half hour and especially the last few minutes.  I loved them though as the hellstorm of the last half hour was handled quite well for a horror movie keep in mind and the final few moments force the viewer to question who they should have been rooting for.  The main protagonists are suddenly quite selfish with the scientists being rather underappreciated as unsung heroes.  At the same time though, remember what Marty said in the beginning and also at the end.  After all, the scientists  are extremely similar to the average viewer who goes to see a horror movie.  Watching them is almost like watching ourselves.  They wait to see some teenagers or young adults get slaughtered and also complain if the slut doesn't unbutton her shirt for them/us.  We go to horror movies and especially for this a lot.  Maybe we do need to collapse.

reviewText: This movie is a study on the tired "slasher" genre and must be observed by any fan of horror films. Is the Cabin really a big Rubik's Cube from the Dark City? Well, no. We can't tell you what the Cabin really is, or even where it is. What we can tell is this: They are watching. Japan couldn't cut it, so now we watch the Cabin in the Woods. We observe the five stereotypical lambs approaching their fates. There is but one clue to be known: "The fool will bind them with his Ancient Logic".You, the viewer, might not find much of the film to be scary...but the real horror is mostly on the other side of the mirror (or window?). There are clues abound, but just as much underground as within the Cabin. The fool will prove to be wiser than most, but is Ancient Logic able to solve the Rubik's Cube? Will the Cabin in the Woods determine their fates?!2.342

reviewText: It's widely acknowledged that films within the horror genre can be incredibly formulaic and easily slotted into one of the sub-genres of horror; be it vampire, werewolf, slasher, zombie, you get the idea. So, as I settled in to watch The Cabin in the Woods, I thought from the trailer that I knew what I was letting myself in for. However, this film far surpassed my expectations.The film starts off in typical horror style with a group of friends setting out for a weekend getaway off the beaten track but if you've watched the trailer, you know that this certainly isn't your run-of-the-mill fright flick.Starring Kristen Connolly (The Happening), Chris Hemsworth (Thor, Snow White and The Huntsman, Star Trek), Anna Hutchison, Fran Kranz (Donnie Darko, The Village) and Jesse Williams, the film conforms to the genre norm of having a hot young cast up front to do the running around, drinking, fornicating, screaming and dying horribly; while being ably supported by Richard Jenkins (Let Me In, Wolf), Bradley Whitford (Scent of a Woman, Billy Madison) and Amy Acker (Angel, Catch Me If You Can). Oh, and there's a lovely little cameo near the end that I defy you not to smile at!The events revolving around the cabin are monitored, guided and controlled akin to some dark version of The Truman Show; and if that's where things stopped, The Cabin in the Woods would be a solid horror film worthy of merit. However, there's a far more sinister hand at work behind the scenes than merely providing murderous reality entertainment and it is the parallel plotline of the puppetmasters at work behind the scenes that really starts to set The Cabin in the Woods apart from the rest of the pack.As always, I appreciated the practical effects involved in The Cabin in the Woods but on a critical note, there was a considerable amount of CGI. In my opinion, the CG effects were only used where necessary in all but a few scenes.The Cabin in the Woods is the brainchild of Drew Goddard and Joss Whedon. The two have collaborated for years together on the likes of Buffy the Vampire Slayer and the Angel TV series; a fact which shines through here. The wise-ass humour, characters and general feel of proceedings all seems very familiar stylistically but I would suggest that this is no bad thing.For some, horror films are now all about how grotesque the next torture scene is or how diabolical the situation the hapless protagonists find themselves in. That's very much not the case with The Cabin in the Woods. This film, to my mind, is a veritable love letter to the genre and there's more than one nod to various films; the titular cabin and its set-up are a little reminiscent of The Evil Dead to name one. Additionally, I could not help but feel that the film was acting as a bit of a mirror, showing the viewer how desensitised to horror they had become by having the characters demonstrate this on-screen and on that note, I will say no more about the plot and its intricacies, for fear of robbing the movie of its true potential.I've tried hard to think of another horror movie that has been so incisive within the genre and all I can think of is Wes Craven's Scream; taking the stereotypical cast of a teen slasher flick and throwing an entirely novel element into the mix, creating a heady brew and some strong horror entertainment indeed.

reviewText: The Cabin in the Woods follows a group of college friends that decide to spend the weekend at an isolated cabin in the woods; but, they don't know that they are being manipulated by a secret group into following a scenario for their own agenda. The Cabin in the Woods is a creative and original horror film that effectively blends some dark humor and satirizes the genre.The story is unique and entertaining; the concept is executed perfectly. It starts off by introducing the college students and the secret organization. The technicians are hilarious, while the students are very generic, and this is obviously on purpose; we have the jock, the bimbo, the stoner, etc. basically the characters you'd expect from a film based on a cabin in the woods. We also have scenes that poke fun at the genre, like the stop at the mysterious, abandoned-like gas station. It's not a pure-breed horror film, but it balances the jokes and scares very well. My favorite part of the film was the final sequence when the monsters are loose in the facility; we see nightmarish creatures causing havoc like killer clowns, werewolves, zombies, and a pinhead style creature but with saws instead of pins (sawhead, maybe?). This final sequence was exhilarating and frightening at the same time and beautifully shot. The actual ending was also amazing and broke the formula we've seen hundreds of times. The acting was great, the special effects were great, the music was amazing, and the story was thoroughly entertaining.Overall, The Cabin in the Woods is a unique horror film that effectively blends some humor; it moves at a very fast pace and is a very entertaining film. I highly recommend this film, if you're not a big fan of horror-comedy movies then I recommend a rental.The Cabin in the Woods has strong violence and gore, and some nudity. (one scene in the woods.)
summary: A Creative and Original Horror Film....

reviewText: Holy crap. I'm not normally a fan of gore porn slasher movies, but I just watched "The Cabin in the Woods", and it's like HP Lovecraft, James Joyce, and Robert A. Wilson all got together to create a satire of the early 21st Century as directed by Brian DiPalma. It defies and exceeds expectations by transcending any categorization. Nothing is prohibited, everything is permitted -- and anything can happen, but this universe still has rules, and watching the unlikely heroes finally figure out those rules is a big part of the fun.Did I mention that this movie is actually a love story? 'Cause yeah, by the end it is...It's a friggin' joyride of a meta movie, and it skewers modern culture at the same time that it calls back to some of the most influential literature of the last century. And it pulls a double pop culture callback through its casting, as well -- keep your eyes particularly upon a certain major character who pops up in the last few minutes and a certain one who... um... hits the wall, so to speak.Anyway.... I thought that it was impossible to still do smart storytelling through genre films. I was wrong. I give this film two thumbs up, five stars, and a big fat "wow."

reviewText: (Possible Spoilers)So 5 friends decide to go on a trip to a remote location to stay in a cabin for a weekend, while going there the run into the typical old gas station owner who warns them about what will happen if they go up to the cabin (without actually ever saying it of course). Once at the cabin there's music, partying, then a bump from the cellar that causes them to go investigate and from there the trip turns deadly as they begin experiencing plenty of horrifying things.All of this sounds like your basic horror fare, but in this movie its played for laughs mostly as all of the things going on in and around the general vicinity of the cabin are controlled by a team of people in a bunker type TV studio where the employees even take bets on what cliche the people in the cabin will do next. Its of course very cheesy in its presentation but thanks to Joss Whedon (Creator of TV's "Buffy The Vampire Slayer" and director of "The Avengers") who helped write this, a lot of what goes on his fresh and the concept while goofy is fun to see unfold.The cast includes Chris Hemsworth ("Thor"), the beautiful Kristen Connonlly ("The Bay"), Richard Jenkins ("Let Me In") and others mos of which are the cardboard cut out horror cliches characters. The concept is quite good, even if it gets pretty goofy towards the end, I still highly recommend this flick as its just plain fun, especially if you like comedy/horror films. *** out of 4 stars.

reviewText: I was expecting to see a horror movie when I went to see this.  But I got something else.  Something much more interesting.  Don't get me wrong, there were parts that were frightening.  Well, that were meant to be.  I never jumped or got scared at all.  What I got was a story that told me a lot while at the same time leaving me wishing I could see more.  I do not want to give anything away.  So I will only say that some people go to a cabin.  Once there the choices they make may determine their fate.  If the fate it not met, worse thing may be in their future.  VERY interesting.  I think it would make a cool anime or comic.  There was one part with nudity.  Not much at all.  There was some language as well.  It really didn't have as much gore as I thought.  There was one part that was gory.  But like a lot of the things that happen in this movie, I found myself laughing.  Not because it was stupid.  Just the way things happened.  If you are going to see this movie because you want to see horror or gore, you better chose a different movie, but if you want to see an interesting idea with a bit of death, this is a movie that you will enjoy.Something else I would like to add.  There are movies like Saw that lay on the gore.  Making people die in far to exaggerated ways.  This movie didn't really do that.  Don't get me wrong, things get very weird, but it was not a movie with blood, blood, blood.  Maybe at one part, but I was glad to see it was not that type of movie.  I should save myself here.  There is blood.  At the end there is a lot.  But, all the times people die, it is almost comedic.  I laughed the entire time.  It was a weird, cool movie.  Check it out.

reviewText: Hey guys let's grab and even-ish number of attractive young adults and go party for a weekend in my isolated country cabin. *yawn seen it*Hey guys let's explore this mysteriously creepy cabin. *yawn seen it*Hey guys creepy things are trying to kill us in this cabin. *yawn seen it*Hadley: [sighs] These freaking zombies. Remember when you could just throw a girl in a volcano?*Wait! WTF they've seen it too?*Hadley: I am never gonna see a merman. Ever.Sitterson: Dude, be thankful. Those things are terrifying. And the cleanup on them is a nightmare.*Laugh Out Loud!*This movie takes the ultimate jab at itself but at the same time gives its own justification (brilliant).If you've ever wondered why a group of young adults have to die when they visit a scary situation: old cabin, scary mansion, old factory.  This movie cleverly legitimatizes it.This movie would actually get a 4.5 in my books, it has just about everything to be entertaining in one way or another.The comedy is dark but spot on and clever in execution.The story attempts to be plausible (for the situation) I have to tip my hat to that.The action (yes action) is exciting and well executed with unexpected results.The because of all of the above horror is over shadowed. I wasn't as scared as I thought I would be and I think this is because the pacing was so fast. It took this movie more into the action genre then horror. Hence the 4/5.I loved the verity of creepy monsters in the movie. It put a danger scale on the each of the monsters which was much appreciated and really added to the tension.However I HATED some of the CGI on some of the monsters ... it just made em look cartoonish and really brought me out of the atmosphere. To be honest they didn't even need to show the full bodies if they where going to use CGI, quick flashes and blood splatters would have sufficed.All in all it was a fun ride and I hope to see more movies like this.If they refine it a little more they can add a whole new dimension to the horror movie genre.
summary: Fun Fun Fun and a bit stupid.

reviewText: and falls flat. I was completely bored. I had absolutely no preconceptions before watching, I had seen no trailers, didn't know who was in it, just the passing comment from a friend that it was "supposed to be awesome." I didn't even read blurb on the back of the case. (if I had, I probably never would have watched it. Maybe. Chris Hemsworth, ya know?) I admit, I thought I was getting a horror movie. Instead, it was mostly a snooze fest. Sometimes you can throw a bunch of tropes into a film and twist them to be awesome (ie, Tucker and Dale vs Evil). Other times you end up with a lame trope-filled movie. Snappy dialogue and a great cast doesn't save this movie. I don't know where it is supposed to take place, but I'm guessing West Virginia.**********Spoilers***********Ok, first we have the Scooby Gang: Fred, Daphne, Thelma, Shaggy, and Scooby Doo, in an RV, going on a trip. Seriously, all hawt guy Chris Hemsworth needs is a purple ascot. Daphne is played by just-dyed-her-hair-blonde (lol) Anna Hutchison, Thelma by Kristen Connolly, Shaggy by Fran Kranz, and Scooby by Jesse Williams. (It did not escape my notice the only dark skinned guy in the group has the role of the dog. Just sayin.) These complete idiots (they are drugged somehow to become this way) are predictably killed one-by-one in yawn inducing fashion. Along the way to a "vacation" cabin, they stop by a dilapidated gas station, where they are (kinda) warned off by an old man who is later used for lolz and never seen again. The Mystery Machine drives through a tunnel next to a vertigo-inducing ravine, finally arriving so there can be some bikini shots and thought-provoking (not) oddities revealed. It's downhill from there. (while I guessed there would be zombies, I missed that they would be redneck cultist zombies.)I was caught off guard when the villain is finally revealed (sort of) at the end. I admit I didn't see that one coming.The over-the-top betting on outcomes, yelling at a screen "Lemme see the boobies" etc, was WAY too much disregard for fellow human beings.  Why do the bad guys fail? Because they are unprofessional morons. Even Fred (Buffy reference, lol), played by Amy Acker, couldn't pull these guys from the brink. Her role appeared to exist to be ridiculed by the village idiots. Because she's female, I assume. Or maybe she was an intern? who knows. I think the film showed way too much of the other side. Sometimes less really is more. (did anyone else feel sorry for "Pinhead"? He looked so sad, like his puppy had just died, and he really, REALLY, needed a hug.)I thought this movie just tried too hard to be... something. It failed miserably. I think it would have done much better if the villains had been thwarted at every turn by the genius-level college kids who have defied their stereotypes. (ie, bad guy says to other bad guy "What the hell do you mean they're going to college to be doctors and economics experts? I told you to find some idiots!) I mean, who sees the outcome of "all the victims live"? OK, so they would have died at the end, but still.One star for the ending& the sheer blasphemy of the film, one star for having Chris Hemsworth in the cast. A little Thor makes everything a little better. :)

reviewText: I am not a true fan of the horror genre, but this one intrigued me. I suspected from the trailers that it wasn't your usual slice 'em and dice 'em horror flick, so I got it and watched it - twice.For me, what made the difference was the story. It actually had one. And it was quite ingenious as well. There were a few holes in it, like how did they really get this cabin in the first place, but when a story is good, I can always suspend belief. The entertainment industry as a whole, often forces us to suspend belief in many movies and shows. If I start telling the story here, I will give away too much of the treats this movie dishes out from the beginning. Let me just say, it is horror, so if blood and gore is not your thing, you probably won't like this one. But, if you aren't put off by it, there are juicy rewards at the end of this movie that separates it from the rest of the mindless horror flicks out there.I recommend this with the caveat that you aren't squeamish and easily frightened. It is that rare horror movie that is actually entertaining, with a good story overall. It won't win awards, but it is surprisingly satisfying for a genre loaded with bad movies. I really liked it. Good cast, smart script, decent acting, and worth paying for if you are in the mood for an hour and a half or so of escapism entertainment. Great popcorn movie with friends! Not for the under 16 crowd, though. Keep the kiddies away from this one. Definitely adult fun here!

reviewText: I have really come to hate the torture porn that horror movies have become. Going into this film, knowing Joss and Drew (former Buffy and Angel writer) were behind it,  I had guessed this would be a satirical mind game. And boy was I not wrong. The entire first half you think they totally ripped off the Evil Dead, and then it turns everything "horror" on its head. I loved the set up of the architypes. The Whore (Anna Hutchison) The Athlete (Chris Hemsworth) The Scholar (Jesse Williams) The Fool (Fran Kranz) and The Virgin (Kristen Connolly), but when we first meet them we learn that Jules (Hutchison) isn't all that whore-like and Curt (Hemsworth) is at college on an ACADEMIC scholarship and that Dana (Connolly) isn't even a virgin. It's all about how society wouuld conceptualize them. The acting is brilliant, Bradley Whitford and Richard Jenkins are hilarious and Whedon favorite Amy Acker brings a sense of reality while acting opposite those two. Hemsworth and Hutchison have a real down to earth chemistry about them and Williams brings warmth and light to a role that could have easily been overshadowed. But the real star of this is the hilariously high and perfectly disheveled Fran Kranz as Marty. He's a cross between Scooby and Shaggy. He's so funny and yet so loyal to this group of friends even though it's clear he is the fifth wheel. Every scene he's in he manages to steal. Real bright future for him ahead.All in all this typical, non typical "horror" film will leave you with the biggest sense of WTF? While also making you feel all tingly inside with hope that maybe this well loved genre will have it's rebirth.

reviewText: For fans of Buffy, Angel, Firefly and Dollhouse, or Rosanne, Parenthood, Toy Story and Titan AE, this is both a treat and a sigh of relief that the great master of supernatural-suspense-horror-dark-comedy-humor is not only here to stay, but he's still got it.Five college aged friends, all representing horror archetypes, enter a world between good and evil while believing they are going to...a...cabin...in the...woods. Ghosts. Witchcraft. Monsters. Prophecy. Magic, and everything in between, it's all real. Stranger still, it's all organized into a technologically advanced and devious corporation that's modernized sacrifice and death.You will see a plethora of Whedon alums as well some seasoned bonafide vets, such as Bradley Whitford, Richard Jenkins and Sigourney Weaver.The basic concept is creative enough, though for some reason, kind of reminds me of the movieCube...but it's predictable. That's not necessarily a bad thing. It's just predictable and doesn't make for anything as scary as I've seen Whedon do in his other works. Whedon gives us what we expect in a typical horror movie with some campy fun and tries to spice it up but it sort of loses its glamour half way though. Was I riveted? Not as much as I'd hoped but it was worth a watch.

reviewText: With geek god Joss Whedon (creator of TV's Buffy and Firefly among other fan favorites) on board, it's fair to say that the expectations for "The Cabin in the Woods" were quite high for enthusiasts of the horror genre. Here he shares a writing credit with the film's director Drew Goddard and the result is one of the year's more entertaining experiments. I truly think that this is a film that will suffer due to those that are willing to discuss too many of the plot points in advance, so I'll be brief in my actual descriptions. I will say this, though, the less you know about the movie--the more fun you can have. In my opinion, even the advertising campaign and trailers hint at too much. You know from the start that this isn't your typical fright fest. Instead, what is served plays up and skewers every horror movie cliche imaginable. It is both hip and witty, as well as smarter than it has any right to be. It twists movie conventions around in clever new ways and makes something that seems remarkably fresh and different. And if you're a fan of horror movies, this is simply fun, fun, fun.Of course, we all know the genre of movies that involve a cabin in the woods (or other appropriately desolate place). Let's get a car full of kids, strand them, and then start picking them off in increasingly creative ways. At the start, that's exactly the scenario that "The Cabin in the Woods" sets up. We meet five standard character archetypes for these type of films: the jock (Chris Hemsworth), the stoner (Fran Kranz), the good girl (Kristen Connolly), the vixen (Anna Hutchison) , and the scholar (Jesse Williams). After a brief bit of character introduction, we're off to the woods. As they settle in, each rises to their individual stereotype. First there's drunken revelry, then there's the discovery of a very spooky basement, and then mayhem ensues. What's going on and can anyone survive? If you've seen the trailers, however, (and if not, this is also included as the first scenes in the movie) you know that there is something more complex at work behind the scenes. But that's all you get from me. Let's just say that the film turns into a post-modern game as much as a traditional horror endeavor.The film really works on several levels. It's funny without being overly precious. It always knowingly involves the audience in its sense of gamesmanship. The fact that we have more information than the characters (but not everything, of course) makes us complicit in an enjoyable voyeuristic experience. And yet, there are plenty of scares and surprises in store. "The Cabin in the Woods" has relatively moderate goals, it just wants to put on a good show. The ending pushes quite far and is deliriously over-the-top. It may not stand up to much intellectual scrutiny, but I didn't care. I was just along for the ride. This may not necessarily be considered among the "best" movies of the year, but it is easily one of the more entertaining ones. And in that way, Whedon and Goddard have honored horror movie fans everywhere. For sheer entertainment, about 4 1/2 stars. KGHarris, 5/12.
summary: Turning Horror Movie Cliches Into A Twisty Post-Modern Game: Beware Of Spoilers And Enjoy

reviewText: I went into "Cabin in the Woods" with zero expectations. I tried to stay as far away from the hype machine as possible. I avoided all trailers and tv spots, I didn't read a single review, and I didn't watch a single interview with any of the cast or crew. I wanted this movie going experience to be as "pure" as possible. All I knew going in was that it was written by Joss Whedon (creator of "Buffy the Vampire Slayer") and it featured a college aged cast trapped in a cabin...in the woods. Seriously, that's all I knew going into the film. I didn't want to know the twists and the turns. I know what expectations can do to a person and I know especially what it can do to a horror fan. So into the movie I went with a clear head ready for a new tale of terror. Let the carnage begin!"Cabin in the Woods" begins with five college students driving out for a vacation to a remote cabin in the woods. Among the group we have the beautiful and slightly "impure" Dana (Kristen Connolly) along with her attractive hunky jock boyfriend Curt (Chris Hemsworth). We have the plain but pretty Jules (Anna Hutchison) who is being set up for a date with book smart boy-next-door Holden (Jesse Williams). Along as the fifth wheel is the punchline stoner Marty (Fran Kranz). That's all I'm going to tell you. Giving away what happens before or after this event will most likely hinder your enjoyment of the movie. All I can say is that some will die, some may live, and there is plenty of blood to be sprayed all around.If there is one thing that has to be said for "Cabin in the Woods" it is that it has a ton of ambition. Far more so than any other horror movie I've seen in years. The "twist" (which I refuse to give away even though many, many trailers and reviews have) is very clever and ingenious in concept. Like other "meta" horror movies, I enjoyed the references "Cabin in the Woods" made to past horror movies (particularly those in the slasher genre). However, that is where my love for the movie both began and ended. I thought this movie was a bit of a mess with no real follow through and an ending that was just lazy screenwriting. I appreciated the concept behind this movie (which, again, I don't want to give too much away so I am being deliberately vague) but found the execution lacking. I also hated pretty much all of the characters and the "comic" relief felt flat to me. I couldn't wait for the "stoner" character to die and the less said about that, the better.I can understand and appreciate why people love this horror movie. It's something different. It isn't PG-13 and it isn't a remake. Nonetheless, I was left quite cold. This film attempts to be a clever horror-comedy packed with meta self awareness. Clever it is. Funny or scary? Not so much. This film is being billed as "Scream" for the next generation. That it is not. "Scream", for all its meta self awareness was both scary and funny as hell. Everything and everyone associated with this picture appear to either be trying far too hard or not enough, I'm not exactly sure which. I know I am in the minority here so if you have a desire to see this film by all means go out there and enjoy the hell out of it. I wanted to and didn't. I appreciate it when any horror movie gets recognition and acclaim. I love to see horror movies that make people fall in love with genre again. If I didn't fall in love with this one, that shouldn't stop you.
summary: It's Not What You Think It Is...

reviewText: Only Drew Goddard and Joss Whedon could make a movie like this. Written by both and directed by Drew Goddard, this movie defies all expectations in its satire of slasher films and torture porn. In what is described as an attempt to "revitalize" the genre, Joss Whedon and Drew Goddard create a brilliant satire of that very same genre, one that can truly be appreciated by anyone (but especially horror fans), albeit a not very scary one.The movie follows four college-aged students who decided to take a weekend trip to a cabin to get away. Dana Polk (Kristen Connolly) is the protagonist here (although even her role is looked at in a very satirical way, as is every character), joined by the jock Curt Vaughan (Chris Hemsworth), his girlfriend Jules Louden (Anna Hutchinson), the stoner Marty Mikalski, and the intelligent and nice guy Holden McCrea (Jesse Williams). The casts is also rounded out by the workers who seem to be pulling the strings (their existence is no spoiler, as their role is seen and heavily implied from the beginning of the film, but for those who don't know much, I will avoid spilling as much as I can), the technicians Gary Stitterson (Richard Jenkins) and Steve Hadley (Bradley Whitford), the security guard Daniel Truman (Brian White), and the chemical technician Wendy Lin (Amy Acker).The plot of the movie takes some interesting turns throughout the movie as the purpose of the cabin is explained. Without saying anything, this movie has a wholly unique and meta premise that brings the satire in full force. There's a reason that only these two writers could make a movie like this, it's full of their unique brand of storytelling and complete love and understanding of horror films. The movie is consistently brilliant in its satire: the five characters are built to be obvious stereotypes of horror movie characters (in fact, the movie references them itself: the Athlete, the Whore, the Fool, the Scholar, and the Virgin) while at the same time playing with the truth in these stereotypes, characters who make smart decisions are then influenced to make dumb ones (the trailer highlights on of the best moments in reference to the concept of splitting up), and many more moments truly show an understanding of the various tropes that exist in these films. Nothing escapes this movie's intelligent and affectionate satire of the genre, and it goes a long way towards enjoying the movie. This alone is why this movie is highly recommended to anyone who loves horror films and anyone who also berates them for their lack of intelligence and originality. Both groups will find this movie to speak to them perfectly.Only, a few problems still exist in the film, albeit small ones that won't detract too much from the experience. The film will really only appeal to the aforementioned groups. Casual fans and anyone just looking for a scare will be wholly disappointed. Despite this movie's obvious love for horror films, it just isn't that scary. The slasher moments don't last a lot of the film, and the scares here are few and far between. The movie focuses much more on parodying the genre than it does actually being a part of the genre. This film will also not amaze anyone with its acting. Not to say the acting isn't good, but it just doesn't stand out too much. The actors and really aren't given a whole lot of chance to stretch their skills anyways, since the movie's focus is so strongly on its writing (which is not necessarily a bad thing, since it is the film's biggest strength).Overall, this is not necessarily a pinnacle of the slasher film genre, and most likely not one to "revitalize" it as the Goddard and Whedon may have hoped. However, this is still an extremely smart film that will be enjoyed by anyone who can appreciate the affection satire. This movie parodies and makes fun of all of the typical tropes of horror films so brilliantly without losing the obvious love it has for them. Still, it will mostly only be enjoyed for that, as the movie is not particularly scary or thrilling otherwise.
summary: A brilliantly plotted but not very scary horror film.

reviewText: I wanted to see The Cabin in the Woods back when it was in theaters.  But every time I went to the movies during that time period I was with someone else.  And they never wanted to see a horror movie, either because horror was too scary or because they considered it a dumb and predictable genre.  (And let's face it, I'm not about to accuse slasher films of being smart.  Their feelings were not invalid.)  But The Cabin in the Woods is not a horror film.  There's about 45 minutes of a slasher film in it, but it isn't really scary and I don't think it's meant to be.  It's mostly a horror parody, with a pinch of satire thrown in for flavor.The Cabin in the Woods is the product of Joss Whedon (Buffy the Vampire Slayer) and Drew Goddard (Cloverfield).  They both wrote the script and Goddard directed.  I can definitely see Whedon's mark on the story, so if you don't like his style, The Cabin in the Woods probably won't work for you.  I am totally unfamiliar with Goddard, but this film was a great first impression.  There's one scene, where a character goes out into the woods and looks over his shoulder, because it is a little creepy outside.  The audience can see the monster weaving in and out of the shadows, but the character just misses her.  It's beautifully framed.  And I can say that for several scenes in this movie - the way things move in and out of frame is very well done.One thing The Cabin in the Woods does very well is that it doesn't fight the cast's charisma.  In too many horror films you just don't care if everyone dies or if anyone escapes the monster.  Chris Hemsworth is the movie's only big name (though he wasn't when the movie was filmed), and anyone whose seen Thor and The Avengers knows he's a pretty jovial presence.  He's the alpha male of the group and a football player, but he's also shown to be smart, both well read and a good problem solver.  After all, the boxes horror movies put people into are ridiculous.  The Cabin in the Woods shatters those stereotypes.  At the same time, it offers a reason for them.The Cabin in the Woods pokes behind the scenes of horror movies, teasing out totally ridiculous reasons for why horror characters act the way they do.  One of the pleasures of The Cabin in the Woods is how it flings the silly, the mundane, and the brutal together.  I know lots of people who were disappointed by the third act and others who thought it was brilliant.  I veer towards brilliant.  It's slower paced than the rest of the movie, but it's different and exciting.  I think most people don't like it because it's where the film totally leaves traditional American horror behind.And, that's about as much as I can say without giving anything away.  Now, I actually think some of the "spoiler" arguments around this movie are dumb.  It would be just as fun if you know what's coming.  But at the same time, there's a pleasure in keeping mum.  I'll leave it at this: it's a fun movie and I've been enjoying thinking through the layers.My final word is to those who don't like gore.  The Cabin in the Woods is definitely not torture porn, and while there's quite a bit of gore, most of it is shot in a discretionary way.  If you don't like any blood, this isn't the film for you.  But there are no over-the-top gross gore scenes, in my opinion.

reviewText: This movie is about five friends who go to a cabin in the woods and get drawn into a mystery. This was a good effort to do a horror-comedy which is notoriously difficult. It doesn't quite work as either but it's a lot of fun. Cabin in the Woods doesn't take itself too seriously so you can't expect a straight-up horror. The plot is fun and weird. You see strange creatures, cameos, buckets of blood, military surveillance and much more. Once it gets rolling you find out the movie is not linear or predictable. Lots of twists and turns as it becomes apparent that logic is not going to be held accountable here. It isn't as coherent or interesting as it could have been. This hits the mark for some and not others. It's something fun to watch on the weekend but hardly a classic like Evil Dead (the original).
