reviewText: It's not fair to call CABIN IN THE WOODS a horror movie, although it wears the disguise of one. Instead, it's a very smart parody of one, made both to wink at and make fun of the horror movie audiences that have evolved over the years. Don't think it's mean-spirited, either. The film is a helluva a lot of fun, and even though the ending is very obviously thumbing its nose at the audience, it would've completely cheapened the whole movie if it had ended in any other way.I shouldn't really be talking about the ending. I don't want to give anything away, after all. Although, with this film, talking about nearly any part of it is giving something very important away. Instead, I'll focus on the two elements that the movie poster, the trailer, and even the title provide.The set-up is common and obvious, in a nothing-up-my-sleeves sort of way. A stoner, jock, nerd (barely qualifies), slut, and virgin (also barely qualifies) go on a weekend trip to a spooky cabin in the woods. This premise is pretty basic, and really the only element that changes is what horror awaits them. At the same time that these young victims are placed in a typical horror movie setting, they are being watched by people who are in a far less typical horror movie setting.The metaphors for the audience are hard to miss. Viewers of the film are turned into characters within the film, and the end result is a film that gratifies an audience's less unique horror movie needs while also turning the whole thing into a brilliant analysis of itself, an analysis that's hilarious on-screen, but which also stuck with me for days after I'd watched the film. The power of a horror film is to take a specific moment and magnify the mortality of it so that viewers can't help but sympathize; it's about taking one person's fear of death and making it everyone's. This fact is the basis for this film's entire set up as well as its snarky, all-hell-breaks-loose ending.The point being that you will laugh far more than you will scream or shudder. It might have been possible for them to have made the film as scary as it is fun, but I don't think it was necessary or even advisable. This film's greatest strength is not just in its excellently acted players, its multi-tiered plotting, or its sharp and brisk dialogue. Mostly, it is in its hilariously creative navel-gazing.
summary: The Best Non-Horror Horror Movie I've Ever Seen

reviewText: If you hate to have surprises ruined then by all means stop reading now. The only way to offer a discussion or review of the movie CABIN IN THE WOODS is to reveal the first of many surprises the film has to offer. It's not a major one and yes most people will gather what's going on before the first 30 minutes is passed but just in case you hate ALL surprises exposed then stop now.For the rest of you this is one movie that will keep you guessing until the last frame hits the screen. And it's not a film that fits comfortably into one single genre. While for the most part I'd consider it a horror film there are elements of science fiction here as well. Suffice to say that with the amount of gore and carnage involved it will most likely be considered a horror film. But unlike most horror films coming out today, this film is completely original while offering a nod or two to the films that came before it.Five college age students are set for a weekend getaway at a cabin in the woods. Curt's (Chris Hemsworth) relatives have bought this place and he and his girlfriend Jules (Anna Hutchinson) are going up with her best friend Dana (Kristin Connelly), Curt's new team mate Holden (Jesse Williams) and their stoner friend Marty (Fran Kranz). Packed up in the RV, they head towards the wilderness with no idea what they will soon encounter.Already we're tossed into familiar territory. It only becomes more so when they stop for gas to be confronted by a seemingly crazed attendant who gives them directions to their destination while telling them it's a bad place to go. You might think you know where the film is going here but trust me, you don't.While all of this plays out we're also seeing the story of what appears to be a high security, high tech location with plenty of lab coat, suit clad officials discussing some project going on. It's not long before we realize that the project is the kids heading to the cabin where this group is prepping to direct them towards what will be the last night of their lives. Why would this group do this and what are they talking about when they discuss the same thing happening in various locations around the world? Well I won't give you that much info here.The group gets to the cabin and things are set in motion early on. While they play a game of truth or dare, the basement doorway blows open and they investigate. What they find is a basement filled with all sorts of curious items from a fortune telling machine to a jewelry box to a diary that Dana begins to read from. Unfortunately these items are the methods of death that these teens are unknowingly choosing from. Back at the lab the boys in research are making bets on which they choose. Once Dana reads from the diary, redneck zombie killers are let lose to deal with the teens.Still you have to wonder what's going on. Why is this technical group putting these kids through this? What reason could they have for killing them off one by one? What is the end result from all the carnage? That's where the originality comes into play and it's something you have to watch the film to find out. While I'll let you know something is going on, I won't give away the films major secret.Everything is above par here which makes it even more compelling to watch. The acting is believable, the writing is superb and the direction well played. Particular kudos go to Richard Jenkins and Bradley Whitford, neither known as horror film stars, who turn in truly hilarious and chilling performances. Nods to classic horror films are seen throughout, everything from EVIL DEAD to HELLRAISER and more. Part of the fun is during the third act recognizing every horror film paid tribute to here.The concept that is revealed at the heart of it all is the most original thing going on here. This is no ordinary horror film. While it may appear the movie is a get kids in the woods and kill them movie there is more going on here. The depth of what is going on is more important than even the viewers realize until the end. If you like movies that surprise you, that keep you guessing and that never give up their surprise until near the end, you'll love this movie. If not, trust me, it might give you a few chills before it ends.

reviewText: The Cabin in the Woods is one of the most original horror films I've seen in years.  Similarly to how Scream broke down the slasher genre in the 90's, Cabin dissects the slew of brainless horror films we've had in the last decade.  The name and (part) of the plot are so painfully generic and it makes perfect sense!  Its a funny, scary, and mocking commentary on what horror films have become.  Its even funnier to see the negative reviews and people saying how the movie is ridiculous and that the ending doesn't make sense because THAT'S WHAT ITS MAKING FUN OF!  People are so used to seeing a cheap slice and dice horror film and get annoyed when the "rules" get broken.  If you don't like it, then you don't like it and that's fine.  But, if you want to see a horror movie that's actually new and original and not another "hot kids get naked and then gruesomely murdered for no apparent reason" slasher rip-off then you need to see The Cabin in the Woods.

reviewText: It's a shame and frustrating to see so many people confused or angry at what this movie is. Due to the nature of the film, it can't be marketed as much more than a slasher flick featuring intentionally cliche teenagers. This is a movie for true horror fans, down to the subtle references to the awesome twists.This movie has an exceptional skill of walking the line of parody yet also having thrilling situations and even characters that you may not necessarily be rooting or caring for very much, yet still are interested in. The film does occasionally use some jump scares or even some creepy atmosphere, yet the focus is on keeping the viewer guessing on what they are going to pull next.Unlike the other reviewers, I don't care for going into any detail about the actual plot much, this is just one that you should jump into as blind and spoiler-free as possible to all extents. Ignore those that are stupidly angry about this not being yet another forgettable teen slasher flick.
summary: An amazing and unique experience for actual horror fans

reviewText: On the surface, THE CABIN IN THE WOODS appears to be another teens going off on a weekend getting slaughtered one by one.  However, there's more to this giddily entertaining film.  That difference doesn't always work for me but amidst all the chaos lies an admittedly original horror movie.My biggest complaint is there are many key scenes that are shot in the dark thereby diminishing their effectiveness.  The acting overall is above average, especially Richard Jenkins and Bradley Whitford as the enigmatic lab techs.  Also the appearance of a noted sci-fi icon adds an unexpected boost.I think the movie has been over-hyped and its climactic conclusion over the top, but CABIN is different enough to elevate it above those movies it is obviously parodying.

reviewText: As a fan of the Delta Green fiction and role-playing game setting for Call of Cthulhu, I'm fond of conspiracy horror.  The Delta Green mailing list was buzzing about The Cabin in the Woods without managing to spoil the details, so I knew I had to see it.  Now I'm sharing that gift with you: GO SEE IT.  Go see it right now.Still on the fence?  Let me do my best to convince you. The Cabin in the Woods is the next evolution of Scream, elevating the winking genre horror conventions to a new level by tacitly acknowledging that everyone knows what will happen.  The film kicks off immediately with a pair of working schlubs, Richard Sitterson (Richard Jenkins) and Steve Hadley (Bradley Whitford) going to work in a secure underground facility.  SPOILER IN THE WOOD: They are, we discover, just cogs in the wheel of a greater horror. The humor is that they could easily be employees in any white-collar workplace, joking about their day, grumbling about the "man downstairs," and alternating between confident professionalism and bored malaise.  In its own way, their soul-grinding day-to-day jobs are just as horrifying as the action above ground.Stumbling into this is our quintet of horror victims: Curt the Jock (Chris Hemsworth), Jules the Slut (Anna Hutchinson), Holden the Nerd (Jesse Williams), Marty the Stoner (Fran Kranz), and Dana the "virginal" Final Girl (Kristen Connolly). They are off to vacation in the wooden cabin of Curt's cousin - Evil Dead fans will immediately realize they've come home.The film flips back and forth between these two worlds, and in a lot of ways it is a contrast between generations.  Where Scream was so consciously self-aware of its tropes that every character was aware of their stupidity, these victims are blithely manipulated - perhaps willingly - into dangerous circumstances.  The unseen older folks invent the technology, monitor their every move, and push levers that influence destinies.  The younger folks joke around, get high, and get naked.  In other words, reality television.If Cabin in the Woods stopped there, it would be a hiply ironic but relatively niche film in the vein of Behind the Mask: The Rise of Leslie Vernon and Tucker and Dale vs. Evil.  Instead, it takes the genre tropes as gospel (literally) and constructs an entire framework of worker bees dedicated to the sole purpose of rationalizing horror movies, all for the enjoyment of their "audience." It's only when that fourth wall begins to break down, when the survivors start bumping up against the illusion of horror, that Cabin in the Woods turn into a meta-commentary on the nature of our own carefully constructed worlds.In the end, the film asks: How far are you willing to go to defend the world you live in? Cabin in the Woods pulls no punches in answering that question differently for each generation. Horror fans, conspiracy fans, monster movie fans, and zombie fans will not be disappointed.

reviewText: This is one of those horror movies that because it gets a theatrical release, and it stars stupid known modern day players, automatically it drew attention from fans of Greys Anatomy and Buffy, not to mention a bunch of girls who would flock to anything with Thor in it. It's a recipe to suck in audience members who don't usually go to see horror films. I can't see horror buffs finding much in this movie at all. So, here is a real review not based at all on whom was in it and giving it undeserving 5 stars, or even 4, no this review will tell it how it is.First off, the plot of the thing is confusing for the most part. It is never really made quite clear what the heck is happening until the very end, and even when explained it ends horribly, writing wise.So, a group of kids go to spend a weekend in a cabin in the woods. Only they discover something in the basement that triggers off a family of zombies to come and get them. This is happening while a group of people are televising it and betting on who will be the monster unleashed to hunt them down. This idea reminded me of what John Cleese and his rich friends where doing in Rat Race. Only the betting seemed to stop after that, and no one was betting on who would be killed next etc... which would have been more interesting than these boring characters trying to run a show... but never explaining exactly who the viewers are? Ritual smitual... explain yourselves.Next up is the teens chosen. One is the ho, one is a virgin, one is a jock, the other a honer student, and of coarse, the dumb dope smoker. None of these characters had any depth or charisma. You don't care if they die or not, so there is no survivor or hero to root for, you just KNOW who it will be. The two women play oppisote characters, yet, both boring. The guys, same thing, and the stoner is the worst of them all. He talks like my grandmother, and just comes out with one liners to try to add humor to the film. Unfortunately the half a millisecond I laughed, I had to stop and cringe when he just kept talking and putting me off this guy being a credible actor. Did they pay him to do this role? I hope not.Once the SHOW has begun, dumb ideas happen, and things not explained or left unanswered occured... like the director has said, "Who cares, audiences will swallow and old BS these days, who cares if it makes sense". There are useless characters introduced with no pay off as to why they where even shown in the first place. Perhaps this movie thought it was tackling typical horror movie situations and trying to make fun of it, but if it doesn't pay off, then you have failed miserably.The kill scenes are for the most part stupid and ridicules. The end result made me wonder if one of the actors was getting out of hand about something on set, so they quickly rushed his death scene to get rid of him as fast as possible that day. He is no favorite actor of mine, but he was the biggest name of the movie, and they kill him off that way? Lame.Two things I hated about the ending. One, the very end of the film. If you end a movie with the end of the world in supposed present day, no one walks away. sure, we know it's fiction, but we walk outside and the Earth is still intact the same way it was before we went in. Why think an audience would be satisfied with an ending like that? It may be fiction, but make something plausible for god sakes.The second complaint about the ending. I wont mention what actor it is and spoil it, but she must have a contract with Hollywood stating she will only do a movie if she shows up in the 3rd or final act of a film. I was shaking my head in disbelief that she would do this, AGAIN. At least in the other movie she was in when she did it, it was homage to a previous film she did, and she had some funny lines to make fun of that older movie... but this one here... there was no point, and I would have cut that scene out as it was pretty much useless. They could have gotten anyone to say those lines, and it still would have been as unsatisfying. No one brings a new character into play in the 3rd or final act, however, it did work in that other movie, but here, what god awful stupid, STUPID idea that was.By the end you have been explained to that every horror situation is chosen, and the virgin escapes or dies by fate. It would have been a better ending to have had the stoner be the virgin. But no, it was just a terrible way to end a movie. It tried to be clever by saying every horror movie/situation that has happened, this is why, but it failed to develop anything else around it, making it hard to just sit back with some popcorn and suspend belief. This movie instead insults your intelligence and expects you to just go with it. Sorry, couldn't do it. Too much made no sense, there was no explanations to so many things, and it tried too hard to poke fun at horror movies, while not realizing it fell into the exact same position of bad horror movies.Josh Weeldon or whatever his name is should just stick to trying to revamp his Buffy series, and the other one should take the name of his series he made and put a GET at the front of it. The rest of the actors should hang there heads in shame for making a movie like this and thinking it would be great.Overall; rent it before you even think about buying it. See it first, heck, even wait for it to be on TV. But say I didn't warn you if you go buy 100's of 5 star reviews written by those who do not go to see horror movies, and are just rating it on their infatuations with certain actors. Think of it this was, what if Justin Beiber played Rocky? As bad as it sounds, his fans would flock, and it was gross millions. But is it a good movie? Hell no.

reviewText: Warning: Major Plot spoilers******Last night we watched 'The Cabin in the Woods'.  From the title and brief description I read,  I was expecting the usual type horror story. The kind with partying college or high school kids isolated from the rest of civilization doing stupid things and a monster killing them off one by one. Just like in so many other films before.  Instead this one had an interesting twist to it.The party bound college kids in this film were actually being set up by some sort of secret organization that periodically sacrificed young people to various type of horrors zombies, ghosts, werewolves, giant bats and so in.  The human sacrifices were needed in order to keep some giant Lovecraftian type creatures from taking over the world.  It's similar to the way virgins had once been sacrificed in ancient cultures to appease their gods like being thrown into a volcano or stabbed on an altar.  Now the young were being sacrificed in a different way and certain types were needed like a studious one, a virgin, an athlete, a buffoon, a promiscuous girl and so on.  Also they were being watched by TV cameras without their knowledge.  They were even drugged in order to affect their actions and ways were set up to prevent their escape.  A few of the assigned victims decided not to give in so easily to the zombies killers sent to destroy them.  Instead they turn the tables on the organization that is using them as sacrifices.  The organization itself was an interesting setup. They almost seemed like any other group of white collar corporate co-workers,  even taking bets on what type of horror the victims would inadvertently pick to destroy themselves.  The way others might bet on the outcome of a weekly pro football game.  When it looked like all was going as planned they seemed to be having a typical office type party to celebrate another success.  They cared little for the lives of the people they had set up.  They viewed it as something necessary for the survival of humanity and were used to it. This added side plot to the movie made all the difference to me, making it refreshingly different instead of the usual formula.As many of you know, I don't care for gore fests or that kind of film.  I did like this movie and the sort that take you off guard, it was not overly gory and was different for a change.  It also had an appropriate final scene.I give it a 3 out of 5 rating.
summary: A refreshingly different take on a tired old horror formula

reviewText: This was, in my opinion, the best movie of the year so far. It has been many months and the disc has finally arrived. This review is for the disc I purchased.This transfer is a great test of your tv's Blac levels. Since the movie predominantly takes place at night, the backgrounds often times get lost in the dark, at least on my tv. Or particularly, when some "baddies" are outsde at night, its extremely difficult to see the features on their faces. The colors are ok but do not pop like Transformers or District 9. But it is absolutely a pleasure to watch this film on Blu-ray anyway.I found the sound to be pretty well done, with lots of good bass when needed and it becomes quite stellar toward the end.Final word. Not as crisp as fans would hope for. When studios have cult hits like this one on their hands, they really need to do the transfer justice for the fans. Wait to pay $20 or less if you are looking to buy. Delayed gratification :)I did want to make a comment about the film itself. If you are a serious, die-hard horror fan, you probably won't like this movie. You don't realize it, but you enjoy predictability. And you also don't usually enjoy using your brain during such movies. This has been my experience with several people. They all happened to be girls in their very early 20s who went in thinking that it was going to be just like every other horror movie, and when it wasn't they all said they thought it was stupid. I asked one girl why she thought it was "retarded" and she said it was because she feels like all the movies she loved before, have been ruined. I find this so interesting. People's old perceptions are shattered so they respond with anger and resentment. Child-like response. An, "if this was true, I must have been wrong before, and that makes me embarrassed/angry, type response."
summary: Best Movie of the Year...Finally in my Hands

reviewText: This picture was ready in 2009 but it's owner, MGM, went bankrupt and thus it took a few years before it was actually released to audiences. First off, this isn't typicaly horror so much as a parody on horror films. There are several tongue-in-cheek remarks and there are several efforts to turn the horror genre on its head.Does it work? Sometimes it does and other times not so much. The ending felt a bit abrupt to me but with what they attempted I can only fault them partially. It's a fun movie that makes you feel the creators are sitting next to you in the theater and whispering their brilliance in your ear. Overall, it plays on the usual stereotypes and then proceeds to give you something entirely different which is mainly going to be satisfying to people who have seen a lot of different horror pictures.Is it scary? Not so much for horror film fans. I would say it's more along the lines of intense so I'm thinking slasher flick which turns into something else which might be termed as horror humor piece reminiscent of "Shaun of the Dead". Expect gore and some of the other elements.Starring a number of people: Anna Hutchinson, Bradley Wedford, Chris Hemsworth and Richard Jenkins. And you should recognize a voice in the latter part of the film but see below in the spoiler section if you can't wait. Note that this is the first time I have noticed Fran Kranz who is now on my radar.People who enjoyed "Tucker & Dale Vs. Evil" are likely to enjoy this picture as well.The budget for this piece was $30M and it made a bit over $65M at the Box Office. Partly created by Joss Whedon.STORY/PLOTTING/EDITING: B; PARODY PRESENTATION: B to B plus; CINEMATOGRAPHY: B minus to B; CHARACTERS/DIALOGUE: B; HORROR FOCUSES: B plus; WHEN WATCHED: end of September 2012; OVERALL GRADE: B.SPOILERS: one could argue there is a fair amount of symbolism in this piece. I've heard some say that Sigourney Weaver is the voice of movies comparing the Ancient Ones to the movie audiences (keep them zoned out so that they keep going to movies). I am not sure if I entirely agree but one could draw that symbolism if they're so inclined and it's nice that there is a subtext happening or maybe happening.The idea that a high tech company is keeping evil things at by with gory sacrifices based on archetypes was an interesting idea. I think they spent too much time on the humor and "look at how clever we are" to make this more than a "B" grade picture. If they had developed some of the ideas more and played with the nuances it would have been higher.The ending in itself made sense. I didn't expect the two remaining kids to fight but I think how it came to that ending could have been developed with a more satisfying narrative structure.

reviewText: This is simply one of the best movies released this year.  It's packed full of humor and knowingly crafted homages to pretty much every horror movie ever made. It's much, much, much longer on humor than it is on scares, but there are definitely some fun bump in the night moments.  However, see this because you love horror and are interested in laughing at and with the genre.  Do not see this if you are expecting Saw 19 or Paranormal 12.  Do not go for the gore or the pure thrills. Go for the fun.  There is an exuberance for movies built into the this flick that you don't get often. It was crafted with love; love of horror tropes and love of the audiences that enjoy them.And don't worry about spoilers. The biggest problem this movie had was the marketing's obsessive concern about spoilers.  There is really nothing to spoil when it comes to plot, as the biggest reveal comes in the first two minutes.  Everything else that you may want to be blind about going in simply relates to the characters and the jokes.  If they would have let more of the cat out of the bag in the marketing, I suspect this film would have been a much bigger hit.  As it was, the commercials made it seem like a twisty new version of whatever gorefest you may have loved in the past, and I think that killed it.  People went in expecting Saw 92, and instead they got something much funnier and more reflective on the genre as a whole.Anyway, just see this damn movie.  Buy this damn movie.  Then proselytize this damn movie.  I have not purchased a DVD in a few years, but I will be pre ordering this one shortly.  That's all you really need to know.

reviewText: I had heard good things about this flick...I should have known better.  I really don't feel like going into the plot because it isn't very interesting.  Maybe I've just seen way too many movies for this to make much of an impression.  It's really nothing that I haven't seen before.  I found the whole thing to be rather monotonous with very little to keep me entertained.  Heck, any episode of Buffy The Vampire Slayer would beat this to hell.  Maybe the horror genre should just take a break for awhile.  We've had way too many bad movies.  Wouldn't it be interesting to actually watch a movie that is original?  Horror doesn't always have to be monsters, gore, torture porn, redneck inbred hillbillies, little Japanese ghost girls, vampires and zombies.  There was a time when it was suspenseful and mysterious.  Now it's just blood, guts and four letter words.  Don't be fooled by thinking this will have clever twists and turns.  The movie is badly constructed and flows like a backed up toilet.  I knew where this was going almost immediately.  The art of storytelling seems to be dying.  It's been replaced with crap like this.  What I wouldn't give for a good quality Hitchcock or Hammer movie instead.  If you decide to watch this junk just be sure to leave your brain cells behind...you won't need them.
summary: Not As Clever As They Think.

reviewText: Director and co-writer (with Joss Whedon), Drew Goddard keeps his tongue firmly planted in cheek with this unusual take on the traditional slasher film.  The movie begins strangely with a scene involving co-stars Bradley Whitford and Richard Jenkins, but moves quickly into what appears to be your run-of-the-mill set up for attractive people to die one-by-one in a remote cabin "on loan from a cousin."  But this movie is different...way different.Sure we have the usual cast of stereotypes being offered up including the hunky athletic type (Chris Hemsworth), the smart one (Jesse Williams), the stoner (Fran Kranz), the sexpot (Anna Hutchison) and the less sexy but cute (Kristen Connolly).  The writers are very effective in keeping the audience guessing with a goodly amount of humor both overt and covert, dosed with plenty of suspense and horrorific scenes.  I can't give too much away however so as one of the characters exclaims, "let's get this party started."
summary: One of the best "slasher" films you'll see.

reviewText: It's hard to talk about this movie without spoilers in any meaningful way, so spoilers ahead. You've been warned.In Cabin in the woods, a group of young people are duped into heading to a beachfront condo. Psyche, they go to a cabin in the woods. A creepy old man warns them not to and everything. The whole situation is pretty formulaic horror. Yet we see that the woodland is in fact a controlled and observed environment, one that is lorded over by a huge bunker full of technicians who proceed to drug, trap, and trick their victims into a series of contrived-yet awfully familiar-horror movie situations. The guests, we eventually learn, are sacrifices to elder gods who demand that archetypical figures (specifically those seen in horror movies) be executed for their placation. As the main characters are stalked by zombies, the technicians are similarly imperiled- other offices around the world have been attempting similar sacrifices and all have failed (we see a variety of scenes of devastation being fled by helicopter and a room of Japanese schoolgirls entrapping a wrathful ghost). At the final hour the two surviving victims of the American horror movie scenario descend beneath the cabin to the bunker where they release a hoard of monsters (all shoutouts to horror film creature standbys) into the bunker, killing everyone. As the dark gods rise from the underworld the survivors opine that "giant evil gods" would have been a fun way to spend a weekend.A lot of reviewers seem to have taken Cabin in the Woods at face value as a horror film. These viewers are idiots. Cabin is simply and clearly a movie about Hollywood- the victims of a horror film as interchangeable cartoons who here are chemically coerced into behaving, like all horror characters, as no real human being would. The technicians who orchestrate the slaughter are filmmakers, painfully self-aware of what they do (at one point the technicians bet on which eldritch abomination the victims will be killed by) yet slavishly dedicated to it. Yet at the climax the "filmmakers" are destroyed by their own creations- just as, perhaps, Hollywood horror is undone by its over-dependance on predictable threats. The idea of horror as a literal human sacrifice is also a pretty good dig at the rash of watch-people-die-horribly torture porn that has so become the norm in horror films of late.The film is also a masterful shoutout to horror classics of the past. Almost every monster we see is a clear reference to a film or video game (even the storage device that holds them is a clear reference to The Cube) and the other nation's failed sacrifices are all pretty clear call-outs to horror classics (including what appears to be a happy ending to The Thing). And in a few places it's actually scary, although that is neither its main focus or its goal.PROS:-Funny, well shot, and smarter than a film student's thesis-Good effects considering it's low profile-Awesome, monster-rich payoffCONS:-Not actually a very effective horror movie-Very little characterization (although this is by design)-Will be largely meaningless to someone unfamiliar with horror moviesTHINGS TO WATCH FOR:-This film contains a couple visual references to Firefly, and to Left 4 Dead (the result of a failed deal between MGM and Valve)-The director of the technicians may be familiar to horror fans
summary: A scathing and hilarious indictment of the horror genre

reviewText: "The Cabin in the Woods" is a terrific horror film that breaks free from the mainstream trend of paranormal home videos and pathetic PG-13 remakes. It is campy and quirky - what I like to call "fun horror" (ala "Scream," "Drag Me to Hell" or "Trick 'r Treat").  And it definitely has its fair share of grit and gore to compliment its tongue in cheek attitude.The story involves a group of partying college kids and a separate, seemingly unrelated team of scientists who are embarking on an experiment. All we know for certain is that the college kids are the unsuspecting experimental guinea pigs. The movie unfolds slowly, and like its main characters, the audience never really knows what's going on.Spoilers do no favors for a film like this, so the plot synopsis ends there. Don't read too many reviews prior to seeing this movie: The less you know about it, the more enjoyable the experience will be.The audience is provided little bits of information throughout the course of the film.  Whenever the plot reveals a new twist, it also introduces new questions. The audience, just like the characters in the movie, are guided through a macabre yet fascinating story that continues to expand into something bigger. The final 25 minutes of the the movie will answer most questions, leave a few unresolved, and spill plenty of blood in the process.Watching "The Cabin in the Woods," I was reminded of certain horror films I grew up watching that were completely mind-boggling and unique... films that today are considered cult classics, such as: "Phantasm," "Re-Animator," and particularly the "Evil Dead" movies. They all had a campy charm to them, and the audience had absolutely no idea what was going on or what was going to happen next. This is what makes CITW such a delight to watch- it takes the most typical horror cliches, complete with the stereotypical group of college kids(the jock, slut, stoner, bookworm and virgin) and manages to create the most original horror movie I've seen in years.While it's never a "terrifying" movie by any stretch, it achieves a respectable level of creepiness throughout. It's a snarky ride that defies traditional horror convention - and for that reason probably won't find its target with mainstream audiences (they will be the "haters"). However, if you're a fanboy (or fangirl) of those campy cult classics that take you on a ride into the unknown (ala "Phantasm", "Evil Dead", "Re-Animator" and a dash of "13 Ghosts" thrown in for good measure), you will probably want to add this to your collection.
summary: Most Original Horror Movie I've Seen In Years

reviewText: I was told this was a terrible film, that it was "not even scary" and was "very cheesy".  I still had to watch it, and I'm glad I did.  The entire film is not just a parody of horror film tropes, but a satire of the horror film audience, and the ending is (while being careful not to spoil it) entirely unexpected and, for me and most intelligent people today, something I can entirely sympathize with as well.  You can see nods to various horror films from across the years, including Hellraiser (which surprised me, as Hellraiser seems, in my own experience, to be so often overlooked and a bit obscure to many people, but definitely a part of any real horror film buff's collection).Now if you go into it expecting it to be a serious horror film, you might be disappointed (unless you're like my family--we went into Evil Dead II thinking it was a serious horror film, and after our initial confusion wore off and we realized it was more of a comedy/parody, we dove right in!)  I think that might be where it's been running into problems, but the "creator of Buffy the Vampire Slayer" printed on the cover of the DVD itself should have been a dead giveaway to most people who would be inclined to even consider it.  It was definitely a dead giveaway to me.  (I rented it initially, but watched it again the moment Amazon/Netflix got it in, and will probably buy it at this point).
summary: Brilliant and hilarious, if you understand horror films to begin with

reviewText: Personally, I wouldn't rate this as one of the worst films ever made; that honor would have to go to *The Idaho Transfer* with Peter Fonda, for me.  But I will say, when I saw this in the theater (paying the long buck for it), I was swayed by the reviewers who said it was a twisty and twisted homage to all the horror cliches we've all grown up with.  And Joss Whedon knows how to make good material--so I was expecting another "Buffy-ized" snark fest.Wow, was I disappointed. . . but for a couple big reasons: A.)I didn't care a whit about the characters <caveat to come>; B.) It was, for me, gratuitously bloody and ugly with an attitude that said, "Gore is wooooo scary" (SCTV Count Floyd voice inserted here).To explain (A.): I KNOW we're not supposed to care about these characters.  They are cartoons, and they are supposed to be; that's why this is an homage.  Of course they're stereotypes: that's what's being parodied, for gosh sakes! I hated the Stoner--but come on, how many times do we need to laugh at a psychotropically configured moron (Jeff Spicoli, is this your kid?)before the stereotypes become stereotypes of themselves? I love homages, but not when they bring nothing new to the table with their characters.I suppose some folks who don't mind the constant barrage of doltish characters spouting the F-bomb (Note to filmmakers: If you want to appear "edgy" and on the cusp of "hip," watch *The Big Lebowski* which uses profanity to further characterization and mood)--and you don't mind last-minute "Time to up the violence quotient since we're running long and we don't want to alienate short-attention-span audiences with dialogue" sequences--you may enjoy this film.But, Joss, where were your characteristic wit and joy that made us love *Buffy* and *Angel* and *Serenity*?  I wanted so badly to like this film, but ended up feeling I'd lost valuable IQ points.  And the popcorn I bought was stale too.

reviewText: I know there will be those out there that hate this movie, and it's to be expected in such a subjective and maligned genre. Fortunately I only compare apples to apples so in reviewing this movie I do so basing it on what it is.What it is is an absolute blast.Two stories in one movie used to deconstruct and "explain" why horror tropes exist in the first place.The movie is funny and its everything you have seen before...sort of.The Jock is on academic Scholarship, The Geek is a "Stud" (subjectively of course), the party girl isn't, the Virgin, well she isn't, and the stoner is the most insightful guy in the room, and the funniest. The Cabin itself though is also not what it seems.But the teenagers in the cabin are only one half of the story and to me actually the less interesting part of the story. What is going on with the white-shirted technicians and scientists makes the movie infinitely more interesting.Just when your typical slasher/horror movie would normally end is just when this movie really gets interesting. The horror homages and frenetic ending are worth the whole thing.I will make this VERY clear, this is meant to be a fun, tongue in cheek, popcorn movie, and it is all of those things, and so worth the price of admission if that's what you like. It is bloody, its a little sexy, its a little over the top purposefully sometimes. it will not be for everyone. My brother despises horror movies and loved this, my wife loves horror movies and loved this, I could care either way and prefer Sci-fi and action movies but loved this passionately, so do not let that be your measuring stick because this is so much more than a horror movie. Sometimes I wanted to refer to it as Evil Dead II meets Buffy The Vampire Slayer, but its more than that as well.There will be haters, because that's what they do, but I GUARANTEE YOU, this will become a cult classic...DING!

reviewText: Did you grow up on Hellraiser, Halloween, Friday the 13th and all that?  Just what ARE these monsters?  Why does every encounter with them seem to involve a jock (dies), the cute coed (dies), the smart guy (dies), the lazy druggie (dies) and the virgin (sometimes dies, sometimes survives)?  Why doesn't anyone just go for help or maybe call the Marines?  Why do they keep doing really stupid things?  (Hey, what's that noise in the basement?  I dunno, but the lights are out, there's a big storm, help is 50 miles away by foot, so let's go check it out!)This movie answers all of those questions.It's not, strictly speaking, a "horror movie" in the traditional sense.  I wouldn't call it it a spoof, though it does have some spoof-type elements.  It's basically the horror movie that explains all other horror movies.  It's a monster horror movie written for the guy who has seen a lot of monster horror movies and has a sense of humor about them.I think the negative reviews are mostly coming from people who either weren't fans of the genre (in which case, you won't "get it") or were really expecting a dead serious scary horror movie (that's not the goal here).If you're with me so far, though, check it out.  It's very well done.  As usual, Joss Whedon injects life into even the most mundane background characters and helps bring the whole story to life.  And you'll finally have a sensible explanation for every other horror movie.
summary: The horror movie for nerds who like horror movies

reviewText: Wish I had been better prepared. PLOT SPOILERI found the difference in move between the puppet masters in the high tech facility and the kids in the horror set-up to be unnecessarily contrasting. The tech guys seemed inexplicably insensitive and inappropriately high spirited and did not seem sinister enough for what they were putting the kids through. I found it only watchable.This did not make much sense to me until a comment in the special features. One guy said that he had grown up in Los Alamos and the high tech folks were basically like the people that he had grown up with. They were just ordinary goof-off at the office types but they were highly motivated to develop weapons that had the potential to kill hundreds of millions and end civilization. So yes the tech types engineering the suffering of the kids were like that -- hurray the bombs work, the missiles work, etc.They were totally into the cause. The cause of course was continuing into modern times the tradition of sacrifice to the evil gods to keep them placated and to keep them from running amok and destroying humanity. Very neat idea in my opinion. Once I realized the sociological concept behind the way the film was done and the festive spirits of the guys in the high tech control center, it all made sense and worked well. In retrospect this was the essence of the film. Doing wicked things can be just a job that can be done enthusiastically if one believes that their cause is justified. Probably a lot of nazis felt this way. They were trained to.The film does not press this and so I had to figure it out.I would not call this a horror film and I can see why a lot of horror fans were disappointed at the "dilution" of genre themes. Even "horror film with a twist" is misleading. I am not sure how one should label it.By the way, the special features were sort of personal and light and not to my tastes. But this one remark did help elevate the film in my opinion to 4 stars. I think some viewers might appreciate it more if they were prepared. I would have.

reviewText: The Texas Chainsaw Massacre, Halloween, Friday the 13th, A Nightmare on Elm Street, Scream and many more were ultimately supposed to finish the Horror Genre by pointing out all the clichés and bad decisions that are still being done today, but alas, even though all those movies were superb.... They didn't do so, and neither will this, but I do believe it is and always will be the best example as to how horror movies are so repetitive!(This Review Does Contains Spoilers)Plot: Five friends head out to a cabin in the woods to basically get drunk, laid, and stoned just to have a fun time to get away from the world, But Some of the More Sinister Parts of the World has Followed Them There, An underground facility located under the cabin has access to what goes on above. Sure the teens get to make their own decisions but if it doesn't appease the bosses needs then they enhance as much as they can.... Now the five teens are being picked off one by one until the remaining survivors realize that they are being punished, for being young, being themselves, being at..... The Cabin in the Woods!Review: I saw this opening night, when I saw this movie I was surprised at how many laughs and jumps there were, I haven't seen that many since Rob Zombies Version of the First Halloween (Which got an applaud by everyone, but sadly this one didn't) This movie deserves all kind of praise, there are two ways you can look at this film and still enjoy and love the hell out of it. One way is to look at it for what it is a horror comedy/parody.... It is a damn good one at that, you except it to have only zombies, but it gets better than that. Or you could look at it as if it were just another horror movie and not to think to hard about it, even if everything seems recycled it still is done in the best way.... If you've already seen the movie then it would be okay just to look at it as a straight up, unoriginal horror movie only if you know that it is a amazing horror comedy/parody! All in all, you can't go wrong with this flick, hell, it turns from a zombie movie into an all out creature/slasher fest all with the simple press of a button!Acting: Even though I knew something bad (such as death) was going to happen I wanted it not to happen and to let it happen. The characters (even the some-what villains) are extremely enjoyable and not to mention likable! When one died you were either cheering are awing (I was cheering and awing at the scene with merman) It was done perfectly. There is not just one main character, all five could be considered that including some others, and even after they're gone you still miss their dialogue, the acting was Mint!Gore: Last fifteen minutes or so are gore filled featuring dismemberment, disembowelment, decapitation, impalement, peeps get shredded, eaten, crushed, stabbed and so much more, before the last fifteen minutes we get an off-screen decapitation, a knife in the throat, back, and hand with some blood! It was defiantly worth the last fifteen minutes!Bottom Line: Is The Best Horror Comedy of 2012, Yes! It has so much entertainment and it's pacing is great, I was already and hour in and it felt like only half an hour, I think it had gone as far as it could've with it's one hour and thirty five minutes mark without being to epic, when the ending hit, if it continued it would've turned into a clash of the titans/300 mix of action and horror rather than what it was, so it stopped when it truly should've! It is perfectly done and for that it is going to be put up on a well deserved pedestal!Rated R for strong bloody horror violence and gore, language, drug use, and some sexuality/nudityIs it worth the Buy on a scale of 1-10: 10For the Movie itself on a scale of 1-5: 5
summary: The Movie that "Scary Movie" should've Been, A Real Genre Stopper

reviewText: I read some other reviews, and can't believe how so many missed the homage to practically everything that's gone before. Joss Whedon is a master, in my eyes, and I have no end of admiration. Director Drew Goddard took Whedon's script, and with a game cast, presented one of the most original "old" scenarios I've seen in many years. It starts out as a parody of The Evil Dead and The Truman Show, but goes off into the unimaginable mind of Joss Whedon, as only he could dream up. It's not a slasher film, as many reviewers were expecting, but rather a tale of survival and redemption, done with style and loads of humor.I don't know what else to say without giving things away, but I was highly entertained...and satisfied. All said, it's an homage of all that went before, and a preview of some original material to come (hopefully).

reviewText: So far, so great.The four archetypical characters go to a cabin in the woods owned by a family member for a fun weekend. Pretty quickly, you realize the environment isn't that friendly. You're going to see some tropes with a twist that will leave you pondering."Cabin in the Woods" is definitely a different take on the cookie-cutter horror genre.  This is one film I wish I had seen in the theaters, because it could benefit from widescreen viewing. If I wasn't the only horror fan in the house, I'd buy the DVD so I could see it again. I'm grateful Amazon has so much content available for rent.Rebecca Kyle, January 2013
summary: Can Joss Whedon do anything I don't love?

reviewText: Did I actually watch Joss Whedon's Cabin in the Woods(released Mar/12),or was it something that just had the same name? I glance at other reviews here and elsewhere,along with the build up hype and have to wonder what the glowing words used like "brilliant","fun","twisted","wonderful",and on and on,are doing associated with a run of the mill horror flick with a run of the mill twist like this one?This is a straight up horror movie,played seriously by its acting characters and with a theme,superficially at least,reminiscent of Evil Dead.The story(spoiler alert)involves a group of five teenagers who plan a trip to a remote cabin in the woods.Along the way they make a brief stop at a run down old gas station whose attendant is less than hospitable.Once at the cabin they discover one room with a two way mirror and then make a walkabout in the basement,whose trapped door had conveniently flown open enticing them down there in the first place.They discover an old diary and one girl(there are two)starts to read a passage,at the end of which,is a bit in latin.One guy,a stoner,says not to read it but of course she does and that starts the proverbial ball rolling.Keeping in the Evil Dead theme(Bruce Campbell would be proud),the dead family from the diary comes out of the ground in the woods and heads towards the house(wouldn't a Wal-Mart have been better?...just asking).One couple has already left the cabin to make out in the woods and one of them becomes the first fatality.The undead invade the cabin and the stoner becomes trapped,while the remaining three flee in the RV they came in.They reach an impasse when a tunnel caves in,then one of them tries to jump a gap in the ravine,on a motorcycle(conveniently attached to the RV for just such an emergency)to go for help.However,just before he lands on the other side he plows into an unseen force field,killing him instantly.We saw this same force field as the five drove in originally and a bird hit it and disintegrated.The remaining two head back in the RV and the male driver gets his along the way.The RV crashes and sinks into a nearby lake and she escapes only to be stalked again on a dock.Just as she's about to become shish kabob#4,the stoner suddenly shows up and helps to dispatch her tormentor.They flee into the woods to a man made hole and door in the ground that the stoner had discovered before he met up with her(doesn't every petrified stoner have the where with all to search for man made openings in the ground,in pitch darkness,while fleeing a family of Freddie Kruegers?).Now before I go further there is an entire backdrop and parallel story happening.This entire scenario,getting the kids up to the cabin and everything scary wise,is being manipulated by people in a control room,dressed in white garb,far away.These folks have sophisticated monitoring equipment and they deliberately place and set up each scenario so the people,in this case the kids,get to chose their own fate.For instance,instead of the diary the girl found and read from,one guy was about to blow on a conch shell,and another was playing with a round gadget,both of which would have taken the scenario in a different direction.The people in the control room even take bets amongst each other as to what scenario the participants will choose.In fact this is a globally run concern,as there are monitors with on going scenarios in Brazil,Japan and Sweden.When someone gets killed a switch is pulled and blood comes streaming down and into a likeness of that individual.What's behind it?Let's go back to the kids.The kids are in the man made hole under which the stoner has found an opening to an elevator.The girl and the stoner decide their only hope is down,and away they go.In their descent they see a menagerie of monsters,each in their own cubicle(the elevator is made of clear plexiglass sides).In fact their elevator is just a small part of a bigger gigantic holding area.They finally reach bottom and get out,when suddenly a voice comes over the loudspeaker explaining that their entire plight has been part of a bigger plan,for those that the voice and the control room folks serve.Armed para-militants are dispatched to retrieve the couple who hide in a bullet proof booth,filled with switches.The girl flips all the switches which unleashes the entire menagerie of monsters.The monsters quickly dispatch the gunmen,and eventually when one of the monsters comes crashing into their booth,they have to flee.While the monsters are running all through the complex and killing those that originally controlled them,the two kids end up in a round room where they are confronted by the originator of the disembodied voice they heard just off the elevators.It is in the form of actress Sigourney Weaver,who is the controller of the complex and who explains that they have set things up all to appease giant ancient evil ones who live far below.If they do not do so to their satisfaction,they will rise again to take over the earth.The two struggle with Sigourney and when a werewolf attacks the girl it becomes Sigourney and the stoner.Just as it looks as if Sigourney is going to win,one of the people that attacked them at the cabin drops in and dispatches her.The stoner kicks both over the open edge of the room.The stoner then shoots the werewolf and he slinks away.The film ends as both sit there,the sun comes up and a giant hand reaches out of the ground from below the earth.I guess it is shift change time for the Earth.It is certainly a different approach to the horror/Sci-Fi genre of films,I will give Mr Wheadon that.When the kids leave their apartment building to go to the cabin we spot a man on the roof with an ear plug saying to someone,somewhere,that they had left,so from there we start guessing as to what it is,or who it is that he represents.Then we see the bird killed in the force field and know something weird is up.As the Evil Dead-like scenario plays out with the kids,we go back and forth between them and the control area,which reveals more and more of its raison d'etre.Of course the end puts all the pieces of the puzzle together.But I don't find anything astonishingly brilliant or even new here,and I certainly do NOT find anything funny in this film.It's entire dynamic is a back handed homage to a myriad of horror flicks and monsters,but other than that there is nothing the least surprising here.In fact one might even say the film itself is a kind of Frankenstein monster;common parts from here,common parts from there and all stitched together to create one entity.From all the hype I was expecting greater things but saw far,far less.I like some of Whedon's work(Firefly),and dislike others(Buffy the Vampire Slayer),but I must admit I was rooting for him in this one but,sorry Mr Whedon you hit the ball but only made it to second base.It was a good try though.Oh yes,for all of the five minutes Sigourney is on screen,she gets FIRST mention and separate credit,as the end credits roll.Now that's star power.Technically speaking the film is in its w/s a/r of 2:40:1 and is clear and crisp.Extras include commentary and five featurettes.All in all a fair to middling horror flick,with kids in a cabin and all doing their Evil Dead impersonations.The special"twist" is it is all controlled,and who the controllers are working for...whoopee.No surprises,nothing new...nothing to see here.2 1/2-3 stars.
summary: Did I watch the same movie as everyone else?

reviewText: The Cabin in the Woods (Drew Goddard, 2011)In 1990, when I first saw Joel Schumacher's Flatliners--to this day the last Joel Schumacher film I actually enjoyed--I came up with a rule of thumb that has served me well in the intervening two decades and change to explain how the normally-loathsome Julia Roberts didn't make he hate her character in that movie: every awful actor gets one good role. I have since found ample evidence that this is the case, from Kevin Costner being not ridiculous in A Perfect World to Jesse Eisenberg wowing me in Zombieland to Albert Brooks not making me want to punch him in the face in Taxi Driver. It never occurred to me that this also might be the case for folks behind the camera, but let me be the first to give credit where credit is due: for the first time, I have encountered a project touched by the vile, vile hand of Joss Whedon  that officially does not suck big green donkey [censored for Amazon consumption]. I KNOW, RIGHT? No one was more surprised than I was. Now, I grant you, some of the Joss Whedon characteristics are still very much in evidence--the movie doesn't resist the temptation to go too far to get the joke nearly as much as it should, some of its minor characters should have come pre-packaged with red shirts, while others exist solely as plot-point advancements, the story adds needless complexity far too often--but in general, this is actually... fun.Plot: if you've seen any half-dozen random horror films, the beginning of this is going to sound familiar. Well, actually, the movie isn't going to let you get anywhere "familiar" to kick itself off; it's going to let you in on at least part of the fun from the opening scene. You know from the get-go that the titular cabin and its soon-to-be young-and-beautiful inhabitants are not the usual slasher-flick fare. But yet here we are, with the (monitored) cabin and the young-and-beautifuls in question. There's Dana (Revolutionary Road's Kristen Connolly), who's coming off a nasty breakup, and her best friend Jules (Wendy Wu: Homecoming Warrior's Anna Hutchison in her first big-screen appearance), who is determined to snap Dana out of her funk. There's Jules' boyfriend Curt (Thor's Chris Hemsworth), the stereotypical jock boyfriend, and his best friend Holden (Brooklyn's Finest's Jesse Williams), with whom Jules and Curt are trying to fix Dana up as part of that save-your-best-pal-from-depression plan. And then there's Shaggy--excuse me, Marty  (Donnie Darko's Fran Kranz), the resident stoner and the guy about whom you ask yourself in every horror movie you have ever seen, "what the hell is this person doing with this group of people? He totally doesn't fit!" This is a bog-standard horror setup......but, like Wes Craven did with Scream in 1996 (but done here about a dozen times better), Whedon and co-writer Drew Goddard (J. J. Abrams' right-hand man, the writer on both Lost and Cloverfield), who also takes to the director's chair for the first time, are intimately familiar with the horror tropes, and are going to lampoon them to full effect here. We already know this situation is Not Right(TM), and it is Not Right in the kind of way that put me in mind of the slick, underrated little thriller My Little Eye from a decade before--but Cabin in the Woods goes in an entirely different, often funny, direction. There is a segment about three-quarters of the way through the film where its quest to keep ramping up the funny threatens to derail it, and it comes very, very close for a while there, especially in the climax--but then comes the denouement, with a great, great cameo (that I had managed to avoid hearing about, so I won't spoil it for you, either) and a scene that manages to tie everything back together and come up with an ending that manages to be completely satisfying, and I gotta say I'm giving this movie as many points for that save as I am for anything else. (And then you top it off by putting Nine Inch Nails' best song ever as your end title theme? Yes.) I didn't expect to like this movie nearly as much as I did. It's a blast. It's actually convinced me that I may actually have to watch something else Whedon does in the future. (But not the Shakespeare adaptation. I'm not open-minded enough for that yet...) ***
summary: This isn't meant to last. This is for right now.

reviewText: Five young people go on an excursion to a cabin located in the woods, hence the title. They are then subjected to a horrifying experience of being terrorized by zombies. There is terror, mutilation, and gruesome death...... a good time is had by all. Despite the graphic violence, this is not your standard blood and gore horror film. Any further on that would be a spoiler, so I will just leave it there. I found the young people quite likeable, and the film is very clever in its unusual treatment of the horror genre. The movie even has a bit of humor in it, at rare times a parody of horror films. Overall, this is a very good movie for those who don't mind being frightened and seeing some attractive young people killed at the hands of the undead.

reviewText: I went to see "The Cabin in the Woods" with a bad attitude.  From what little I had seen it seemed like yet another variation of the "Friday the 13th" slasher genre with a group of college aged students (played by less than great actors) going to spend a weekend in the woods in which there would be sex, pot smoking, and partying and of course there would be a strange force in the woods killing the youngsters one by one.Yes this element exists,  but there is somuch more going on here.  Think "Friday the 13th" meets "The Truman Show".  The action that takes place in the woods is fun to watch but it's nothing compared to watching the action in a control room.  Bradley Whitford and the always great Richard Jenkins make this movie a treat.  And then of course there is the climax which is second to none.  Awesome script, good laughs (all intentional), fun movie to watch.Peace.
summary: A very good take on the horror genre

reviewText: First a slight word of warning, I am a Joss Whedon fanboy all the way-- and this movie only strengthens that.The next paragraph will be spoiler-free, every part after that read at your own risk!From the very start this movie is not what you think it is.  If not for the trailers already spoiling a tiny bit I would have been completely surprised by the somewhat strange and mundane opening (immediately after the opening credits but before the title screen).  Who these people are and what they're doing is the ultimate plot of the film, and unless someone has told you something about this movie already it's a pretty safe bet that you'll never guess what's really going on.  Even better than that, though, is the dissection of the horror genre that follows.  The same things that always happen in horror movies happen in this movie as well--there's a jock, a stoner, a brain a slut and a good girl just like every other horror movie ever.  But are they really those people?  From the start you get the idea that maybe they're not, and the reasons they end up acting the way they do are the heart of the movies' plot.  It's original, genuinely disturbing at a few parts, funny, and engrossing.  If you haven't seen it I would recommend seeing it as soon as you can, before someone ruins it--the less you know about this movie going into it the better.  "Let's get this party started" indeed...If you haven't seen it you should probably stop reading here...SPOILERS FOLLOW!!!!....I loved what this movie became--I think I would have genuinely been let-down if the ending hadn't happened the way it did.  Don't get me wrong, parts of this movie were ultimately silly (why do they have a "system purge" button?  Because of course they do!), but I loved the deeper subtext hinted at in this movie:  the security guard being our conscience (should we really be watching and, on some level, enjoying this?), Sigourney Weaver acting as the Executive Producer and the controllers acting as Director and Producer while everyone else is the "crew" all to bring the Elder Gods (us) the entertainment they crave to keep them from "rising up" (i.e. stop going to movies). There are so many funny, little moments in this as well--the Harbinger on the phone (and, in a throwaway moment, basically tells us "the fool" is going to derail the entire thing); the awesomeness of the white board (I so want to know who...or what...Kevin is and what he would have done); the great moment with Marty and the bong, and really most of Marty's moments are pretty great.The blu ray presentation is pretty good (although there are a lot of trailers on this disc) and the supplementals are better than the average supplementals.  The making-of not being just a "rah rah everyone's great" but a real, honest-to-goodness documentary about how they made the movie that is interesting to watch.  I haven't watched it with the commentary on yet but will pretty soon, as I've heard that's pretty great as well.  The sound is epic--particularly during the system purge with bullets flying and monsters screaming and people screaming and blood splattering--you really feel like you're in the middle of it (but in a good way).Highly recommended all the way around.
summary: Turns the genre on it's ear!

reviewText: The Cabin in the Woods is without a doubt, one of the most original comedy/horror movies I've ever seen. It never attempts to originally play itself off as your typical teen slasher flick liked The Evil Dead or Friday the 13th. Cabin in the Woods is highly original, highly creative, and highly entertaining. The very first scenes focus on what appear to be workers in a typical office or corporation of some sort, and it is filled with the typical office type humor you might expect from a film like Office Space or Dilbert, but it quickly becomes clear that something far more sinister and mysterious is at work, and the five young college kids who are planning to go to a "cabin in the woods" for an afternoon of fun and excitement, as is the typical horror movie setup, end up getting far more bloody and brutal than even the audience, both in the film and in the "office", expect.As the film progresses the five stereotypical characters, portrayed by Kristen Connolly, Chris Hemsworth, Anna Hutchison, Fran Kranz, and Jesse Williams, slowly realize that something is very wrong in their little cabin in the woods, but it isn't until the end that they realize the danger is far greater than they could have ever imagined. In addition to being a dark satire on slasher flicks and "torture porn", the film, if you really think about it, is actually far more disturbing than it is funny. It takes a good, hard, nihilistic look at our messed up world and offers hints or explanations on how it got that way, going far back to the ancient times when our ancestors sacrificed their fellow men and women to vengeful, murderous gods. The very gods whose dark presence continues to spread misery and suffering in our world to this very day through various religions and cults.It's a very thought-provoking and intelligent movie that has fun playing with your expectations about who will live and who will die, and as such has a very strong air of unpredictability, something which is very refreshing to see. I can't tell you how many times I could tell who was going to live and who was going to die long before it happened in movies like Wrong Turn and Sleepaway Camp. This was a real treat indeed, it succeeded at being funny, it succeeded at being scary, it just succeeded overall. At first I was bummed about having the stereotypical characters you always see in these types of films, but towards the end when I realized that they were that way for a reason, that automatically turned my opinion of this film from great, to fantastic. A well deserved 5 stars. The ending was awesome too, totally didn't expect that.
summary: Thank You Drew Goddard and Josh Whedon

reviewText: Alot of reviews here a pretty darn positive regarding this bold movie and if you only watch it once I would agree.However I watched it again last night and guess what? It's just not half as interesting when you already know exactly what's gonna happen and that cost a couple of points alone.I rate movies with certain point scale and being a movie where re-watching it is maybe a third as entertaining as the initial viewing takes away any buying potential period.Now, I'm not saying this applies to all movies with a great twist but generally if you know Bruce is dead in the Sixth Sense there is virtually no rason to watch the movie hoping to be entertained in a major way.Ditto with Cabins in the Woods.It is awesome that they even tried something like this and it's a twist that more or less can't be guessed as it's so far off the ususal horror crap however try watching it again and try to pretend it was even half as good as the first time you watch it...I dare you.Walking out of the movies I was pretty sure I would buy this when it came out...after watching again I think I can do without.However I would agree you need to watch this at least once.PSIf your like me you'll probably find yourself pausing at a few scenes near the end just to catch all the bloody action on the screen. Those parts will always entertain but there simply wasn't enough of that for my taste.
summary: Yeah it was alright but trying watching it again

reviewText: Full of stereotypical horror movie cliché set-ups and situations, The Cabin in the Woods has taken the predictable and made it unpredictable. Five young friends head out for a weekend of fun. You know that they are in trouble when they pull up to their little vacation spot and it looks strikingly similar to the cabin fromEvil Dead 2. And indeed, just like Evil Dead 2, the kids provide a satirical at times take on what happens when you inadvertently release some mean boogymen into their retreat.Man, this would have been a cool video game! In fact, according to a 9/23/2012 Joystick article, there was almost a Cabin in the Woods download pack forLeft 4 Dead 2. Unfortunately, when MGM went bankrupt it not only delayed the movie from a 2011 release to a 2012 release, it also quashed the video game downloadable content. Although, according to the article, that did not prevent Cabin Director Drew Goddard from giving viewers a glimpse of some L4D monsters in the movie. But the L4D monsters are only a couple in a plethora of nasties that include an array of horrors from the more classic zombies, werewolves and other more familiar nightmarish figures to some unique, very video game-esque supernatural beings/entities.So what's with all these monsters? Where do they come from? Why are they here? Well that's the interesting, unpredictable twist part of the movie that revealing in a review would be a major spoiler. It's all eventually explained in the movie to an extent, but where the monsters came from is still a tad bit unclear at the movie's conclusion.I was thoroughly entertained by Cabin in the Woods. Horror fans should not pass on this. It's not so much scary as it is fun and cool to watch.
summary: That's a Spooky Looking Place...Let's Go In!

reviewText: Rented this movie on Redbox, and liked it so much I went out and bought the DVD to see the bonus features.  Now I've watched it straight through four times, watched the full commentary once, and watched all of the bonus features.  IMO, this is the best horror movie to come out in years.  As you may have heard, it has funny moments that satirize the horror movie genre, but never at the expense of the actual horror.  Make no mistake - this movie is not a straight parody, nor is it a farce.  Rather, it credits the viewer with a certain awareness of the conventions of the horror genre, acknowledges them, then delivers some real horror that seems fresh and real.  That's a tricky tightrope to walk, but the producers, directors and cast of this movie pull it off in spades.  This is a movie that rewards repeated viewings.  I've noticed something new every time I've watched it.  It has wit, and it has grit.  If you like fresh, original horror, give this movie a shot.  There are a few other horror movies I've enjoyed as much, but none more.
summary: Best horror movie of modern times

reviewText: If you can force yourself to keep watching what appears to be a typical slaughter of college kids in the woods, this movie is well worth it because something's VERY different here. The entire cabin deal is a set-up by one of many government agencies around the world, an attempt to keep the world from being destroyed. Destroyed by what, you ask? You have to wait to find out. The last 1/3 of the film is especially good, with special effects that are great and a "reveal" at the end that would have H.P. Lovecraft standing and cheering, "YES, yes, yes!" The underlying story is pure Lovecraft but it couldn't be advertised that way without ruining it for a lot of viewers. I have a lot of respect for this film and love showing it to friends, all of whom are surprised and delighted by the end, whether they know Lovecraft's writings or not. GET IT AND ENJOY!
summary: H.P. Lovecraft Would Have Loved This Film

reviewText: The reviews for this film have degenerated into an absurd war between Joss Whedon fans - who apparently find pure perfection in everything he does - and people who are perplexed at the virulence of those who defend a film they found third rate and unentertaining.I wouldn't normally bother reviewing a film I disliked as much as this one. I do so only because I think Joss Whedon is a genuine talent and, a few years back, was something of a wunderkind. He made some great television, and I looked forward to watching him develop his talents. But his two recent efforts, this film and Avengers, have been unworthy vehicles. He seems to have realized this himself, because they're crafted in a half-hearted way that seems almost apologetic - or maybe I just think an apology is warranted and I'm seeing things that aren't there. Either way, where is the Joss Whedon who had so much promise? A few witty quips (and there are VERY few in this movie) do not a good film make.I understand that this was intended as a send up of horror movie tropes, but that has been done frequently in recent years, and this movie has nothing fresh to add. It doesn't work on any level and commits the ultimate crime of being simply uninteresting. I couldn't wait for it to end.
