reviewText: "The Cabin in the Woods" is a 2012 horror film that has a great cast of actors and actress's such as Sigourney Weaver (Alien, Ghostbusters), Richard Jenkins (Step Brothers, The Visitor), Bradly Whitford (Adventures in Babysitting, Revenge of the Nerds II), and Tim De Zarn. (South Central) (Those were the only recognizable people I saw in the film.) The rest of the cast features various young and up-and-coming stars - Their names being Chris Hemsworth, Jesse Williams, Fran Krantz, Kristen Connolly, and Anna Hutchison. The entire cast did very well with their roles.The film is co-written and produced by Joss Whedon and directed and co-written by Drew Goddard. The two have also worked together previously on the television shows "Buffy the Vampire Slayer" and "Angel".I liked this film because I am a fan of actors Richard Jenkins and Bradly Whitford, and it was fun for me seeing them act together. They both steal the show in my view. Jenkins plays the part of a man named Gary Sitterson and Whitford plays the part of a man named Steve Hadley. The two are co-workers and both appear to be typical business men. Each man is very comical, but serious when they need to be, and given what they do for a living, a sense of humor is an important thing for the men to have."The Cabin in the Woods" is about five college students who go to a remote cabin for a weekend get-away. Their names are Dana Polk, Holden McCrea, Marty Mikalski, Jules Louden, and Curt Vaughan. Upon arriving at their destination, the five young adults soon discover that this party is not going to be what they expected.....However - The film is also not what we the audience expect it to be either.....It turns out that the students are being video taped by agents for the government. The technicians, Sitterson and Hadley, watch the group of youths from various monitors in their control panel and are able to create the environment the group are in and give them mind-altering drugs to control them into following a procedure. The drugs gradually reduce the group's judgment and perception, and also increase their sexual stimulation. In time, Sitterson and Hadley figuratively fatten the young people up for the kill and essentially coerce them to "pick their poison". i.e. Pick which type of monster(s) is going to hunt them and kill them.I rather not type more about the plot because I feel the less you know about this film, the better.Another reason why I enjoy this film is because I am intrigued by conspiracy theories. i.e. Area 51, the Illuminati, the New World Order, etc. In all honesty, I don't think there are any government cover-up's, however I keep an open-mind and it is an entertaining and interesting idea and this film essentially explores that topic.In my opinion, the characters of Sitterson and Hadley are clearly apart of or associated with the U.S. government and what they are doing is one of the government's underground projects. Sitterson and Hadley are not the only ones apart of this group - There is an entire staff of adults of all ages, races and genders who work from within this building that assist Sitterson and Hadley - From maintenance workers, to security guards, and more. Just regular people who you could pass on the street and not give two thoughts about. The interesting part is - All these folks seem like harmless and decent people. It's very interesting watching these people interact like regular people given where they are and what they do. In fact, watching all the employees of this place is almost slightly like watching a light-hearted comedy about a bunch of employees in their offices just working and joking together like every other Average Joe and Average Jane out there.However, I suspect if places like Area 51 for example have Aliens inside them, and/or Area 51 is a place for the government to meet up to discuss things like creating a new world order, or time travel testing is conducted out there, etc, I see no reason why the human employees of Area 51 on their break-time wouldn't not only have discussions about whatever is going on in their personal lives, but would also have a sense of humor because they are still human as anyone, and what they are apart of would be pure horror for some people, and for me personally, if I worked there, it would take getting use to, so being able to joke around, flirt with female co-workers, and just talk about what my weekend plans are with co-workers would be desperately needed to keep me sane.What makes a horror film entertaining to me is if the villain or villains are well-acted by the performer(s) and can convince the audiences that their character's really believe the evil things they are doing is righteous. I also like it if the villain or villains even appear likable despite their violent ways. It makes the film more realistic. In real life, no one thinks they are doing evil and feel their actions are totally justifiable and that is what we are treated to in "The Cabin in the Woods".I enjoy this film because it's scary, thought-provoking, funny, entertaining, and like a hybrid of several horror films in one. The two biggest being a slasher film and torture porn.The reason why I watched this film is because I am entertained by some horror movies. I feel watching them is similar to riding a roller coaster. i.e. There's something appealing about being scared, but knowing you are not in any danger.I also enjoy underdog stories because I can relate to them, and most horror films are underdog stories. i.e. You have a character facing a challenge where the odds are highly stacked against them, and it's fun cheering them on, hoping they can overcome.Finally, I am a fan of horror films because I am intrigued by human nature and feel horror films sometimes explore the dark side of human nature, thus horror films can serve as good educational tools which in turn can improve lives because it can teach you lessons on how to behave in life for example and help you make better choices.One of tag lines for this film is "You think you know the story". Going into this film, I thought I had a good idea of what the film was about, but the tag-line was proven to be correct, and I was in for a surprise. I figured the film would be another typical horror film that takes place in the woods, and it was, but there is a twist to it. Before I saw this movie, I knew nothing about it. I never even saw the trailer. I discovered the film thanks to various advertisements for it on the Internet which lead me to watching it. Me knowing nothing about the film increased the entertainment for me.I watched this film on blu-ray on my HDTV with surround sound and the screen was very clear, the sounds were perfect, and made me feel like I was right in the middle of the action, the lighting was perfect, and the movements of the cameras were good as well. The pacing of the film was perfect. The film is not too long, but it's not too short either. The character development of all the main characters was done well and you get to see them all react to all kinds of different and crazy situations. I enjoyed the film's soundtrack as well. The action was wonderful. The ending action sequence reminded me of the ending action sequence in "Titanic" because there is total chaos at the end. It's great.Those who enjoy scary movies should check the film out. I think people who are looking for fun, roller-coaster-like entertainment would enjoy this film a lot. I also think people who believe in conspiracy theories, as well as those who are anti-big government would like the film too.The blu-ray includes plenty of special features that go into great detail in the making of this film.I highly recommend "The Cabin in the Woods" to horror fans everywhere.

reviewText: "This we offer in humility and fear, for the blessed peace of your eternal slumber as it ever was." When five friends plan a weekend getaway to a secluded cabin things start off as planned. While relaxing at night they hear a strange sound, when the go off to investigate all hell breaks loose. One by one the friends begin to get killed off, then things start to get out of control. I have to admit that based off the few previews I saw this was not what I expected. I did enjoy it and it was a fun movie to watch though. The thing that kind of depressed me though is that this type of thing may not be that far away from reality. While there is the clichéd slasher movie aspects in this it is not your typical slasher type movie. This one had equal parts comedy and horror. That combination may turn off a lot of horror fans, but to me that made it a really fun experience. If you are looking for a true horror/slasher like "Friday the 13th" this is not it. If you are looking for a good time and a horror you can laugh at then this is what you are looking for. Overall, a very fun experience. A comedy/horror that is worth checking out. I give it a B.
summary: Not your typical horror/slasher movie. Equal parts comedy and horror made this really fun to watch. I liked it. I say B

reviewText: For more than two years now, horror movie fans and loyal followers of Joss Whedon have spoken of the legendary horror film, The Cabin in the Woods. Well, to be honest it was legendary without ever seeing the light of day, and unfortunately for the Whedon geeks out there it didn't look like we'd find out what all the fuss was about. Why were people throwing out phrases like "game changer" and calling it the next Scream? For once the clamor was dead on right. The Cabin the Woods is the new standard bearer for the horror movie genre. Period.That's not hyperbole. Joss Whedon and director Drew Goddard have taken every one of the cliches we've come to expect from horror and given them enough unique twist, all the while winking and rubbing our expectations right in our faces. There are so many surprises that are both hilarious flat out bonkers that it's crucial not to spoil anything, and it goes far beyond the simple mystery of whoever the antagonist is like in Wes Craven's Scream films. In fact, we know right from the start who is beyond all of the mayhem. The big mystery is why, and the answer comes at the end of one of the craziest final acts you'll ever see. There's a unicorn involved. That's all that can, and should be, said about it.Even the simplicity of the title serves to lower your defenses. In the beginning we're introduced to the archetypes we've come to look for: there's the slutty blond bombshell, Julie(Anna Hutchinson); the paranoid stoner, Marty(Fran Kranz); the brainiac, Holden(Jesse Williams); the "virgin", Dana(Kristin Connolly); and an unknown Chris Hemsworth as Curt, the token jock. The plot is hilariously familiar, with the boozing, horny friends heading off to a cabin in the thick of the woods near a corn pone mountain town. Recipe for disaster? Of course it is, and it isn't long before strange family heirlooms are disturbed, ominous journals are read, and things start going bump in the night.Yet that's just a small piece of the puzzle, as we learn early on that somebody else is pulling the strings, namely a shadowy government organization led by two fairly average joes played by veteran character actors, Richard Jenkins and Bradley Whitford. That's not spoiling anything major, so don't fret. This portion of the film is played up mostly for comedic effect, as they run some sort of game orchestrating every terrible thing that befalls the clueless youngsters. The vibe feels like an extended episode of Whedon's Buffy the Vampire Slayer, with laughter used to lighten the genuine life and death stakes.Goddard and Whedon's script keeps you completely off balance, a rarity for any genre but horror movies in particular. It's so smart and cleverly aimed at our own perceived notions of where the story should go, that it's easy to overlook that some of the performances are actually quite good. The banter between Jenkins and Whitford, including a running gag involving the latter's love of a particular classic movie monster, make up the bulk of the movie's biggest laughs.Analyzing horror films has become old hat now, with that little sub-genre falling into self parody. Scream 4 is a prime example of what happens when the satire fails to evolve. Whedon is too smart to let that happen here, so hopefully we won't be seeing any The Cabin the Woods sequels. Don't let anybody spoil your experience, so get your tickets to the film early before the biggest shocks(including one awesome cameo!) get ruined!
summary: Puts most other horror movies to shame

reviewText: If you've ever watched a horror movie, you've seen characters headed for their doom after making an obvious mistake and asked yourself, `how could they be so stupid?' What if your job depended on that very stupidity? Better yet, what if the world as we knew it depended on that stupidity?Five college students, Dana (played by Kristen Connolly), Curt (played by Thor himself Chris Hemsworth), Jules (played by Anna Hutchison), Marty (played by Fran Kranz) and Holden (played by Grey's Anatomy's Jesse Williams) are all packed and ready for some much needed rest and relaxation in a remote cabin in the woods (I know, the title was no help in predicting that). Separately, two men in a corporate facility whose nature is not fully explained are gearing up for a series of operations taking place worldwide and one happening domestically that determines the future of their employment. While en route to their secluded cabin, our college students stop for gas and are more than moderately spooked by the station attendant who tells them that tragedies have befallen more than one of the previous owners. Still they press on and the attendant, Mordecai (played by Tim de Zarn) relays that to the two men in the corporate facility (played by Richard Jenkins and Bradley Whitford) while they laugh at the man's ghoulish demeanor which he maintains long after the collegians depart.There's a good deal more to this story, but to reveal any more would give away too much. What I can tell you is that I enjoyed this movie immensely. The relatively unknown cast members serve their purpose and the more accomplished professionals, namely Whitford, Jenkins, and a largely unseen Sigourney Weaver add an entirely different dimension to a film that might otherwise be cookie-cutter from its inception. If you enjoy horror or enjoy a good parody, you will enjoy The Cabin the Woods.

reviewText: [The following review contains minor spoilers.]Five young students travel to a remote cabin in the woods. Beneath this familiar horror template there is another story going on, about which you will learn by the end of "Cabin in the Woods," directed by Drew Goddard (his debut as director), who is also the writer of "Cloverfield." His debut film is pretty fun, but if you ask me if I want to watch it again, the answer is no.Like the POV-style monster flick, "Cabin in the Woods" is based on two or more incongruous ideas put together in a straightforward way. On one level it is a standard horror movie. On another it is a kind of conspiracy theory, which is pretty good, but nothing new. There is more to come, which will certainly make you speechless, either you are impressed with it, or you just find it too silly.After all, the ending could be anything. The problem of "Cabin in the Woods" is despite occasional humor and scare, the film is not as smart as it thinks it is. The whole setting is elaborate, but each segment is often predictable. The film shows its hand far too soon, signposting what will happen next (the flying bird scene, for instance).The acting is surprisingly good, with five principal young actors Kristen Connolly, Chris Hemsworth, Anna Hutchison, Fran Kranz and Jesse Williams, and two veterans Richard Jenkins and Bradley Whitford. With their solid performances and a few nice surprises, the film feels like a mystery novel you enjoy reading once, but will not take up again.

reviewText: The "plot" of THE CABIN IN THE WOODS is a classic cliché of horror films: a group of five friends travels to a cabin in the woods out in the middle of nowhere that is supposedly owned by a cousin of one of the friends. There's a jock, a slutty girl, a scholar, a stoner, and an innocent. The trip to the cabin is really spooky complete with a run-down gas station where the group stops for a fill-up and to make sure their directions to the cabin are correct. Once they get to the cabin in the woods, it's even creepier. However, from the opening sequence the audience already knows this isn't a typical horror movie because these five friends are under surveillance and everything about their trip seems predetermined. One can't really say more than that without giving important plot twists away.THE CABIN IN THE WOODS is unlike any horror movie I have seen before. There's a lot of humor in the film that reminds one of the horror films of Sam Raimi (the EVIL DEAD movies, and DRAG ME TO HELL). Also, from the beginning I was reminded of the John Ritter movie, STAY TUNED. THE CABIN IN THE WOODS has elements from these films, yet it is something completely different. It starts out following many of the clichés of the horror genre and then manipulates those clichés into something different. Then, when you think you've got things figured out, it takes that idea and manipulates it again, changing it into something completely different.The movie has broad appeal. There's tons of gore for those who like to see blood and guts. There's a flash of female nudity for the horny males. There's the secret mind game that seems to be going on for those who enjoy the mystery and suspense that often accompanies a horror story. There's the occasional cheap scare where something jumps up or pops out of nowhere. All of those elements are in THE CABIN IN THE WOODS. However, all of those elements are carefully manipulated to fit into the grand scheme of the movie that's a carefully constructed critique of the horror genre in general.Though THE CABIN IN THE WOODS is one of the best horror movies I've seen in years, it's not a movie that will appeal to everyone. Those who don't like horror films should stay away as well as anyone who is squeamish when seeing lots of blood. All kinds of people die in this movie and they die in ways you'd never expect. Beyond that, THE CABIN IN THE WOODS is the smartest (and in my opinion, best) horror movie to be released in years. I know the next time I visit a cabin in the woods, I'll be looking for the strings.

reviewText: I watched this movie twice over the weekend, so that pretty much says how much I liked it. I'm sorry - guts, gore, zombies, violent deaths - what is it, romantic comedy??Anyway, don't be swayed by the 1-star OR 5-star reviews. Check it out for yourself.

reviewText: This is a good popcorn movie. One to watch just for fun if you're willing to suspend any questions you may have about plot holes or things that don't seem to make too much sense. Just "enjoy the ride".The story revolves around 5 college friends who are getting away for a weekend in the woods at a cousin's cabin. Simple enough. He really gets in to his character and while the script isn't Shakespeare, really made the most of each line he had.There is the normal amount of blood and gore you might expect when teen agers/college students go off in the woods at night, but also some fresh twists.Humor is supplied by the "back ground" players, "puppet masters" who are orchestrating this play. Very funny - intentionally. And of course a tip of the cap to Sigourney Weaver who is worked in to the script as the "Director" of the operation - chosen no doubt for her association to Sci Fi as Ripley.Over all this was a fun movie that I'm likely to watch again in the future. Just don't try to tie up all the loose ends of the plot or ask too many questions about it, cause they don't all come together if you do.

reviewText: So, when the title flashes in big bold letters at start of film, you know it's a spoof on horror flicks. So, I invested an hour and a half on this film. I didn't know it was a slasher flick -my girlfriend rented it (shame on me for not checking, eh?) What did I get out of it? Some chuckles but not much more. The problem with this movie is, after the stupidity keeps on coming, it gets old and predictable. Even unpredictability becomes predictable and old. Understand? The absurdities from start to finish left this viewer not really caring at all. In fact, I was bored half way through and almost turned it off-wish I had. Don't get me wrong, I love a good parody,. but slashing up teenagers (or old actors- supposed to be young) and the violence for the sake of Joss saying "look, how blood loving our violent society is" does not help stop the spread of violence itself.The last 20 minutes of the film could have been written by a 10 year old, and have been equally believable to what Joss came up with. Don't look for any great philosophical point or moral to this flick-or logic/explanations; how did they capture all those monsters? Does society really allow killing teenagers for a hidden god?I wish Joss would have made the villain the people who profit from slasher flicks, like himself or Hollywood.Or maybe made the pot-geek the virgin who kills the girl instead and saves-nothing. But hey, the ending made no sense so it is all a joke. You can watch other similar films that make a mockery of slasher films, too.Oh, one more thing this film does have on it's side: because it is mocking horror flicks, it cannot be criticized for anything poorly done-at all. The defense is "well, don't slasher flicks have bad acting?" or "don't slasher flicks have stupid endings?" on and on. Don't start criticizing this films every mistake, cause most are probably intentional.But then again...oh, and many reviewers say the ending was unpredictable, I wasn't shocked or surprised. Very formulated through the end. Yes, I guessed the geek wasn't really dead and would return, on and on.So would YOU like it? Well, did you like Scary Movie? and Hunger Games? Like to see blood and people slaughtered? Go for it. But, not much scary stuff because Joss intentionally cuts back to control room for some tired, worn jokes/gimmicks. So, a good film for a short 1 1/2 hour joke. I don't think the film could have been any longer.I think the reviewers who enjoyed this movie are young. And I say that because they love anything that is sarcastic and breaks the norm, even if it is not well done or conceived. Hey, I was young once too! Our DNA dictates we break from the clan. What Joss did here was like other movies but goes one step further by making it even more absurd/unbelievable. Hope this helps.

reviewText: Blu-ray Review:Will you enjoy this? It's hard to say. Read below:Audiences often don't like films that shift genres, play with the conventions of the genre incorporating elements of multiple "types" of films or change the rules of the game while the movie is being watched. "Cabin in The Woods" does all three and whether or not you'll enjoy it largely will be determined by your enjoyment of films that do that very thing such asEvil Dead 2 (25th Anniversary Edition) [Blu-ray]orScream [Blu-ray]. In fact, if you enjoyed Whedon's seriesBuffy the Vampire Slayer: The Complete SeriesorSupernatural: The Complete Seventh Season [Blu-ray] then you'll probably enjoy this film.SPOILERS:With "Cabin in the Woods" Drew Goddard (a former writer on "Lost", "Buffy" and "Cloverfield) and Joss Whedon turn the horror conventions of the slasher flick on its head combining elements of H. P. Lovecraft, "The Truman Show" and "Scream" creating a sort of "meta" horror movie. Since the film also has elements of satire I wouldn't go into "Cabin in the Woods" expecting a straight horror experience as the film plays with the expectations of the genre as well. Those looking for a slasher film that will scare them scene after scene would do well to steer clear of this "Cabin". If you enjoyed "Buff The Vampire Slayer", you'll enjoy "Cabin". If you didn't, you probably won't enjoy this.A quintet of college kids head up to a deserted cabin that was recently purchased by the cousin of Curt(played by Chris Hemsworth ofThor (Two-Disc Blu-ray/DVD Combo + Digital Copy)). He drags along his girlfriend (Anna Hutchinson), teammate (Jessie Williams), Anna's roommate (Kristin Connolly) and their stoner friend Marty (Fran Kurtz)  and As the creepiness builds we discover that they are being watched, manipulated prior to being attacked and picked off by the resurrected corpses of the former inhabitants. Those in the control room (the Richard Jenkins ofThe Visitor [Blu-ray]who inhabits the banality of evil in his role here and Bradley Whitford ofThe West Wing: The Complete Series Collection) who are observing and guiding the fate of these four insuring they'll die horribly to prevent something evil from being released. Imagine "Evil Dead II" with a bit more satire and you'll have a sense of the feel of "Cabin in the Woods" is like.END OF SPOILERS:The Blu-ray for "Cabin in the Woods" is a bit disappointing. While it accurately represents what was seen in theaters, the lack of contrast unfortunately makes the darker sequences in the film a bit too murky. Yes, it represents the films that Whedon and Goddard are satirizing look like but I expected a slightly sharper presentation. The rest of the film looks pretty good but given that some of the key sequences occur at night, I would have liked slightly better resolution.The audio, on the other hand, is a knock out 5.1 lossless presentation. Dialogue is never overwhelmed by the various sound effects or the marvelous score by David JulyanThe Descent (Original Unrated Cut) [Blu-ray],The Prestige [Blu-ray]).The special features are quite solid and include a commentary track by Goddard and Whedon. We get a number of featurettes that are quite good "We Are Not Who We Are" about the making of the movie; "An Army of Nightmares" focuses on the animatronic/make up effects; "Primal Terror" focuses on the visual effects. We also get "The Secret Secret Stash" about Marty's pot stash. "Hi, My Name Is Joss and I'll Be Your Guide" features Whedon giving a guided tour of the sets for the show. We also get the "Wondercon Q & A" after the screening of the film. We also have "It's Not What You Think" a "Bonusview" special feature allowing you to see interviews and behind-the-scenes footage while watching the movie.Will "The Cabin in The Woods" be for everyone? No. I feel it's a clver mixture of satire and horror and enjoyed it quite a bit. Your mileage may vary though depending on your taste.

reviewText: The Cabin In The Woods sounds like and starts off as the typical campy horror story - a bunch of college kids get access to a cabin in the woods for a weekend and when there find spooky things.  Well it comes as a pleasant surprise when you find that the previous description is merely a lead-in to something far grander and more creative!  I don't wish to insert spoilers in here but suffice it to say that there is much more than meets the eye in this movie.. otherwise how could the hackneyed nighttime attack by a couple of zombies in a spooky cabin filled with college kids eventually lead to humanity's probable demise?  You'll have to watch it to find out.
summary: It's Nothing Like What You Think...

reviewText: WHAT A PLEASANT SURPRISE! I knew nothing about it when I clicked "Play Now" and the surreal crosscuts between your typical B-Movie teen-weekend-slasher and a beautifully realized high-tech uberHQ worthy of a Bond film immediately snagged my curiosity. As the disparate elements began to coalesce, the awesome cleverness of the storytellers began to reveal itself, by degrees. By the time you think it can't get better, the SPFX third-stage fires and the movie goes into orbit! Excelsior, the pinnacle has - no, it hasn't -- it immediately plunges into warp drive, slinging surprise after twisty surprise right to the bittersweet end! I'm definitely going to see it again, it's almost too much to absorb in one sitting. It's suspenseful and terrifying and sexy and hilarious and not just a little sardonic ...  no spoilers intended! (I see now Joss Whedon is in the mix ... that explains much!) A must see if you have no idea what to watch, you won't regret it!
summary: Better Than I COULD Have Expected ... GREAT Surprise!

reviewText: I would have passed on this film due to the title itself and it had always reminded me of how cliché horror movies being taken place in "the woods." But, seeing the image of an interesting cabin, rotating and in the air, on the cover prompt me to stand still and take a look. Then, I got to watching it and found myself in awe of its interesting plot, an overwhelming full of scary characters, a shocking twist, and my pre-notion of cliché just went out the dirty window. I actually said to myself at the end of this movie, "Well, you don't see that everyday."This film follows five "typical" young students who plans on spending their vocation in a cabin in the woods far, far away from the civilization. If one is aware of the "typical" plot of how these students will face, you would be right. However, there is another "story" observing these students and that is scary in itself. When these two "stories" collide, all hell broke loose...literally.It sure makes one think about all the horror films being made to "satisfy" the audience, so to speak. This film is absorbing to watch with great actors.

reviewText: This is a parody of any horror movie. The special effects are really well done and the acting is really good, but at no point in the movie we believe the plot (because there is no real plot). And the end while totally predictable is totally out of control.The "plot": five friends go to spend a week end in a cabin in the woods next to their college campus; they discover in the basement a journal that has one sentence in Latin; the "virgin" reads it and then all hell breaks loose; they do not realize until the end that everything is orchestrated by a corporation that competes globally. They finally make it inside the headquarters and release all the creatures that kill all the employees.The best line comes from Sigourney Weaver that unfortunately we only see for 2 minutes at the end of the movie. While she is introducing the five stereotypes of any horror movies (the athlete, the hooker, the geek, the drug addict, and the virgin) she looks at the "virgin", and the "virgin" goes: me a virgin? Then Sigourney Weaver gives her THE answer: we work with what we have!!!At no point in the movie we are scared nor we care for any of the characters.Two stars only for the special effects but this movie has no real plot and no purpose!
summary: Average movie because there is no real plot!

reviewText: I did enjoy watching this movie but, it left a lot to be desired. You can't take a B-Movie theme & make an A-Movie out of it. The comedy was really dry with a few hahas but, mostly huhs. The premise was sexy college kids going out to the woods to party instead, they were mostly nerdy kids with little sexiness & very limited drug use (sex & drugs are the reason they're supposed to die). The scene in the beginning with the alleged virgin in her underwear that did show her southern details a little & the one sex scene in the woods with a little top-free action was the limit of the sexiness in this film (movies like this should be chock full of T&A!! Especially in these progressive times). I really didn't like the fact that they only sent one monster type after the kids. A wild night of survival would've been a lot better than wham bam everybody's dead except this one person. Also, having them killing to keep some gods from destroying the Earth seemed kind of stupid. They should've been doing it to fulfill some sick individuals fantasy instead. It did have a lot of blood but, no real memorable deaths. It had jokes but, very few laughs. It also had nudity but, it lasted less than two minutes. This movie just lacked excitement all together. I'm really surprised Chris Hemsworth agreed to do this film as it really knocked him down a peg in my book. It was enjoyable but, it just didn't deliver.
summary: Nothing new, original or much interesting....
